{"title_page": "Khas people", "text_new": "{{About|medieval and modern day Khas people|ancient Indo-Iranian group of same name|Khasas|medieval kingdom|Khasa Malla kingdom|native language of Khas people|Khas language}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group        = Khas/Khasia/Kus/Parbate/Pahari/Gorkhali\n|native_name  = \u0916\u0938/\u0916\u0938\u093f\u092f\u093e/\u092a\u0930\u094d\u0935\u0924\u0947/\u092a\u0939\u093e\u0921\u0940/\u0917\u094b\u0930\u094d\u0916\u093e\u0932\u0940 \n|image        = <!-- See WP:NOETHNICGALLERIES -->\n|caption      =  \n|population   = '''{{Circa|16 million|lk=yes}}'''<ref name=ethnologue1>{{cite web|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/18/language/npi/|title=Nepali (npi)|work=Ethnologue|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref>\n|region1      = {{flag|Nepal}}\n|pop1         =\n|ref1         =\n|region2      = {{flag|India}}\n|pop2         =\n|ref2         =\n|languages    =[[Khas language]] and regional dialects (e.g. [[Doteli language]]) \n|rels  = Mostly  [[Hinduism]], [[Buddhism]]\n|related      = [[Kumaoni people]], [[Garhwali people]], [[Dogra]], [[Magar people|Magar]], [[Pahari people]] and [[Indo-Aryan peoples|other Indo-Aryan peoples]]\n|footnotes    = \n}}\n'''Khas people''' ({{lang-ne|\u0916\u0938}}) also called '''Khas Arya'''{{#tag:ref|See<ref name=\"Khadka\">{{Cite news|last=Khadka|first =Suman |URL=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2015-02-25/drawing-caste-lines.html|title= Drawing caste lines|date=25 Feb 2015|newspaper= [[The Kathmandu Post]]|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"thehimalayantimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/khas-arya-quota-provision-civil-services-opposed/|title=Khas Arya quota provision in civil services opposed|author=|date=10 November 2017|website=thehimalayantimes.com|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21731658-good-government-might-be-too-much-hope-nepals-election-may-last-bring-stability|title=Nepal\u2019s election may at last bring stability|author=|date=|website=The Economist|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/ampnews/2018-03-28/pm-briefs-international-community.html|title=The Kathmandu Post -PM briefs international community|author=|date=|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/from-the-nepali-press/quotable-quota/|title=Quotable quota|first=Nepali|last=Times|date=|website=www.nepalitimes.com|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/kp-oli-swearing-in-ceremony-nepal-elections-5119820/|title=Next Door Nepal: Another chink in the wall|author=|date=2 April 2018|website=indianexpress.com|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/39123/?categoryId=81|title=Oli in balancing avatar|author=|date=|website=myrepublica.com|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Nepal-seeks-unity-from-its-first-local-elections-in-20-years|title=Nepal seeks unity from its first local elections in 20 years|author=|date=|website=Nikkei Asian Review|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thewire.in/politics/lessons-for-india-from-nepal-history-of-cow-slaughter|title=Lessons for India From Nepal's History of Banning Cow Slaughter - The Wire|author=|date=|website=The Wire|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2018-04-07/what-does-high-caste-chauvinism-look-like.html|title=What does high caste chauvinism look like?|author=|date=|website=ekantipur.com|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref>|name=\"khas arya\"|group=\"nb\"}} ({{lang-ne|\u0916\u0938 \u0906\u0930\u094d\u092f}}) are an [[Indo-Aryan peoples|Indo-Aryan]]{{sfn|Hagen|Thapa|1998|p=114}} [[ethno-linguistic group]] native to the [[Indian subcontinent]], what is now present-day [[Nepal]] and [[Indian states]] of [[Uttarakhand]] ([[Kumaon division|Kumaon]]-[[Garhwal division|Garhwal]]), [[Himachal Pradesh]] and [[Jammu and Kashmir]]. The Khas people speak the [[Khas language]]. They are also known as '''Parbatiyas''', '''Parbates''' and '''Paharis/Pahades'''.or '''Gorkhali''' The term ''Khas'' has now become obsolete, as the Khas people have adopted communal identities such as [[Bahun]] and [[Chhetri]] because of the negative stereotypes associated with the term ''Khas''.{{sfn|William Brook Northey|C. J. Morris|1928|p=123}}{{sfn|K. S. Singh|2005|p=851}}{{sfn|Dor Bahadur Bista|1991|p=48}}\n\nAlthough the term \"Khas\" has gained popularity in Nepali identity politics since the 1990s, many castes currently categorized as Khas may not identify themselves as Khas.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} According to the [[Constitution of Nepal]], [[Bahun|Brahmins]], [[Chhetri|Chhetris]], [[Thakuri|Thakuris]], and [[Sannyasa|Sanyasis]] who are citizens of Nepal should be considered as Khas Arya for electoral puposes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lawcommission.gov.np/en/archives/888|title=Part-8 Federal Legislature \u2013 Nepal Law Commission|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nThey have been connected to the [[Khasas]] mentioned in the ancient Hindu literature.{{sfn|John T Hitchcock|1978|pp=112-119}} Historian Bal Krishna Sharma and [[Dor Bahadur Bista]] speculates that the Khas or kus people were of [[Indo-Aryan migrations|Indo-Aryan origin]].{{sfn|Sharma|1999|p=181}}{{sfn|Dor Bahadur Bista|1991|p=47}} Historian [[Baburam Acharya]] speculates that Khas are a sub-clan of ''Ai\u1e0da'', an [[Indo-Iranian people|Arya]] clan originated at Idavritt (modern day [[Kashmir]]).{{sfn|Acharya|1975|p=199}}{{#tag:ref|Historian [[Baburam Acharya]] speculates that in the 3rd millennium BCE., there were two clans of '''[[Aryan|Arya]]''' in the northern [[Indian subcontinent]]; ''Ai\u1e0da'' and ''M\u0101nava''. ''Ai\u1e0da'' who were named after their homeland ''I\u1e0davritt'' (modern day [[Kashmir]]), settled over [[Panjab]] and [[Gangetic plain|Ganga-Jamuna plain]] while ''M\u0101nava'' settled over [[Awadh]] region. [[Chandravanshi]] kings like [[Bharata (Mahabharata)|Bharata]] and [[Yudhisthir]] belonged to ''Ai\u1e0da'' while [[Suryavansha|Suryavanshi]] kings like [[Ramachandra]] belonged to ''M\u0101nava''. Later, ''Ai\u1e0da'' built dominion over [[Magadh]] while ''M\u0101nava'' had dominion over [[Videha]].{{sfn|Acharya|1975|p=199}}|name=\"arya clan\"|group=\"nb\"}} Khas were living in the ''Idavaritt'' in the 3rd millennium BCE. and the original meaning of the term ''Khas'' was [[Raja]] or [[Kshatriya]] (''Yoddha'').{{sfn|Acharya|1975|p=199}} He further speculates that Kashmir has been named from its local residents Khas as '''Khasmir'''.{{sfn|Acharya|1975|p=199}} In the 2nd millennium B.C.E., one group of Khas migrated towards [[Iran]] while the other group migrated east of [[Sutlej river]] settling only in the hill regions up to [[Bheri River]].{{sfn|Acharya|1975|p=200}} Historian Balkrishna Pokhrel contends that Khas were not the [[Vedic Aryan]]s but [[Aryan]]s of latter period like the [[Gurjara]], [[Darada]], [[Saka|Shaka]], and [[Pallava]].{{sfn|Pokhrel|1973|p=229}} He further asserts that post-Vedic Aryans were akin to Vedic Aryans in terms of [[Indo-Aryan languages]] and [[Indian culture]].{{sfn|Pokhrel|1973|p=229}}\n\n== History ==\nKhas are believed to have arrived in the western reaches of Nepal at the beginning of first-millennium B.C.{{sfn|Dor Bahadur Bista|1991|p=15}} or middle of first-millennium A.D.{{sfn|Sharma|1999|p=112}} from the north-west. It is likely that they absorbed people from different ethnic groups during this immigration.{{sfn|John T Hitchcock|1978|p=113}} They have been connected to the medieval [[Khasa Malla kingdom]].{{sfn|John T Hitchcock|1978|pp=112-119}} In the initial phase, majority of Khas people became [[Brahmin]]s and others became [[Kshatriya]]s.{{sfn|Sharma|1999|p=112}}\n\nTraditionally, the Khas were divided into \"Khas [[Brahmin]]s\" (also called [[Bahun]]s) and \"Khas [[Rajput]]s\" (also called [[Chhetri]]s). In the [[Kumaon division|Kumaon]] and [[Garhwal division|Garhwal]] regions of Uttarakhand in India, the Khas Brahmins and Khas Rajputs had a lower social status than the other Brahmins and Rajputs. However, in present-day western Nepal, they had the same status as the other Brahmins and Rajputs, possibly as a result of their political power in the Khasa Malla kingdom.{{sfn|John T Hitchcock|1978|pp=116-119}} \n\n[[File:Mandhata Shahi- SAKE-1612.jpg|thumb|Copper Inscription by King of [[Doti]], ''Raika'' Mandhata Shahi at [[Saka Era]] 1612 (\u0936\u093e\u0915\u0947 \u0967\u096c\u0967\u0968) (or 1747 [[Bikram Samvat]]) in old [[Khas language]] using [[Devanagari]] script]]\nUntil the 19th century, the [[Gorkha Kingdom|Gorkhali]] referred to their country as ''Khas Desh'' (Khas country).{{sfn|Richard Burghart|1984|p=107}} As they annexed the various neighbouring countries (such as Newar of the [[Newar people]]) to the Gorkha kingdom, the terms such as ''Khas'' and ''Newar'' ceased to be used as the names of countries. The 1854 legal code (''Muluki Ain''), promulgated by the Nepali Prime Minister [[Jung Bahadur Rana]], himself a Khas,{{sfn|Dor Bahadur Bista|1991|p=37}} no longer referred to ''Khas'' as a country, rather as a ''[[j\u0101ti|j\u0101t]]'' (species or community) within the Gorkha kingdom.{{sfn|Richard Burghart|1984|p=117}}\n\nThe [[Shah dynasty]] of the Gorkha Kingdom, as well as the succeeding [[Rana dynasty]], spoke the [[Khas language]] (now called the Nepali language). However, they claimed to be Rajputs of western Indian origin, rather than the native Khas Kshatriyas.{{sfn|Richard Burghart|1984|p=119}} Since outside Nepal, the Khas social status was seen as inferior to that of the Rajputs, the rulers started describing themselves as natives of the Hill country, rather than that of the Khas country. Most people, however, considered the terms ''Khas'' and ''Parbatiya'' (''Pahari/Pahadi'' or [[Hill tribes of Northeast India|Hill people]]) as synonymous.{{sfn|Richard Burghart|1984|p=107}}\n\nJung Bahadur also re-labeled the Khas ''j\u0101t'' as [[Chhetri]] in present-day Nepal.{{sfn|Richard Burghart|1984|p=119}} Originally, the [[Brahmin]] immigrants from the [[Gangetic plain|plains]] considered the Khas as low-caste because of the latter's neglect of high-caste taboos (such as alcohol abstinence).{{sfn|Susan Thieme|2006|p=83}} The upper-class Khas people commissioned the [[Bahun]] (Brahmin) priests to initiate them into the high-caste Chhetri order and adopted high-caste manners. Other Khas families who could not afford to (or did not care to) pay the Bahun priests also attempted to assume the Chhetri status but were not recognized as such by others. They are now called Matwali (alcohol-drinking) Chhetris.{{sfn|Dor Bahadur Bista|1991|p=48}}\n\nBecause of the adoption of the ''Chhetri'' identity, the term ''Khas'' is rapidly becoming obsolete.{{sfn|William Brook Northey|C. J. Morris|1928|p=123}} According to [[Dor Bahadur Bista]] (1991), \"the Khas have vanished from the ethnographic map of Nepal\".{{sfn|Dor Bahadur Bista|1991|p=48}}\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Khas women 1880.jpg|Khas women, photographed in 1880\nFile:Bhimsen_Thapa_of_Nepal (cropped).jpg|[[Mukhtiyar]] [[Bhimsen Thapa]], the widely accepted first Prime Minister of Nepal \nFile:Major Indo-Aryan languages.png|[[Khas language]], Belongs to the north Indo-Aryan Hill group as shown as ''Nepali'', in purple\n</gallery>\n\n==Communities==\nHistorian Balkrishna Pokhrel writes the communities or caste in Khas group were [[Bahun|Brahman]], [[Chhetri]], [[Gharti]], [[Damai]], [[Kami (caste)|Kami]], [[Sarki (ethnic group)|Sarki]], Hudka, Tamote, [[Gandarbha|Gaine]], [[Badi people|Badi]], etc.{{sfn|Pokhrel|1973|p=229}} The tribal designation Khas refers to in some contexts only to the upper-class Khas group, i.e. [[Bahun]] and [[Chhetri]], but in other contexts may also include the low status (generally untouchable) occupational Khas groups such as [[Kami (caste)|K\u0101mi]] (blacksmiths), [[Damai|Dam\u0101i]] (tailors), and [[Sarki (ethnic group)|S\u0101rki]] (shoemakers and leather workers).{{sfn|Whelpton|2005|p=31}} Khas people are addressed with the term ''Khayan'' or ''Parbatiya''{{sfn|Pokhrel|1973|p=229}} or ''Party\u0101'', ''Parbat\u00e9'' meaning hill-dweller by [[Newar]]s.{{sfn|Whelpton|2005|p=31}} The hill Khas tribe are in large part associated with the [[Gurkha|Gorkhali]] warriors.{{sfn|Whelpton|2005|p=31}}\n\n==Language==\n\n===History===\nThe Khas people originally referred to their language as ''[[Khas language|Khas kur\u0101]]'' (Khas speech), which was also known as ''Parbatiya'' (the language of the hill country). The Newar people used the term ''Khayan Bhaya'', ''Parbatiya''{{sfn|Pokhrel|1973|p=229}} and ''Gorkhali'' as a name for this language, as they identified it with the Gorkhali conquerors. The Gorkhalis themselves started using this term to refer to their language at a later stage.{{sfn|Richard Burghart|1984|p=118}} In an attempt to disassociate himself with his Khas past, the Rana monarch Jung Bahadur decreed that the term Gorkhali be used instead of ''Khas kur\u0101'' to describe the language. Meanwhile, the [[British India]]n administrators had started using the term ''Nepal'' (after Newar) to refer to the Gorkha kingdom. In the 1930s, the Gorkha government also adopted this term to describe their country. Subsequently, the Khas language also came to be known as ''Nepali language''.{{sfn|Richard Burghart|1984|pp=118-119}} It has become a national language of Nepal and [[lingua franca]] among the majority of population of [[North Bengal]], [[Sikkim]] and [[Bhutan]].{{sfn|Pokhrel|1973|p=229}}\n\n===Classification===\nHistorian Balkrishna Pokhrel contends that the [[Khas language]] belonged to neither the [[Iranian languages]] nor the [[Languages of India|Indian languages]], but to the mid [[Indo-Iranian languages]].{{sfn|Pokhrel|1973|p=229}}\n\n==Modern==\n\n===Nepal===\nModern-day Khas people are referred to as Khas Brahmin (commonly called as Khas [[Bahun]]), Khas Rajput (commonly called as Khas [[Chhetri]]) and Khas Dalit.{{sfn|John T Hitchcock|1978|pp=116-119}} Khas people are popularly referred in modern times as ''Khas Arya''.\n\n===India===\nIn [[Kumaon District|Kumaon]] and [[Garhwal District|Garhwal]] regions of [[Uttarakhand]] in India, too, the term ''Khas'' has become obsolete. The Khas (or Khasia) people of Kumaon adopted the self-designation Kumaoni Jiagahari Rajput, after being elevated to the Rajput status by the [[Chand kings]]. The term Khas is almost obsolete, and people resent being addressed as Khas because of the negative stereotypes associated with this term.{{sfn|K. S. Singh|2005|p=851}}\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Khas Malla rulers===\n*[[Khasa Malla kingdom|Khas Malla rulers]]\n\n===Other Khas===\n*[[Bir Bhadra Thapa]]{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=22}}\n*[[Amar Singh Thapa (Sardar)|Sanukaji Amar Singh Thapa]]{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=22}}\n*[[Bhimsen Thapa]]{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=22}} \n*[[Jung Bahadur Rana]]{{sfn|Dor Bahadur Bista|1991|p=37}}\n*[[Kalu Pande]] (Kaji) {{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=22}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{ref begin}}\n*{{citation | last = Acharya| first = Baburam | editor-last = Bhandari| editor-first = Devi Prasad | title = Itihas Kaalbhanda Pahile | journal = Purnima | volume = 8| issue = 1| pages = | location = Kathmandu | date = 1975 | url = http://himalaya.socanth.cam.ac.uk/collections/journals/purnima/pdf/Purnima_08_04.pdf| accessdate = }}\n* {{cite book |author=Dor Bahadur Bista |author-link=Dor Bahadur Bista |title=Fatalism and Development: Nepal's Struggle for Modernization |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JzFROpFVYRAC&pg=PA48 |year=1991 |publisher=Orient Blackswan |isbn=978-81-250-0188-1 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |a