 wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Al-Amin Hossain]] 3/85 (22.4 overs)\n\n| score-team1-inns2 = 195 (41.1 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Mushfiqur Rahim]] 74 (96)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Umesh Yadav]] 5/53 (14.1 overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns2 = \n| runs-team2-inns2 = \n| wickets-team2-inns2 = \n\n| result = India won by an innings and 46 runs\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1187017.html Scorecard]\n| umpires = [[Marais Erasmus]] (SA) and [[Joel Wilson (umpire)|Joel Wilson]] (WI)\n| motm = [[Ishant Sharma]] (Ind)\n| toss = Bangladesh won the toss and elected to bat.\n| rain = \n| notes =\n}}\n\n==Notable events==\n[[File:Day night test at Eden gardens.jpeg|thumb|330px|Day 1, India's first ever Day/night test match, held at Eden Garden]] \n[[File:Eden gardens manual scoreboard.jpg|thumb|Eden Gardens Manual Scoreboard]]\n[[File:Eden Gardens Block Map.jpg|thumb|Eden Gardens Block Map]]\n* In 1946, an in-form [[Mushtaq Ali]] was dropped from the Indian team selected to play an unofficial test against [[Australian Services XI]]. Following crowd protests (with slogans like \"No Mushtaq, No Test\"), the selectors brought him back to play.<ref name=Mushtaq_Ali>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/cricket/2001/dec/17mush.htm |title=Unfortunately, they don't look for talent today: The Rediff Interview with Mushtaq Ali |publisher=Rediff.com |date=17 December 2001 |accessdate=12 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111201100352/http://www.rediff.com/cricket/2001/dec/17mush.htm |archive-date=1 December 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Rioting occurred at the ground during the 1966/67 West Indies and 1969/70 Australian tours.<ref name=\"cric\" />\n* In 1977, [[New York Cosmos (1970\u201385)|New York Cosmos]] played a Football match against [[Mohun Bagan]] at the stadium. [[Pel\u00e9]] played in that match for the Cosmos. The match was drawn at 2\u20132.\n* 16 football fans died in a stampede after a derby league game between East Bengal and Mohun Bagan on 16 August 1980.\n* Hosted [[Nehru Cup]] in [[1984 Nehru Cup|1984]], where [[India national football team]] played against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], [[Poland national football team|Poland]], [[China national football team|China PR]], [[Romania national under-21 football team|Romania U-21]] and [[Vasas Budapest]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Nehru Cup 1984 - Match Details |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesn/nehru84det.html |website=www.rsssf.com |publisher=RSSSF |accessdate=16 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116143112/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesn/nehru84det.html |archive-date=16 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Eden Gardens hosted the [[1987 Cricket World Cup Final]] which was first ever [[Cricket World Cup]] final hosted outside England. The match ended with Australia defeating England by 7 runs. This was first time Australia won the [[List of Cricket World Cup finals|Cricket World Cup Final]].\n* The 1996 World Cup semi-final was called off and Sri Lanka awarded the match after crowd disturbances following an Indian batting collapse.<ref name=\"cric\" />\n* During the 2nd final of the [[1997 Pepsi Independence Cup]], the Test and ODI captains of the Indian cricket team of all time (with a few notable exceptions) were given a lap of honour around the stadium.\n* In 1999, leading Indian batsman [[Sachin Tendulkar]] was [[run out]] after colliding with Pakistan's [[Shoaib Akhtar]]. Akhtar had impeded Tendulkar and the crowd rioted, forcing the police to evict the spectators. The match continued in front of an empty stadium.\n* [[Kapil Dev]] took an ODI hat-trick against the Sri Lankans in 1991 at the ground.\n* [[Harbhajan Singh]] took a hat-trick against [[Australian cricket team|Australia]] in 2000/01 at the ground. He became the first Indian to take a hat-trick in Test cricket.\n*In 2000/01, [[V.V.S. Laxman]] scored 281 against [[Australian cricket team|Australia]] in the [[Second Test, 2000\u201301 Border\u2013Gavaskar Trophy]]. This remains the highest score at the ground. He was involved in a memorable 376 runs partnership with [[Rahul Dravid]] who scored 180. They batted through the whole Day 4 of the test match without losing their wickets. Australia were defeated despite enforcing India to follow-on. It was only the third time in Test history that a team had won after being forced to [[follow on]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63920.html |title=Border-Gavaskar Trophy \u2013 2nd Test |publisher=Cricinfo |access-date=19 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623123925/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63920.html |archive-date=23 June 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is widely considered to be one of the greatest Test matches in cricket history.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/sports_talk/1224298.stm | work=BBC News | title=The greatest Test ever? | date=16 March 2001 | access-date=6 October 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117005702/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/sports_talk/1224298.stm | archive-date=17 November 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n*In 2005, in an ODI against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]], Eden Gardens crowd booed the [[India national cricket team|Indian team]] and [[Greg Chappell]] because of [[Sourav Ganguly]]'s dropping from the team. Chappell allegedly showed middle finger to the crowd. \n*In 2005,Sachin Tendulkar scored his 10,000th run in Test Cricket against Pakistan on this ground making him the second Indian batsman and fifth overall to achieve this feat.\n* Eden Gardens hosted the historic 199th (penultimate) Test match of [[Sachin Tendulkar]]'s career against West Indies from 6-10 Nov 2013. India defeated West Indies by an innings and 51 runs in 3 days.\n* On its 150th anniversary, on 13 November 2014, Eden Gardens witnessed the highest ever score by a batsman in One Day Internationals, a 264 off 173 balls scored by [[Rohit Sharma]] during the 4th One Day International of Sri Lanka vs India at the venue.\n*On 3 April 2016, in this venue, within a span of hours, the finals of the ICC world cup Twenty20 tournaments for the [[2016 ICC Women's World Twenty20 Final|women]] and for the [[2016 ICC World Twenty20 Final|men]] were won by the respective [[West Indies women's cricket team|women's]] and [[West Indies cricket team|men's]] teams of the West Indies.\n*The stadium hosted the 200th and 250th home tests for India in 2005 and 2016 respectively.\n* On January 22, 2017, [[Ravindra Jadeja]] became the first Indian left arm spinner to take 150 One Day International wickets, when he dismissed [[Sam Billings]].\n*On September 21, 2017, [[Kuldeep Yadav]] became the third bowler for India to take a hat-trick in an ODI after [[Chetan Sharma]] and [[Kapil Dev]]. When he took a hat-trick against Australia.\n*On November 22, 2019, India's first ever [[Day/night cricket|Day/Night test match]] [[Bangladeshi cricket team in India in 2019\u201320#2nd Test|between India and Bangladesh]] was hosted at Eden Gardens.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1498140 |title=Bangladesh brace for another historic first against India |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Stats and Records==\n===Matches Hosted===\n({{small| as on 5 November 2019}})\n* [[Test cricket|Test]] \u2014 41\n* [[One Day International|ODI]] \u2014 30\n* [[Twenty20 International|T20I]] \u2014 7\n\n===Records===\n* The most runs in Test Matches played here are scored by [[V.V.S. Laxman]] (1217 runs),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/|title=Live cricket scores, commentary, match coverage - Cricket news, statistics - ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo|access-date=11 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113014130/http://www.espncricinfo.com/|archive-date=13 January 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> followed by [[Rahul Dravid]] (962 runs) and [[Sachin Tendulkar]] (872 runs). The most wickets taken here was by [[Harbhajan Singh]] (46 wickets) followed by [[Anil Kumble]] (40 wickets) and [[Bishen Singh Bedi]] (29 wickets).\n* The most runs in ODIs scored here by a batsman is by [[Sachin Tendulkar]] (496 runs), followed by [[Mohammed Azharuddin]] (332 runs) and [[Virat Kohli]] (326 runs). The most wickets taken here is by [[Anil Kumble]] and [[Kapil Dev]] (14 wickets each), followed by [[Ravindra Jadeja]] (9 wickets).\n* [[VVS Laxman]] and [[Mohammed Azharuddin]] have scored 5 centuries each at this venue.\n* The highest ever ODI individual score of 264 is made by [[Rohit Sharma]] on this ground against Sri Lanka in 2014.\n*On September 21, 2017, [[Kuldeep Yadav]] became the third bowler for India to take a hat-trick in an ODI after [[Chetan Sharma]] and [[Kapil Dev]]. When he took a hat trick  against Australia.\n*The highest runs scored ever in IPL at Eden Gardens was scored on 28 April 2019. The score was scored by Kolkata Knight Riders against Mumbai Indians. The score was 232/2. MI Scored 198/7 After Hardik Pandya Scored 91(34) Deliveries handing KKR its 100th T20 win.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" !colspan=4|Eden Gardens Records\n|-\n! style=\"width:200px;\"| Category !! style=\"width:400px;\"|Test Matches !! style=\"width:400px;\"|ODI Matches !! style=\"width:400px;\"|T20I Matches\n|-\n! scope=row| Highest Inning Score\n|| '''657/d'''  - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|AUS}} (2001)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/ground/57980.html?class=1;filter=advanced;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=aggregate;view=innings|title=Eden Gardens Test Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223103947/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/ground/57980.html?class=1;filter=advanced;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=aggregate;view=innings|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''404/5''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|SRI}} (2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=2;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=team;view=innings|title=Eden Gardens ODI Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223104017/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=2;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=team;view=innings|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''201/5'''  - {{cr|PAK}} vs {{cr|BAN}} (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/ground/57980.html?class=3;filter=advanced;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=aggregate;view=innings|title=Eden Gardens T20I Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225040530/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/ground/57980.html?class=3;filter=advanced;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=aggregate;view=innings|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=row| Lowest Inning Score\n|| '''90''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|WIN}} (1983)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=1;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings;wicketsmin1=10;wicketsval1=wickets|title=Eden Gardens Test Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223103135/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=1;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings;wicketsmin1=10;wicketsval1=wickets|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''120/8''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|SRI}} (1996)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=2;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings;wicketsmin1=10;wicketsval1=wickets|title=Statistics / Statsguru / ODI matches / Team records / Eden Gardens / Team score|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223103501/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=2;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings;wicketsmin1=10;wicketsval1=wickets|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''70''' - {{cr|BAN}} vs {{cr|NZL}} (2016)<ref name=\"T20i large victory\"/>\n|-\n! scope=row| Largest Victory - By Innings\n|| '''Innings & 336 runs'''  - {{cr|WIN}} vs {{cr|IND}} (1983)<ref name=\"test large victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/largest_margins.html?class=1;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens Test Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035855/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/largest_margins.html?class=1;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || {{n/a}} || {{n/a}}\n|-\n! scope=row| Largest Victory - By Runs\n|| '''329 runs'''  - {{cr|SA}} vs {{cr|IND}} (1996)<ref name=\"test large victory\" /> \n|| '''161 runs''' - {{cr|ZIM}} vs {{cr|KEN}} (2011)<ref name=\"ODI large victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/largest_margins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens ODI Record|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035536/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/largest_margins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''75 runs''' - {{cr|NZ}} vs {{cr|BAN}} (2016)<ref name=\"T20i large victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=3;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings|title=Eden Gardens T20I Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035637/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=3;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=row| Largest Victory - By Wickets\n|| '''10 Wickets''' - {{cr|AUS}} vs {{cr|IND}} (1969)<ref name=\"test large victory\" /> \n|| '''10 Wickets''' - {{cr|SA}} vs {{cr|IND}} (2005)<ref name=\"ODI large victory\" /> \n|| '''6 Wickets''' - {{cr|ENG}} vs {{cr|IND}} (2011) and {{cr|SRI}} vs {{cr|AFG}} (2016)<ref name = \"T20i large victory\" />\n|-\n! scope=row| Largest Victory - By Balls Remaining\n| {{n/a}} \n|| '''90 balls''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|KEN}} (1998)<ref name=\"ODI large victory\" /> \n|| '''13 balls''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|PAK}} (2016)<ref name =\"T20i large victory\" />\n|-\n! scope=row| '''Narrowest Victory - By Runs'''\n|| '''28 runs'''  - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|ENG}} (1972)<ref name=\"test narrow victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=1;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens ODI Record|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035544/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=1;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''2 runs''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|RSA}} (1993)<ref name=\"ODI narrow victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens ODI Record|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035902/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''55 runs''' - {{cr|PAK}} vs {{cr|BAN}} (2016)<ref name=\"T20i narrow victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=3;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens T20I Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225040628/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=3;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=row| '''Narrowest Victory - By Wickets''' \n|| '''7 Wickets''' - {{cr|ENG}} vs {{cr|IND}} (2012)<ref name=\"test narrow victory\" /> \n|| '''2 Wickets''' - {{cr|PAK}} vs {{cr|IND}} (1987)<ref name=\"ODI narrow victory\" /> \n|| '''4 Wickets''' - {{cr|WIN}} vs {{cr|ENG}} (2016)<ref name = \"T20i narrow victory\" />\n|-\n! scope=row| '''Narrowest Victory - By Balls Remaining'''\n| {{n/a}} \n|| '''1 ball''' - {{cr|PAK}} vs {{cr|WIN}} (1989)<ref name=\"ODI narrow victory\" /> \n|| '''2 ball''' - {{cr|WIN}} vs {{cr|ENG}} (2016)<ref name =\"T20i narrow victory\" />\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of international cricket centuries at Eden Gardens]]\n* [[List of international cricket five-wicket hauls at Eden Gardens]]\n* [[List of stadiums by capacity]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage-inline|Kolkata/Maidan}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110207010720/http://worldcup2011schedule.com/eden-gardens-cricket-stadium-kolkata-india/  Eden Gardens Cricket Stadium Kolkata, India] \u2013 Eden Gardens Cricket Stadium Seating Layout\n* [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/14/949.html CricketArchive statistics for Eden gardens]\n* [http://www.kolkatabengalinfo.com/2012/01/kkr-ipl-5-eden-gardens-kolkata-matches.html  IPL-5 Matches at Eden Gardens] \u2013 IPL 2012 Matches at Eden Gardens\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{S-start-collapsible|header={{S-sta|et}}}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = [[Cricket World Cup]]<br>Final Venue\n | before = [[Lord's]]\n | after = [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]<!-- [[1992 Cricket World Cup]] -->\n | years = [[1987 Cricket World Cup|1987]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = [[ICC World Twenty20]]<br>Final Venue\n | before = [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium|Sher-e-Bangla]]\n | after = [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]<!-- [[2020 ICC World Twenty20]] -->\n | years = [[2016 ICC World Twenty20|2016]]\n}}\n{{End}}\n\n{{Test cricket grounds in India}}\n{{Kolkata topics}}\n{{Indian Premier League}}\n{{Football stadiums in India}}\n}}\n[[Category:Test cricket grounds in India]]\n[[Category:National stadiums|India]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1864]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:Cricket grounds in West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Football venues in West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Cricket in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:1987 Cricket World Cup stadiums]]\n[[Category:1996 Cricket World Cup stadiums]]\n[[Category:2011 Cricket World Cup stadiums]]\n", "name_user": "Soooji", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix spelling mistake", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eden_Gardens"}
{"title_page": "Tom Moore (fundraiser)", "text_new": "{{short description|British Army Officer and fundraiser}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n| name               = Tom Moore\n| image              = Tom Moore (soldier).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Moore during his military service\n| birth_name         = Thomas Moore\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Keighley]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = British\n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma mater         = \n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Army officer\n* Managing director \n}}\n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| known for          = {{Plainlist|\n* Second World War veteran\n* 2020 fundraising walk\n}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Keighley Grammar School]], West Yorkshire\n| boards             = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = 2\n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| website            = {{URL|https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs|tomswalkforthenhs}}\n| module = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n   | allegiance  = {{GBR}}\n   |branch       = {{flagicon image|Flag of the British Army (1938-present).png}} [[British Army]]\n   |serviceyears = 1939\u20131946\n   |rank         = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n   |unit         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]]\n* [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n* [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n}}\n   |commands     = \n   |battles           = {{tree list}}\n*[[World War II|Second World War]]\n**[[Burma campaign 1944\u201345|Burma Campaign]]\n***[[Battle of Ramree Island]]\n   |awards = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Thomas Moore''' (born 30 April 1920), known as '''Captain Tom''', is a former [[British Army]] officer, best known for his philanthropic work. Moore served in India and in the [[Burma campaign]] during the [[Second World War]]. He later became an instructor in [[armoured warfare]]. After the war, he worked as a managing director of a concrete company. He also raced motorcycles. On 6 April 2020, at the age of 99, he began to walk around his garden in aid of [[NHS Charities Together]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]], with the goal of raising \u00a31,000 by his hundredth birthday on 30 April. By 18 April he had raised over \u00a323<!-- please update the figure in two places, and the date/timestamp -->&nbsp;million, and a further \u00a34.27 million in [[Gift Aid]].\n\n==Early life and family==\n\nMoore was born to Wilfred, one of a family of builders, in [[Keighley]], in the former [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], on 30 April 1920 and was raised in the town.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Faye |title=The story behind the 99-year-old legend who raised \u00a314m for the NHS |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/16/tom-moore-story-behind-14000000-nhs-legend-12565964/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Metro |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strayfm.com/news/local-news/3082429/coronavirus-veteran-from-keighley-raises-over-2-million-for-nhs/|title=Coronavirus: Veteran from Keighley raises over \u00a32 MILLION for NHS|date=14 April 2020|publisher=Stray FM|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/14/war-veteran-99-raises-2m-for-nhs-by-walking-lengths-of-back-garden|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36m for NHS by walking lengths of back garden|first=Jessica|last=Murray|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He was educated at [[Keighley Grammar School]] and completed an apprenticeship in [[civil engineering]].<ref name=\"Nicholls\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/14/second-world-war-veteran-raises-2-million-nhs/ |title=Second World War veteran raises more than \u00a33m for NHS |first=Dominic |last=Nicholls |date=14 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nMoore  enlisted in the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment#8th Battalion|8th Battalion, Duke of Wellington's Regiment]] (8 DWR) at the beginning of the [[Second World War]], stationed in [[Cornwall]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> He was selected for officer training in 1940,<ref name=\"Nicholls\" />  and attended an Officer Cadet Training Unit before being commissioned as a [[second lieutenant#United Kingdom & other Commonwealth countries|second lieutenant]] on 28 June 1941.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35218|date=11 July 1941|page=4057|supp=y}}</ref>\n\nMoore became a member of the [[Royal Armoured Corps]] on 22 October 1941 when his battalion, the 8 DWR, became an armoured unit, designated as the [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35740|date=9 October 1942|page=4432|supp=y}}</ref><ref name=\"Nicholls\"/> Later he was transferred to the 9th Battalion (9 DWR) in India, which had also been redesignated as the [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]. He was initially posted to [[Bombay]] and subsequently to [[Calcutta]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> His regiment were equipped with [[M3 Lee]] tanks and participated in the [[Battle of Ramree Island]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whiting |first1=Charles |last2=Taylor |first2=Eric |date=2008 |title=The Fighting Tykes: An Informal History of the Yorkshire Regiments in the Second World War |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9kt-AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA132 |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |page=132 |isbn=978-1844156450}}</ref> He was promoted to war-substantive [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 1 October 1942 and to temporary [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 11 October 1944.<ref>{{cite book |date=1946 |title=The Quarterly Army List (August 1946 - Part I) |location=London |publisher=HM Stationery Office |isbn= |pages=385a |url=https://archive.org/details/armylistaugpart121946grea/page/398/mode/2up|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe served in [[Arakan Campaign 1942\u201343|Arakan]] in western Burma and afterward in [[Sumatra]] after the Japanese surrendered,<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52278746|title=Army veteran, 99, raises \u00a34m for 'humbled' NHS|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref> by which time he had risen to the rank of captain.<ref name=\"Nicholls\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/> On his return to Britain he served as an instructor at the Armoured Fighting Vehicle School in [[Bovington Camp|Bovington]], Dorset.<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/>\n\n=== Decorations ===\nDuring his war service, Moore was awarded three medals:<ref name=\"ES\">{{cite news |title=War veteran, 99, hits \u00a314m for NHS as Hancock calls him an inspiration |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/war-veteran-tom-moore-matt-hancock-9-million-nhs-a4415496.html |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n*[[1939\u20131945 Star]]\n*[[Burma Star]]\n*[[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]\n\n== Later work and hobbies ==\n\nAfter leaving the army, he worked as managing director of a company manufacturing [[concrete]].<ref name=\"Spary\" />\n\nFor 64 years he organised the DWR's annual reunion.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\nMoore raced motorcycles competitively, wearing the number 23.<ref name=\"Hancocks\">{{cite web |last1=Hancocks |first1=Simon |title=Veteran NHS fundraiser Captain Tom Moore was also a motorcycle racer |url=https://www.visordown.com/news/general/veteran-nhs-fundraiser-captain-tom-moore-was-also-motorcycle-racer |website=Visordown |accessdate=17 April 2020 }}</ref> He rode a [[The Scott Motorcycle Company|Scott motorcycle]], winning several trophies.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\n== Tom's 100th Birthday Walk  ==\n[[File:Captain Tom Moore fundraising walk.jpg|thumb|upright|Moore during the fund-raising initiative walk. He is wearing the [[1939\u20131945 Star]], [[Burma Star]], and [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]. |alt=Moore wearing a blazer with regimental badge, regimental tie and three medals]]\n\nOn 6 April 2020 he began a fundraising campaign to help the British [[National Health Service]] (NHS) during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] by aiming to complete one hundred, {{convert|25|m|yard|abbr=on}} laps of his garden, ten laps per day, with the help of a [[Walker (mobility)|walking frame]], branding the endeavour \"'''Tom's 100th Birthday Walk For The NHS'''\".<ref name=\"Spary\" /><ref name=\"Low\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52290976\">{{cite web |title=Army veteran's \u00a37m for NHS 'out of this world' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52290976 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe initial \u00a31,000 goal having been realised on Friday 10 April, the target was increased, first to \u00a35,000, and eventually to \u00a3500,000 as more people around the world became involved.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/nhs-100-birthday-walk-army-veteran-tom-moore-fundraise-a9463561.html |title=99-year-old army veteran raises more than \u00a31m for NHS with \u2018100th birthday walk\u2019 |date=14 April 2020 |work=The Independent |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> The fund-raising soared exponentially when the British media publicised the endeavour. Moore, who joined [[Twitter]] in the same month, used the site to express joy over accumulating such a staggering amount of money for the NHS.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=CaptainTomMoore |number=1250418629218168833 |date=15 April 2020 |title=7 MILLION POUNDS!!!! The Great British public, your generosity is just incredible! THANK YOU!! }}</ref> \n\nThe [[JustGiving]] page for his walk reports that, as of 14:30 18 April 2020 (UTC), he had raised in excess of \u00a323<!-- please update the figure in two places, and the date/ timestamp-->&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"JGTM\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs |publisher=[[JustGiving]] |accessdate=18 April 2020 }}</ref> the largest-ever amount raised by a JustGiving campaign,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |website=inews.co.uk| access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-18098819|title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard|last=Shaw|first=Neil|date=2020-04-16|website=walesonline|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> beating the previous record of \u00a35.2&nbsp;million raised (partially posthumously) by [[Stephen Sutton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen's fundraising page |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/stephen-sutton-tct |website=JustGiving |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Butterworth\">{{cite news |last1=Butterworth |first1=Benjamin |title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=inews.co.uk }}</ref> More than 1.1 million individuals have donated.<ref name=\"JGTM\" />\n\nFunds raised by Moore are being spent on such things as well-being packs for National Health Service staff facilitating rest and recuperation rooms, devices to enable hospital patients to keep in contact with family members, and community groups who support patients once discharged from hospitals.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52325713\">{{cite web |last1=Shepka |first1=Phil |last2=Lewis |first2=Katy |title=How will Captain Tom Moore's millions be spent? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52325713 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe achieved his initial target of one hundred laps on the morning of 16 April, watched [[Social distancing measures related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|at a safe distance]] by a [[guard of honour]] from the [[1st Battalion, The Yorkshire Regiment|1st Battalion of the Yorkshire Regiment]],<ref name=\"Shaw\">{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Neil |title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard |url=https://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-4050824 |work=hulldailymail |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> into which the DWR were merged in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx |title=The Yorkshire Regiment |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence]] |archivedate=27 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527064813/http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx }}</ref> He has said he will not stop, and aims to do a second hundred.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" />\n\nLater on 16 April a UK Government spokesman said:<ref name=\"Lovett\">{{cite news |last1=Lovett |first1=Samuel |title=UK death toll rises again as lockdown to be extended \u2013 follow live |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-news-live-update-latest-today-cases-deaths-lockdown-covid-19-a9467756.html#post-1187989853 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The Prime Minister will certainly be looking at ways to recognise Tom's heroic efforts.}}\n\nOn reaching the \u00a35&nbsp;million mark, Moore explained his motivation:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-52296313/coronavirus-army-veteran-tom-moore-finds-out-he-s-raised-5m-for-nhs |title=Army veteran, 99, finds out he's raised \u00a35m for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When we started off with this exercise we didn't anticipate we'd get anything near that sort of money. It's really amazing. All of them, from top to bottom, in the National Health Service, they deserve everything that we can possibly put in their place. They're all so brave. Because every morning or every night they're putting themselves into harm's way, and I think you've got to give them full marks for that effort. We're a little bit like having a war at the moment. But the doctors and the nurses, they're all on the front line, and all of us behind, we've got to supply them and keep them going with everything that they need, so that they can do their jobs even better than they're doing now.}}\n\nBy mid-day on 17 April, more than 505,000 people had signed a petition calling for him to be knighted.<ref name=\"BBC-52321262\">{{cite news |title=Prince William hails veteran's \u00a318m NHS fundraiser |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52321262 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Charity recording ===\n\nTo mark Moore's 100th lap, the singer [[Michael Ball]] has recorded a version of \"[[You'll Never Walk Alone]]\", with the NHS Voices of Care Choir. Moore provides spoken words.<ref name=\"ITV\">{{cite news |title=Captain Tom Moore launches You'll Never Walk Alone charity single with Michael Ball |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-18/captain-tom-moore-launches-you-ll-never-walk-alone-charity-single-with-michael-ball/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=ITV News }}</ref> The recording has been released as a digital single by Decca Records.\n\n===Similar fundraising efforts===\nMoore's success inspired retired Welsh farmer Rhythwyn Evans to walk 91 laps of his bungalow in [[Silian, Ceredigion|Silian]], [[Ceredigion]], before his 91st birthday. Evans said that his walk was \"inspired by and in solidarity with Captain Tom Moore\" and that he aimed to raise \u00a31,000 for his local health board \"to give something back to the community\", having lived to a \"ripe old age\". As of 14:30, 18 April 2020 (UTC), Evans has raised over \u00a312,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/uk-news/2020/04/18/grandfather-walks-91-laps-around-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-to-raise-cash-for-nhs/ |title=Grandfather walks 91 laps around bungalow on 91st birthday to raise cash for NHS|publisher=Shropshire Star|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-52333077/coronavirus-capt-tom-moore-inspires-91-year-old-s-walk-for-nhs|title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore inspires 91-year-old's walk for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=17 April 2020 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"JGDE\">{{cite web |title=Her 91 dros COVID-19 Rhythwyn |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/david-evans186 |accessdate=18 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMoore married Pamela in 1968,<ref name=\"Lavender\">{{cite news |last1=Lavender |first1=Jane |title=Captain Tom Moore had 'given up on love' before he met beloved late wife aged 50 |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-given-up-21876074 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=mirror |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> and they had two daughters.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> Pamela died circa 2006.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> He has lived with one of his daughters, Hannah, her husband, and two grandchildren, in [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]] since 2008.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /> He also has two other grandchildren.<ref name=\"Brown\" /> In recent years he has received treatment from the NHS for skin cancer and, in 2018, a broken hip.<ref name=\"Brown\" /><ref name=\"Low\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/captain-tom-moore-99-walks-to-raise-millions-for-the-nhs-fzpn0cjfb|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, raises \u00a35m for NHS with 100th birthday walk|first=Valentine|last=Low|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/99-year-old-army-veteran-raises-2-million-charity-walking-his-backyard-1497742|title=99-year-old army veteran raises $2 million for charity by walking in his backyard|first=Khaleda | last=Rahman|date=14 April 2020|website=Newsweek|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spary\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/world/war-veteran-raises-millions-garden-scli-intl-gbr/index.html|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36 million by walking laps of his garden|first=Sara |last=Spary|website=CNN|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs Moore's fund-raising page]\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{YouTube|wUP-ty-Tj5E|You'll Never Walk Alone}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52316856 Captain Tom Moore: How the war veteran captured our hearts] \u2013 BBC news\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Tom}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Duke of Wellington's Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:English civil engineers]]\n[[Category:People from Keighley]]\n[[Category:Skin cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Royal Armoured Corps officers]]\n[[Category:English motorcycle racers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Army Officer and fundraiser}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n| name               = Tom Moore\n| image              = Tom Moore (soldier).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Moore during his military service\n| birth_name         = Thomas Moore\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Keighley]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = British\n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma mater         = \n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Army officer\n* Managing director \n}}\n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| known for          = {{Plainlist|\n* Second World War veteran\n* 2020 fundraising walk\n}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Keighley Grammar School]], West Yorkshire\n| boards             = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = 2\n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| website            = {{URL|https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs|tomswalkforthenhs}}\n| module = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n   | allegiance  = {{GBR}}\n   |branch       = {{flagicon image|Flag of the British Army (1938-present).png}} [[British Army]]\n   |serviceyears = 1939\u20131946\n   |rank         = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n   |unit         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]]\n* [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n* [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n}}\n   |commands     = \n   |battles           = {{tree list}}\n*[[World War II|Second World War]]\n**[[Burma campaign 1944\u201345|Burma Campaign]]\n***[[Battle of Ramree Island]]\n   |awards = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Thomas Moore''' (born 30 April 1920), known as '''Captain Tom''', is a former [[British Army]] officer, best known for his philanthropic work. Moore served in India and in the [[Burma campaign]] during the [[Second World War]]. He later became an instructor in [[armoured warfare]]. After the war, he worked as a managing director of a concrete company. He also raced motorcycles. On 6 April 2020, at the age of 99, he began to walk around his garden in aid of [[NHS Charities Together]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]], with the goal of raising \u00a31,000 by his hundredth birthday on 30 April. By 18 April he had raised over \u00a323<!-- please update the figure in two places, and the date/timestamp -->&nbsp;million, and a further \u00a34.27 million in [[Gift Aid]].\n\n==Early life and family==\n\nMoore was born to Wilfred, one of a family of builders, in [[Keighley]], in the former [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], on 30 April 1920 and was raised in the town.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Faye |title=The story behind the 99-year-old legend who raised \u00a314m for the NHS |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/16/tom-moore-story-behind-14000000-nhs-legend-12565964/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Metro |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strayfm.com/news/local-news/3082429/coronavirus-veteran-from-keighley-raises-over-2-million-for-nhs/|title=Coronavirus: Veteran from Keighley raises over \u00a32 MILLION for NHS|date=14 April 2020|publisher=Stray FM|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/14/war-veteran-99-raises-2m-for-nhs-by-walking-lengths-of-back-garden|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36m for NHS by walking lengths of back garden|first=Jessica|last=Murray|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He was educated at [[Keighley Grammar School]] and completed an apprenticeship in [[civil engineering]].<ref name=\"Nicholls\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/14/second-world-war-veteran-raises-2-million-nhs/ |title=Second World War veteran raises more than \u00a33m for NHS |first=Dominic |last=Nicholls |date=14 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nMoore  enlisted in the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment#8th Battalion|8th Battalion, Duke of Wellington's Regiment]] (8 DWR) at the beginning of the [[Second World War]], stationed in [[Cornwall]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> He was selected for officer training in 1940,<ref name=\"Nicholls\" />  and attended an Officer Cadet Training Unit before being commissioned as a [[second lieutenant#United Kingdom & other Commonwealth countries|second lieutenant]] on 28 June 1941.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35218|date=11 July 1941|page=4057|supp=y}}</ref>\n\nMoore became a member of the [[Royal Armoured Corps]] on 22 October 1941 when his battalion, the 8 DWR, became an armoured unit, designated as the [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35740|date=9 October 1942|page=4432|supp=y}}</ref><ref name=\"Nicholls\"/> Later he was transferred to the 9th Battalion (9 DWR) in India, which had also been redesignated as the [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]. He was initially posted to [[Bombay]] and subsequently to [[Calcutta]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> His regiment were equipped with [[M3 Lee]] tanks and participated in the [[Battle of Ramree Island]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whiting |first1=Charles |last2=Taylor |first2=Eric |date=2008 |title=The Fighting Tykes: An Informal History of the Yorkshire Regiments in the Second World War |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9kt-AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA132 |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |page=132 |isbn=978-1844156450}}</ref> He was promoted to war-substantive [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 1 October 1942 and to temporary [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 11 October 1944.<ref>{{cite book |date=1946 |title=The Quarterly Army List (August 1946 - Part I) |location=London |publisher=HM Stationery Office |isbn= |pages=385a |url=https://archive.org/details/armylistaugpart121946grea/page/398/mode/2up|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe served in [[Arakan Campaign 1942\u201343|Arakan]] in western Burma and afterward in [[Sumatra]] after the Japanese surrendered,<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52278746|title=Army veteran, 99, raises \u00a34m for 'humbled' NHS|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref> by which time he had risen to the rank of captain.<ref name=\"Nicholls\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/> On his return to Britain he served as an instructor at the Armoured Fighting Vehicle School in [[Bovington Camp|Bovington]], Dorset.<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/>\n\n=== Decorations ===\nDuring his war service, Moore was awarded three medals:<ref name=\"ES\">{{cite news |title=War veteran, 99, hits \u00a314m for NHS as Hancock calls him an inspiration |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/war-veteran-tom-moore-matt-hancock-9-million-nhs-a4415496.html |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n*[[1939\u20131945 Star]]\n*[[Burma Star]]\n*[[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]\n\n== Later work and hobbies ==\n\nAfter leaving the army, he worked as managing director of a company manufacturing [[concrete]].<ref name=\"Spary\" />\n\nFor 64 years he organised the DWR's annual reunion.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\nMoore raced motorcycles competitively, wearing the number 23.<ref name=\"Hancocks\">{{cite web |last1=Hancocks |first1=Simon |title=Veteran NHS fundraiser Captain Tom Moore was also a motorcycle racer |url=https://www.visordown.com/news/general/veteran-nhs-fundraiser-captain-tom-moore-was-also-motorcycle-racer |website=Visordown |accessdate=17 April 2020 }}</ref> He rode a [[The Scott Motorcycle Company|Scott motorcycle]], winning several trophies.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\n== Tom's 100th Birthday Walk  ==\n[[File:Captain Tom Moore fundraising walk.jpg|thumb|upright|Moore during the fund-raising initiative walk. He is wearing the [[1939\u20131945 Star]], [[Burma Star]], and [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]. |alt=Moore wearing a blazer with regimental badge, regimental tie and three medals]]\n\nOn 6 April 2020 he began a fundraising campaign to help the British [[National Health Service]] (NHS) during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] by aiming to complete one hundred, {{convert|25|m|yard|abbr=on}} laps of his garden, ten laps per day, with the help of a [[Walker (mobility)|walking frame]], branding the endeavour \"'''Tom's 100th Birthday Walk For The NHS'''\".<ref name=\"Spary\" /><ref name=\"Low\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52290976\">{{cite web |title=Army veteran's \u00a37m for NHS 'out of this world' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52290976 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe initial \u00a31,000 goal having been realised on Friday 10 April, the target was increased, first to \u00a35,000, and eventually to \u00a3500,000 as more people around the world became involved.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/nhs-100-birthday-walk-army-veteran-tom-moore-fundraise-a9463561.html |title=99-year-old army veteran raises more than \u00a31m for NHS with \u2018100th birthday walk\u2019 |date=14 April 2020 |work=The Independent |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> The fund-raising soared exponentially when the British media publicised the endeavour. Moore, who joined [[Twitter]] in the same month, used the site to express joy over accumulating such a staggering amount of money for the NHS.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=CaptainTomMoore |number=1250418629218168833 |date=15 April 2020 |title=7 MILLION POUNDS!!!! The Great British public, your generosity is just incredible! THANK YOU!! }}</ref> \n\nThe [[JustGiving]] page for his walk reports that, as of 14:30 18 April 2020 (UTC), he had raised in excess of \u00a323<!-- please update the figure in two places, and the date/ timestamp-->&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"JGTM\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs |publisher=[[JustGiving]] |accessdate=18 April 2020 }}</ref> the largest-ever amount raised by a JustGiving campaign,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |website=inews.co.uk| access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-18098819|title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard|last=Shaw|first=Neil|date=2020-04-16|website=walesonline|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> beating the previous record of \u00a35.2&nbsp;million raised (partially posthumously) by [[Stephen Sutton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen's fundraising page |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/stephen-sutton-tct |website=JustGiving |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Butterworth\">{{cite news |last1=Butterworth |first1=Benjamin |title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=inews.co.uk }}</ref> More than 1.1 million individuals have donated.<ref name=\"JGTM\" />\n\nFunds raised by Moore are being spent on such things as well-being packs for National Health Service staff facilitating rest and recuperation rooms, devices to enable hospital patients to keep in contact with family members, and community groups who support patients once discharged from hospitals.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52325713\">{{cite web |last1=Shepka |first1=Phil |last2=Lewis |first2=Katy |title=How will Captain Tom Moore's millions be spent? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52325713 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe achieved his initial target of one hundred laps on the morning of 16 April, watched [[Social distancing measures related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|at a safe distance]] by a [[guard of honour]] from the [[1st Battalion, The Yorkshire Regiment|1st Battalion of the Yorkshire Regiment]],<ref name=\"Shaw\">{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Neil |title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard |url=https://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-4050824 |work=hulldailymail |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> into which the DWR were merged in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx |title=The Yorkshire Regiment |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence]] |archivedate=27 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527064813/http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx }}</ref> He has said he will not stop, and aims to do a second hundred.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" />\n\nLater on 16 April a UK Government spokesman said:<ref name=\"Lovett\">{{cite news |last1=Lovett |first1=Samuel |title=UK death toll rises again as lockdown to be extended \u2013 follow live |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-news-live-update-latest-today-cases-deaths-lockdown-covid-19-a9467756.html#post-1187989853 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The Prime Minister will certainly be looking at ways to recognise Tom's heroic efforts.}}\n\nOn reaching the \u00a35&nbsp;million mark, Moore explained his motivation:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-52296313/coronavirus-army-veteran-tom-moore-finds-out-he-s-raised-5m-for-nhs |title=Army veteran, 99, finds out he's raised \u00a35m for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When we started off with this exercise we didn't anticipate we'd get anything near that sort of money. It's really amazing. All of them, from top to bottom, in the National Health Service, they deserve everything that we can possibly put in their place. They're all so brave. Because every morning or every night they're putting themselves into harm's way, and I think you've got to give them full marks for that effort. We're a little bit like having a war at the moment. But the doctors and the nurses, they're all on the front line, and all of us behind, we've got to supply them and keep them going with everything that they need, so that they can do their jobs even better than they're doing now.}}\n\nBy mid-day on 17 April, more than 505,000 people had signed a petition calling for him to be knighted.<ref name=\"BBC-52321262\">{{cite news |title=Prince William hails veteran's \u00a318m NHS fundraiser |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52321262 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Charity recording ===\n\nTo mark Moore's 100th lap, the singer [[Michael Ball]] has recorded a version of \"[[You'll Never Walk Alone]]\", with the NHS Voices of Care Choir. Moore provides spoken words.<ref name=\"ITV\">{{cite news |title=Captain Tom Moore launches You'll Never Walk Alone charity single with Michael Ball |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-18/captain-tom-moore-launches-you-ll-never-walk-alone-charity-single-with-michael-ball/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=ITV News }}</ref> The recording has been released as as digital single by Decca Records.\n\n===Similar fundraising efforts===\nMoore's success inspired retired Welsh farmer Rhythwyn Evans to walk 91 laps of his bungalow in [[Silian, Ceredigion|Silian]], [[Ceredigion]], before his 91st birthday. Evans said that his walk was \"inspired by and in solidarity with Captain Tom Moore\" and that he aimed to raise \u00a31,000 for his local health board \"to give something back to the community\", having lived to a \"ripe old age\". As of 14:30, 18 April 2020 (UTC), Evans has raised over \u00a312,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/uk-news/2020/04/18/grandfather-walks-91-laps-around-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-to-raise-cash-for-nhs/ |title=Grandfather walks 91 laps around bungalow on 91st birthday to raise cash for NHS|publisher=Shropshire Star|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-52333077/coronavirus-capt-tom-moore-inspires-91-year-old-s-walk-for-nhs|title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore inspires 91-year-old's walk for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=17 April 2020 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"JGDE\">{{cite web |title=Her 91 dros COVID-19 Rhythwyn |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/david-evans186 |accessdate=18 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMoore married Pamela in 1968,<ref name=\"Lavender\">{{cite news |last1=Lavender |first1=Jane |title=Captain Tom Moore had 'given up on love' before he met beloved late wife aged 50 |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-given-up-21876074 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=mirror |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> and they had two daughters.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> Pamela died circa 2006.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> He has lived with one of his daughters, Hannah, her husband, and two grandchildren, in [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]] since 2008.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /> He also has two other grandchildren.<ref name=\"Brown\" /> In recent years he has received treatment from the NHS for skin cancer and, in 2018, a broken hip.<ref name=\"Brown\" /><ref name=\"Low\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/captain-tom-moore-99-walks-to-raise-millions-for-the-nhs-fzpn0cjfb|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, raises \u00a35m for NHS with 100th birthday walk|first=Valentine|last=Low|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/99-year-old-army-veteran-raises-2-million-charity-walking-his-backyard-1497742|title=99-year-old army veteran raises $2 million for charity by walking in his backyard|first=Khaleda | last=Rahman|date=14 April 2020|website=Newsweek|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spary\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/world/war-veteran-raises-millions-garden-scli-intl-gbr/index.html|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36 million by walking laps of his garden|first=Sara |last=Spary|website=CNN|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs Moore's fund-raising page]\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{YouTube|wUP-ty-Tj5E|You'll Never Walk Alone}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52316856 Captain Tom Moore: How the war veteran captured our hearts] \u2013 BBC news\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Tom}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Duke of Wellington's Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:English civil engineers]]\n[[Category:People from Keighley]]\n[[Category:Skin cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Royal Armoured Corps officers]]\n[[Category:English motorcycle racers]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word reworded", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Moore_(fundraiser)"}
{"title_page": "2023 Pan American Games", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Pan American Games| 2023 | Pan American |\n| image       = Santiago2023.png\n| image_size  = 250\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| host_city   = [[Santiago]], Chile\n| motto       = ''Follow Your Passion''<br>''{{Lang-es|Sigue Tu Pasi\u00f3n}}''\n| nations     = 41 \n| athletes    = \n| events      = 39 [[Pan American Games sports|sports]]\n| opening     = October 20 \u25c7\n| closing     = November 5 \n| opened_by   = \n| cauldron    = \n| stadium     = [[Estadio Nacional Julio Mart\u00ednez Pr\u00e1danos]]\n| prev        = [[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]]\n| next        = ''[[2027 Pan American Games|2027 TBD]]''\n}}\n{{Pan American Games series|2023}}\nThe '''2023 Pan American Games''', officially the '''XIX Pan American Games''', will be the 19th edition of the [[Pan American Games]] and an international multi-sport event scheduled to be held from October 22 to November 5, 2023 in [[Santiago]], [[Chile]].<ref>https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1057486/santiago-confirmed-as-host-of-2023-pan-american-games</ref>\n\n==Bidding process==\n{{further information|Bids for the 2023 Pan American Games}}\n\nTwo bids were submitted for the 2023 Pan American Games. [[Santiago]], [[Chile]] and [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]] both submitted bids, but Buenos Aires withdrew their bid in April 2017, leaving Santiago as the sole candidate.<ref>{{cite web|title=Santiago and Buenos Aires Will Compete To Host 2023 Pan American Games |url=http://santiagotimes.cl/2017/02/08/santiago-and-buenos-aires-will-compete-to-host-2023-pan-american-games/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Presidente del COCH: Chile debe postular de inmediato a los Juegos Panamericanos 2023 |url=http://www.adnradio.cl/noticias/deportes/presidente-del-coch-chile-debe-postular-de-inmediato-a-los-juegos-panamericanos-2023/20131021/nota/1999072.aspx}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Buenos Aires se postular\u00e1 para organizar los Juegos Panamericanos 2023 y podr\u00eda ser la \u00fanica candidata |url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1979581-buenos-aires-se-postulara-para-organizar-los-juegos-panamericanos-2023-y-podria-ser-la-unica-candidata}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Santiago virtual sede de los Panamericanos del 2023 tras la baja de Buenos Aires |url=http://chile.as.com/chile/2017/04/21/masdeporte/1492806953_278571.html |work=AS Chile |date=April 21, 2017}}</ref> \n\n===Host city election===\nSantiago was unanimously elected as the host city at the [[Association of National Olympic Committees|ANOC]] General Assembly in [[Prague]] on November 4, 2017. This will mark the first time Chile hosts the Pan American Games. Santiago was initially awarded the right to host the [[1975 Pan American Games|1975]] and later [[1987 Pan American Games]], but withdrew as host both times due to financial and political problems. Most recently, Santiago was a candidate for the [[2019 Pan American Games]] but lost to [[Lima]].<ref>https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1057486/santiago-confirmed-as-host-of-2023-pan-american-games</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" | 2023 Pan American Games bidding results\n|-\n! City\n! NOC name\n! Votes\n|-\n||'''[[Santiago]]'''|| '''{{flagicon|Chile}} Chile'''\n| align=center| '''Unanimous'''\n|}\n\n==Marketing==\n\n===Emblem===\nThe official emblem was unveiled on July 17, 2019, at the Centro de Alto Rendimiento CAR. The emblem was designed by Consultora b2o.\n\n===Mascot===\nThe mascot will be launched in 2021.\n\n===Slogan===\nThe slogan was unveiled the same day as the emblem. The slogan of the games is \"Follow Your Passion\" (Spanish: \"Sigue tu pasi\u00f3n\").\n==Sports==\n\nAccording to the Official Bidding Report published in late 2017, the 2023 Pan American Games programme is scheduled to feature 39 sports.<ref name=\"Magazine\">{{cite web |title=Revista Santiago 2023 Ciudad Candidata |trans-title=Santiago 2023 Candidate City Magazine |url=https://traspaso.digital.gob.cl/actas/otros/descarga/539 |website=Santiago 2023 |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |language=Spanish |date=2017}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n''Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of medal events to be contested in each sport/discipline.''\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[List of water sports|Aquatics]]\n** {{GamesSport|Artistic swimming|Events=2}}\n** {{GamesSport|Diving|Events=10}}\n** {{GamesSport|Open water swimming|Events=2}}\n** {{GamesSport|Swimming|Events=36}}\n** {{GamesSport|Water polo|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Archery|Events=8}}\n* {{GamesSport|Athletics|Events=48}}\n* {{GamesSport|Badminton|Events=5}}\n* {{GamesSport|Baseball|Events=1}}\n* {{GamesSport|Basketball|Events=4}}\n* {{GamesSport|Basque pelota|Events=10}}\n* {{GamesSport|Bowling|Events=4}}\n* {{GamesSport|Boxing|Events=15}}\n* {{GamesSport|Canoeing}} \n** [[Canoe sprint]] <small>(12)</small>\n** [[Whitewater slalom|Canoe slalom]] <small>(6)</small>\n* {{GamesSport|Cycling}}\n** [[BMX]] <small>(4)</small>\n** [[Mountain biking]] <small>(2)</small>\n** [[Road bicycle racing|Road]] <small>(4)</small>\n** [[Track cycling|Track]] <small>(12)</small>\n* {{GamesSport|Equestrian}}\n** [[Dressage]] <small>(2)</small>\n** [[Eventing]] <small>(2)</small>\n** [[Show jumping|Jumping]] <small>(2)</small>\n* {{GamesSport|Fencing|Events=12}}\n* {{GamesSport|Field hockey|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Football|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Golf|Events=3}}\n* {{GamesSport|Gymnastics}}\n** [[Artistic gymnastics]] <small>(14)</small>\n** [[Rhythmic gymnastics]] <small>(8)</small>\n** [[Trampoline]] <small>(2)</small>\n* {{GamesSport|Handball|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Judo|Events=14}}\n* {{GamesSport|Karate|Events=14}}\n* {{GamesSport|Modern pentathlon|Events=5}}\n* {{GamesSport|Racquetball|Events=6}}\n* {{GamesSport|Roller sports}}\n** [[Artistic roller skating|Figure Skating]] <small>(2)</small>\n** [[Inline speed skating|Speed Skating]] <small>(6)</small>\n* {{GamesSport|Rowing|Events=14}}\n* {{GamesSport|Rugby sevens|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Sailing|Events=11}}\n* {{GamesSport|Shooting|Events=15}}\n* {{GamesSport|Softball|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Squash|Events=7}}\n* {{GamesSport|Surfing|Events=8}}\n* {{GamesSport|Table tennis|Events=7}}\n* {{GamesSport|Taekwondo|Events=12}}\n* {{GamesSport|Tennis|Events=5}}\n* {{GamesSport|Triathlon|Events=3}}\n* [[Volleyball]]\n** {{GamesSport|Beach volleyball|Events=2}}\n** {{GamesSport|Volleyball|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Water skiing|Events=10}}\n* {{GamesSport|Weightlifting|Events=14}}\n* {{GamesSport|Wrestling}}\n** [[Freestyle wrestling|Freestyle]] <small>(12)</small>\n** [[Greco-Roman wrestling|Greco-Roman]] <small>(6)</small>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Venues==\n\n{{expand section|date=October 2017}}\n\n==The Games==\n===Participating nations===\nAll 41 nations who are members of the [[Pan American Sports Organization]] are expected to compete.\n\n<!--''The numbers in parenthesis represents the number of participants expected to qualify.''-->\n{{col-begin|width=100%}}\n{{col-1-of-4}}\n* {{flagPASO|ANT|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|ARG|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|ARU|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BAH|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BAR|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BIZ|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BER|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BOL|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BRA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|IVB|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|CAN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|CAY|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|COL|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|CHI|2023|}} '''(Host)'''\n{{col-2-of-4}}\n* {{flagPASO|CRC|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|CUB|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|DMA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|DOM|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|ECU|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|ESA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|GRN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|GUA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|GUY|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|HAI|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|HON|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|JAM|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|MEX|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|NCA|2023|}}\n{{col-3-of-4}}\n* {{flagPASO|PAN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|PAR|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|PER|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|PUR|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|LCA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|SKN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|VIN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|SUR|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|TRI|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|USA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|URU|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|VEN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|ISV|2023|}}\n{{col-4-of-4}}\n[[File:2015 Pan American Games Participating Countries.png|thumb|right|A map of all 41 participating nations]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[2022 Commonwealth Games]]\n*[[2023 Parapan American Games]]\n*[[2024 Summer Olympics]]\n*[[2028 Summer Olympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n<br>\n==External links==\n*[http://www.santiago2023.org/ Santiago 2023 Official Site]\n*[http://www.panamsports.org PASO website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[2019 Pan American Games|Lima]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=XIX [[Pan American Games]] <br /> ''[[Santiago]]''|years=(2023)}}\n{{s-aft|after=''[[2027 Pan American Games|TBD]]''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Pan American Games}}\n\n[[Category:2023 Pan American Games| ]]\n[[Category:Scheduled multi-sport events|Pan American Games 2023]]\n[[Category:2023 in multi-sport events]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions hosted by Chile]]\n[[Category:Multi-sport events in Chile]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Santiago]]\n[[Category:2023 in Chile]]\n[[Category:2023 in South American sport]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Pan American Games| 2023 | Pan American |\n| image       = Santiago2023.png\n| image_size  = 250\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| host_city   = [[Santiago]], Chile\n| motto       = ''Follow Your Passion''<br>''{{Lang-es|Sigue Tu Pasi\u00f3n}}''\n| nations     = 41 \n| athletes    = \n| events      = 39 [[Pan American Games sports|sports]]\n| opening     = October 20 \n| closing     = November 5 \n| opened_by   = \n| cauldron    = \n| stadium     = [[Estadio Nacional Julio Mart\u00ednez Pr\u00e1danos]]\n| prev        = [[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]]\n| next        = ''[[2027 Pan American Games|2027 TBD]]''\n}}\n{{Pan American Games series|2023}}\nThe '''2023 Pan American Games''', officially the '''XIX Pan American Games''', will be the 19th edition of the [[Pan American Games]] and an international multi-sport event scheduled to be held from October 22 to November 5, 2023 in [[Santiago]], [[Chile]].<ref>https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1057486/santiago-confirmed-as-host-of-2023-pan-american-games</ref>\n\n==Bidding process==\n{{further information|Bids for the 2023 Pan American Games}}\n\nTwo bids were submitted for the 2023 Pan American Games. [[Santiago]], [[Chile]] and [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]] both submitted bids, but Buenos Aires withdrew their bid in April 2017, leaving Santiago as the sole candidate.<ref>{{cite web|title=Santiago and Buenos Aires Will Compete To Host 2023 Pan American Games |url=http://santiagotimes.cl/2017/02/08/santiago-and-buenos-aires-will-compete-to-host-2023-pan-american-games/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Presidente del COCH: Chile debe postular de inmediato a los Juegos Panamericanos 2023 |url=http://www.adnradio.cl/noticias/deportes/presidente-del-coch-chile-debe-postular-de-inmediato-a-los-juegos-panamericanos-2023/20131021/nota/1999072.aspx}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Buenos Aires se postular\u00e1 para organizar los Juegos Panamericanos 2023 y podr\u00eda ser la \u00fanica candidata |url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1979581-buenos-aires-se-postulara-para-organizar-los-juegos-panamericanos-2023-y-podria-ser-la-unica-candidata}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Santiago virtual sede de los Panamericanos del 2023 tras la baja de Buenos Aires |url=http://chile.as.com/chile/2017/04/21/masdeporte/1492806953_278571.html |work=AS Chile |date=April 21, 2017}}</ref> \n\n===Host city election===\nSantiago was unanimously elected as the host city at the [[Association of National Olympic Committees|ANOC]] General Assembly in [[Prague]] on November 4, 2017. This will mark the first time Chile hosts the Pan American Games. Santiago was initially awarded the right to host the [[1975 Pan American Games|1975]] and later [[1987 Pan American Games]], but withdrew as host both times due to financial and political problems. Most recently, Santiago was a candidate for the [[2019 Pan American Games]] but lost to [[Lima]].<ref>https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1057486/santiago-confirmed-as-host-of-2023-pan-american-games</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" | 2023 Pan American Games bidding results\n|-\n! City\n! NOC name\n! Votes\n|-\n||'''[[Santiago]]'''|| '''{{flagicon|Chile}} Chile'''\n| align=center| '''Unanimous'''\n|}\n\n==Marketing==\n\n===Emblem===\nThe official emblem was unveiled on July 17, 2019, at the Centro de Alto Rendimiento CAR. The emblem was designed by Consultora b2o.\n\n===Mascot===\nThe mascot will be launched in 2021.\n\n===Slogan===\nThe slogan was unveiled the same day as the emblem. The slogan of the games is \"Follow Your Passion\" (Spanish: \"Sigue tu pasi\u00f3n\").\n==Sports==\n\nAccording to the Official Bidding Report published in late 2017, the 2023 Pan American Games programme is scheduled to feature 39 sports.<ref name=\"Magazine\">{{cite web |title=Revista Santiago 2023 Ciudad Candidata |trans-title=Santiago 2023 Candidate City Magazine |url=https://traspaso.digital.gob.cl/actas/otros/descarga/539 |website=Santiago 2023 |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |language=Spanish |date=2017}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n''Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of medal events to be contested in each sport/discipline.''\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[List of water sports|Aquatics]]\n** {{GamesSport|Artistic swimming|Events=2}}\n** {{GamesSport|Diving|Events=10}}\n** {{GamesSport|Open water swimming|Events=2}}\n** {{GamesSport|Swimming|Events=36}}\n** {{GamesSport|Water polo|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Archery|Events=8}}\n* {{GamesSport|Athletics|Events=48}}\n* {{GamesSport|Badminton|Events=5}}\n* {{GamesSport|Baseball|Events=1}}\n* {{GamesSport|Basketball|Events=4}}\n* {{GamesSport|Basque pelota|Events=10}}\n* {{GamesSport|Bowling|Events=4}}\n* {{GamesSport|Boxing|Events=15}}\n* {{GamesSport|Canoeing}} \n** [[Canoe sprint]] <small>(12)</small>\n** [[Whitewater slalom|Canoe slalom]] <small>(6)</small>\n* {{GamesSport|Cycling}}\n** [[BMX]] <small>(4)</small>\n** [[Mountain biking]] <small>(2)</small>\n** [[Road bicycle racing|Road]] <small>(4)</small>\n** [[Track cycling|Track]] <small>(12)</small>\n* {{GamesSport|Equestrian}}\n** [[Dressage]] <small>(2)</small>\n** [[Eventing]] <small>(2)</small>\n** [[Show jumping|Jumping]] <small>(2)</small>\n* {{GamesSport|Fencing|Events=12}}\n* {{GamesSport|Field hockey|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Football|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Golf|Events=3}}\n* {{GamesSport|Gymnastics}}\n** [[Artistic gymnastics]] <small>(14)</small>\n** [[Rhythmic gymnastics]] <small>(8)</small>\n** [[Trampoline]] <small>(2)</small>\n* {{GamesSport|Handball|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Judo|Events=14}}\n* {{GamesSport|Karate|Events=14}}\n* {{GamesSport|Modern pentathlon|Events=5}}\n* {{GamesSport|Racquetball|Events=6}}\n* {{GamesSport|Roller sports}}\n** [[Artistic roller skating|Figure Skating]] <small>(2)</small>\n** [[Inline speed skating|Speed Skating]] <small>(6)</small>\n* {{GamesSport|Rowing|Events=14}}\n* {{GamesSport|Rugby sevens|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Sailing|Events=11}}\n* {{GamesSport|Shooting|Events=15}}\n* {{GamesSport|Softball|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Squash|Events=7}}\n* {{GamesSport|Surfing|Events=8}}\n* {{GamesSport|Table tennis|Events=7}}\n* {{GamesSport|Taekwondo|Events=12}}\n* {{GamesSport|Tennis|Events=5}}\n* {{GamesSport|Triathlon|Events=3}}\n* [[Volleyball]]\n** {{GamesSport|Beach volleyball|Events=2}}\n** {{GamesSport|Volleyball|Events=2}}\n* {{GamesSport|Water skiing|Events=10}}\n* {{GamesSport|Weightlifting|Events=14}}\n* {{GamesSport|Wrestling}}\n** [[Freestyle wrestling|Freestyle]] <small>(12)</small>\n** [[Greco-Roman wrestling|Greco-Roman]] <small>(6)</small>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Venues==\n\n{{expand section|date=October 2017}}\n\n==The Games==\n===Participating nations===\nAll 41 nations who are members of the [[Pan American Sports Organization]] are expected to compete.\n\n<!--''The numbers in parenthesis represents the number of participants expected to qualify.''-->\n{{col-begin|width=100%}}\n{{col-1-of-4}}\n* {{flagPASO|ANT|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|ARG|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|ARU|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BAH|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BAR|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BIZ|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BER|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BOL|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|BRA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|IVB|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|CAN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|CAY|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|COL|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|CHI|2023|}} '''(Host)'''\n{{col-2-of-4}}\n* {{flagPASO|CRC|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|CUB|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|DMA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|DOM|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|ECU|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|ESA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|GRN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|GUA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|GUY|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|HAI|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|HON|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|JAM|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|MEX|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|NCA|2023|}}\n{{col-3-of-4}}\n* {{flagPASO|PAN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|PAR|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|PER|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|PUR|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|LCA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|SKN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|VIN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|SUR|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|TRI|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|USA|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|URU|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|VEN|2023|}}\n* {{flagPASO|ISV|2023|}}\n{{col-4-of-4}}\n[[File:2015 Pan American Games Participating Countries.png|thumb|right|A map of all 41 participating nations]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[2022 Commonwealth Games]]\n*[[2023 Parapan American Games]]\n*[[2024 Summer Olympics]]\n*[[2028 Summer Olympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n<br>\n==External links==\n*[http://www.santiago2023.org/ Santiago 2023 Official Site]\n*[http://www.panamsports.org PASO website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[2019 Pan American Games|Lima]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=XIX [[Pan American Games]] <br /> ''[[Santiago]]''|years=(2023)}}\n{{s-aft|after=''[[2027 Pan American Games|TBD]]''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Pan American Games}}\n\n[[Category:2023 Pan American Games| ]]\n[[Category:Scheduled multi-sport events|Pan American Games 2023]]\n[[Category:2023 in multi-sport events]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions hosted by Chile]]\n[[Category:Multi-sport events in Chile]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Santiago]]\n[[Category:2023 in Chile]]\n[[Category:2023 in South American sport]]\n", "name_user": "181.54.181.73", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_Pan_American_Games"}
{"title_page": "John Darras", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox MP\n| honorific-prefix =Sir\n| name = John Darras\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Shropshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Shropshire]]\n| parliament = English\n| majority = \n| predecessor1 = Sir Hugh Cheyne, Sir [[Roger Corbet (died 1395)]]\n| alongside1= Sir William Hugford\n| successor1 = Sir Adam Peshale, Sir William Hugford\n| term_start1 = 20 January 1393\n| term_end1 = 10 February 1393\n| predecessor2 = [[John Burley]], George Hawkestone\n| alongside2= John Burley\n| successor2 = [[David Holbache]], Thomas Whitton\n| term_start2 = 6 October 1404 \t\n| term_end2 = 13 November 1404\n| birth_date = c. 1355\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = March 1408\n| death_place = [[Neenton]]\n| death_cause=Suicide by hanging\n| nationality = English\n| spouse =Joan Corbet (died c. 1400)\n| party = \n| relations =Sir Roger Corbet (brother-in-law)\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation =Landowner, soldier.\n| profession =\n| religion =Roman Catholic\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n}}\n'''John Darras''' (c.1355\u20131408) was an English soldier, politician and landowner, who fought in the [[Hundred Years' War]] and against the [[Glynd\u0175r Rising]]. A client of the FitzAlan [[Earls of Arundel]], he served them in war and peace, helping consolidate their domination of his native county of [[Shropshire]]. He represented [[Shropshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Shropshire]] twice in the [[House of Commons of England]]. He died by his own hand.\n{{Location map+\n |Shropshire\n|relief=yes\n| width=500\n| float=right\n|border=\n|caption=Relief map of Shropshire and surrounding counties to show estates held or claimed by John Darras (blue dots) and his wife, Joan Corbet (red dots). Estates disputed with the Mawddwys are shown in pink.\n|alt=a map of Shropshire pinpointing estates connected with John Darras and Joan Corbet.\n|places=\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.3640|long=-2.3153|label=Ribbesford|mark = blue pog.svg|position=right|link=Ribbesford}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.3379|long=-2.3957|label=Rock|mark = blue pog.svg|position=top|link=Rock, Worcestershire}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5824|long=-2.4631|label=Linley|mark=blue pog.svg |link=}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.4876|long=-2.5359|label=Neenton|mark=blue pog.svg|position=left|link=Neenton}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.469|long=-2.4669|label=Sidbury|mark=blue pog.svg|position=right|link=}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.6851|long=-2.896|label=Yockleton|mark=pink pog.svg|position=left|link=Yockleton}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5283|long=-2.9099|label=Wentnor|mark=pink pog.svg|position=left|link=Wentnor}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.66|long=-2.9794|label=Caus|mark=pink pog.svg|position=right|link=Caus Castle}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5850|long=-2.981|label=Shelve|mark=pink pog.svg|position=right|link=}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5339|long=-2.345|label=Morfe Forest|label_size=80|mark=Legenda rezerwat scisly.svg|marksize=25 |position=right|link=Morfe Forest}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5786|long=-2.5043|label=Shirlett Forest|label_size=80|mark=Legenda rezerwat scisly.svg|marksize=25 |position=left|link=}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5323|long=-2.4193|label=Bridgnorth|label_size=110 |mark=Burg.svg|marksize=20 |position=left|link=Bridgnorth}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.7108|long=-2.7495|label=Shrewsbury|label_size=110 |mark=Burg.svg|marksize=20 |position=right|link=Shrewsbury}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.6095|long=-2.5979|label=Harley |mark=red pog.svg |position=top|link=Harley, Shropshire}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5493|long=-2.7137|label=Gretton |mark=red pog.svg |position=left|link=Gretton, Shropshire}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.6036|long=-2.6468|label=Kenley |mark=red pog.svg |position=left|link=Kenley}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.2884|long=-2.1647|label=Hampton Lovett |mark=red pog.svg |position=left|link=Hampton Lovett}}\n}}\n\n==Background and early life==\nJohn Darras was the son of:<ref name=mp>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/darras-john-1355-1408 DARRAS, John (c.1355\u20131408), of Sidbury and Neenton, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref>\n:*'''Ralph Darras''' or Daras of [[Neenton]]. The Darras family were not large landowners but part of the emerging [[landed gentry]]. Ralph Darras held the manors of Neenton and Sidbury,<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol14/pp348-350 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Edward III, Addendum to Vol. X, no. 355.]</ref> both south-west of [[Bridgnorth]] in Shropshire, part of the [[Welsh Marches]]. Although most such families were of [[Anglo-Normans|Anglo-Norman]] origin, Darras, originally rendered de Arras,<ref name=linley/> or d'Arras, signifies origins in [[Arras]], historically the chief town of [[Artois]] in Flanders.<ref>Hanks et al, p. 160</ref> It is generally rendered Daras in late medieval documents.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/inquisitionsasse04grea#page/246/mode/2up Feudal Aids, volume 4, p. 246.]</ref>\n:*'''Joan Forcer''', daughter and coheiress of Thomas Forcer. Joan, together with her sisters Burga and Elizabeth, was also an heiress of Sir Henry Ribbesford of [[Ribbesford]], near [[Bewdley]] in Worcestershire, who was the brother of their grandmother, Avice or Hawise le Forcer.<ref name=rib>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp297-317#h3-0003 Ribbesford with the Borough of Bewdley \u2013 Manors]</ref>\n\nRalph Darras, John's father, died in December 1461, when John was only about seven years of age.<ref name=ipq11-270/> This was during the second major outbreak of the [[Black Death]] in Shropshire,<ref>Baugh and Elrington (1989), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol4/pp72-118#anchorn23 Domesday Book: 1300\u20131540, note anchor 23.]</ref> although there is no record of Ralph Darras's cause of death. The plague brought great economic shifts alongside the human cost. Shropshire [[Inquisition post mortem|inquisitions post mortem]] taken during the plague outbreak show that land lay uncultivated and some landowners struggled to pay even very modest rents,<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol11/pp194-206 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Edward III, Volume 11, File 166, no. 233.]</ref> and some estates were considered worthless.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol11/pp400-414 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Edward III, Volume 11, File 179, no. 537.]</ref> While the majority of the rural population was placed at an advantage by labour shortages, landlords were forced to relax conditions imposed on tenants and to buy in labour.<ref>Baugh and Elrington (1989), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol4/pp72-118#anchorn196 Domesday Book: 1300\u20131540: Demesne agriculture, note anchor 196-199.]</ref> This is the economic and agrarian background to John Darras's lifelong struggles to consolidate and extend his estates and to find additional sources of income, mainly through business and military service.\n\nJohn Darras's mother, Joan, must also have died in his childhood. He fought legal battles to secure her inheritance, but alongside his aunts, not his mother.\n\n==Landowner==\n[[File:Sidbury church - geograph.org.uk - 395182.jpg|thumb|Holy Trinity church at [[Sidbury, Shropshire]]. The nave was already old by the time of Darras, as it was built in the 12th century, although the whole building underwent restoration in 1881.<ref>[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1053776 Church of Holy Trinity] at [[Historic England]].</ref>]]\n[[File:Ribbesford Church - geograph.org.uk - 703615.jpg|thumb|St Leonard's church at Ribbesford. The manor was the focus of early attempts by Darras to enlarge his holdings. There has been a small church on the site since about 1100. It was enlarged from the early 15th century, with modifications including the present nave.<ref>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42900#s5 Ribbesford with the Borough of Bewdley \u2013 Churches]</ref><ref>[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1115135 Church of St Leonard] at Historic England.</ref>]]\nThe inquisition following his father's death, taken at [[Bridgnorth]] on 19 March 1362, shows that the main estates Darras inherited from his father were the manors of Sidbury and Neenton, which were held of [[Edmund Mortimer, 3rd Earl of March]].<ref name=ipq11-270>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol11/pp215-230 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Edward III, Volume 11, File 168, no. 270.]</ref> in return for providing a [[hobelar]] (a light cavalryman mounted on a [[Irish Hobby|hobby]]) for [[Wigmore Castle]] when there was war in the [[Welsh Marches]]. There were also a few other small, scattered holdings, notably a third of the manor of Linley, held of the [[Wenlock Priory|Prior of Wenlock]].<ref name=linley>Currie et al, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol10/pp348-354#h3-0002 Linley \u2013 Manor and other estates.]</ref> This was a small patrimony and Darras fought legal battles, sometimes backed by force, at several points in his life to extend his holdings, although with limited success.\n\nIn 1379,<ref>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp297-317#n193 Ribbesford with the Borough of Bewdley \u2013 Manors, note anchor 193]</ref> and again in 1383,<ref>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp297-317#fnn196 Ribbesford with the Borough of Bewdley \u2013 Manors, footnote 196]</ref> Darras and his aunts Burga and Elizabeth contested ownership of the manors of Ribbesford and [[Rock, Worcestershire]], which had been held by Sir Henry Ribbesford, also under the Mortimers of [[Wigmore, Herefordshire|Wigmore]].<ref name=rib/> They were opposed by John de Resunden, the husband of their distant relative, Iseult. They won their suit but for reasons unknown the estates were both<ref name=rock-manor>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp319-328#h3-0002 Rock or Ake \u2013 Manors.]</ref> soon in the hands of [[Thomas de Beauchamp, 12th Earl of Warwick]], one of the [[Lords Appellant]], who was temporarily stripped of all his lands during [[Richard II of England|Richard II]]'s counter-coup of 1397.\n\n[[File:Priest's gravestone, Rock.jpg|thumb|left|A medieval monk, depicted on a gravestone at Rock. The church was monastic property.]]\nPatronage of the churches on most of these estates, potentially a lucrative right, went to Darras. The [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rectory]] of Sidbury was in his gift and he is known to have made presentations to it. On 16 June 1386 Darras authorised an exchange of clergy, by which the local priest went to St Katherine's chapel in [[Hereford Cathedral]] and the former cathedral chaplain, Philip Kentles, became rector of Sidbury.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork18unknuoft#page/n143/mode/2up ''Registrum Johannis Gilbert'', p. 125.]</ref> St Katherine's chapel served the Bishop's Palace,<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/rchme/heref/vol1/pp90-144#h3-0002 ''Hereford: Ecclesiastical'' in An Inventory of the Historical Monuments in Herefordshire, Volume 1, South west.]</ref> so this exchange must have been of importance to [[John Gilbert (bishop of St David's)|John Gilbert]], presumably earning Darras a modicum of episcopal favour. In April 1392 Darras appointed a successor after Philip's death.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork14unknuoft#page/n421/mode/2up ''Registrum Johannis Trefnant'', p. 176.]</ref> At Neenton too Darras held and used the advowson, presenting Roger Murimore as incumbent of the church in November 1399.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork14unknuoft#page/n427/mode/2up ''Registrum Johannis Trefnant'', p. 183.]</ref> Linley's church was a chapel of Holy Trinity Church in [[Much Wenlock]],<ref>Currie et al, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol10/pp348-354#h3-0006 Linley \u2013 Church.]</ref> which was in the hands of Wenlock Priory, the feudal overlord, leaving Darras with no control. However, while he had effective control of Ribbesford, the [[advowson]] must have been his to exercise, as it went with the manor.<ref>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp297-317#h3-0006 Ribbesford with the Borough of Bewdley \u2013 Advowsons.]</ref> In the case of Rock, however, the principal manor in the parish was not Rock itself but Alton,<ref name=rock-manor/> and the advowson of the church went with it: although there had been challenges from the Ribbesford family, the advowson was held by the [[Abbey of Saint-Evroul]] in [[Normandy]] during the 14th century.<ref>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp319-328#h3-0004 Rock or Ake \u2013 Advowson.]</ref>\n\nAs a substantial, if not grand, landowner, Darras was evidently enjoyed a degree of trust among the local [[landed gentry]]. He is known to have acted for others in land transactions, including Malcolm de la Mare,<ref name=mp/> Thomas Whitton and John Meisy.<ref>[http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/getrecord/CCA_X3365_67_40/ Shropshire Archives Document Reference: 3365/67/40, Recognizances 1377\u20131378], at Discovering Shropshire's History.</ref> His business associates tend to recur as personal and family allies throughout his known career.\n\n{{chart top|Family tree to illustrate the Ribbesford property disputes}}\nDerived from the table given by Wrottesley.<ref>Wrottesley. [https://archive.org/stream/pedigreesfromple00wrotrich#page/134/mode/2up Pedigrees from the Plea Rolls, p. 134.]</ref> and further information from the [[Victoria County History]].<ref name=rib/>\n{{tree chart/start}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|.}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | |Henry| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |Hawise|Henry=Henry de Ribbesford|Hawise=Hawise}}\n{{tree chart| |,|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.| | | | | |!}}\n{{tree chart|Jul| |John| |Walter|v|Con| |John2| |Thomas| | | |Tom|John=John the Elder|Walter=Walter|John2=John the Younger|Thomas=Thomas|Jul=Juliana|Tom=Thomas le Forcer|Con=Constance}}\n{{tree chart| |!| | | | | | | |,|-|^|-|.| | | | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.}}\n{{tree chart|Is| | | | | |Wal| |Rog| | | | | | | |Burg| |Liz| |Joan|v|Ral|Is=Isolda or Iseult|Wal=Walter|Rog=Roger|Burg=Burga|Liz=Elizabeth|Joan=Joan|Ral=Ralph Darras}}\n{{tree chart| |!| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!}}\n{{tree chart|Is|-|JohnR| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |JohnD|Is=Iseult|JohnR=John de Resunden|JohnD=John Darras}}\n{{tree chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==Marriage and family==\n[[File:Moreton Corbet Castle from west 01.JPG|thumb|Remains of the medieval [[keep]] at [[Moreton Corbet Castle]], with the [[curtain wall (fortification)|curtain wall]] curving around to the gatehouse, restored in the mid-16th century on the right. On the right are remains of the [[Elizabethan architecture|Elizabethan]] house. The Corbets of Moreton Corbet were themselves powerful allies but also, like Darras, found further security in the Arundel affinity.]]\nDarras married '''Joan Corbet'''. The marriage took place before 1390. However, as Darras is not recorded as active on Joan's behalf in the Corbet property disputes of 1385, it must have been in the second half of the 1380s. Darras formally entered the Arundel affinity in 1387, which may coincide approximately with his marriage.\n\nJoan Corbet was the daughter of \n:*'''Sir Robert Corbet''' (died 1375) of Moreton Corbet.<ref name=visitation/> The Corbets of Moreton Corbet had taken over as the senior line of Corbets in the region, as the Corbets at [[Caus Castle]] had petered out in 1347.<ref name=landlords/>\n:*'''Elizabeth Le Strange''', daughter of Fulk, 1st [[Baron Strange of Blackmere|Baron Strange]] of [[Blakemere|Blackmere]].<ref name=rog/><ref>[https://archive.org/stream/familyofcorbetit02corb#page/368/mode/2up Corbet, pedigree facing p.368,]</ref> The Le Strange family were another important dynasty of [[Marcher Lords]] with many branches. The Blackmere barony was of fairly recent foundation. Elizabeth's father was called to parliament by [[Edward II of England|Edward II]] and served him as Seneschal of Gascony,<ref>[http://www.gasconrolls.org/indexes/entity-004770.html Fulk Lestrange at the Gascon Rolls Project (1317\u20131478)], accessed 4 December 2013</ref> the head of the administration of the remaining [[Plantagenet]] possessions in France. The title could be passed through both male and female, and the tortuous line of descent of the Le Stranges may have been one of the factors predisposing the Corbets towards reinforcing [[male primogeniture]] through dubious property transactions. From 1383 it passed via female descent and marriage to the Talbot family,<ref name=landlords/> and was one of the many titles collected together by John Talbot, [[Baron Furnivall]] and later [[Earl of Shrewsbury]].\n\nJoan was the widow of Robert de Harley of Willey and had a daughter and heiress, Alice, who married Sir Hamo Peshall or Hamon Peshale. Joan brought a range of properties, acquired from her own family and her first husband, which must have greatly increased Darras's comfort and security while she was alive. She had a considerable amount of [[jointure]] property from her first marriage \u2013 in Shropshire at [[Harley, Shropshire|Harley]], [[Gretton, Shropshire|Gretton]], Willey and [[Kenley, Shropshire|Kenley]], and in [[Worcestershire]] part of a manor at [[Hampton Lovett]],<ref name=mp/> known as Over Hall.<ref name=hampton>A History of the County of Worcester: Volume 3: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43102#s2 Hampton Lovett \u2013 Manors], cf. footnote 28.</ref> Some of these properties passed to Roger Willey, a relative of Sir Robert Harley, in 1400,<ref name=mp/> presumably on Joan's death: Willey was a business associate of Darras.<ref name=cpr1405-08-271/> The Hampton Lovett property, however, was destined for Alice, Joan and Robert Harley's daughter, who married Sir Hamo Peshall.<ref name=hampton/>\n\nJoan was almost certainly some years older than Darras. It is not clear whether they had children, although Darras may have left a son named Roger.<ref name=mp/> Joan seems to have died around the turn of the century, with her properties largely leaving his control, prompting Darras to an active and fairly successful search for further sources of income in the years following.\n\nJoan's family, the Corbets of [[Moreton Corbet Castle]] were one of the rising gentry families, steadily increasing their estates and their influence.<ref name=landlords>Baugh and Elrington (1989), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol4/pp72-118#h3-0002 Domesday Book: 1300\u20131540: Landlords]</ref> However, they were not of the first rank, and both they and Darras were increasingly to seek advancement through the [[affinities|affinity]] of the FitzAlans, the [[Earls of Arundel]], who were supreme both economically and politically in Shropshire as well being among the greatest magnates in England.\n\n==The Corbet property disputes==\n[[File:Richard II King of England.jpg|thumb|Richard II, who intervened in and profited from the Corbet property disputes.]]\nJoan Corbet's brother, [[Roger Corbet (died 1395)|Sir Roger]], was preoccupied with family disputes over property, many of which involved Joan. Darras inevitably took his wife's side, sometimes bringing him into disrepute with the king and his government.\n\nRoger Corbet had two older brothers, Thomas and John, as well as a younger brother, John, and sisters, including Joan, who was possibly the eldest of the siblings.<ref name=visitation>[https://archive.org/stream/visitationshrop00britgoog#page/n188/mode/2up Visitation of Shropshire, p. 134.]</ref> Roger and Joan's parents, Robert and Elizabeth Corbet, had been concerned to keep the family estates together in a time of short life-spans and tortuous succession that affected many landowning families. As the eldest son, Thomas, predeceased his parents, the initial target had been to prevent the estates going to Elizabeth, his daughter, who had married [[John Ipstones|Sir John Ipstones]], a quarrelsome and sometimes violent man who served twice as MP for [[Staffordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Staffordshire]].<ref name=ips>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/ipstones-sir-john-1394 IPSTONES, Sir John (d.1394), of Blymhill, Staffs.] \u2013 Author: C.R.</ref> In the 1360s they initiated a complex series of property transactions, using the device of [[fine of lands]], and intended to keep the bulk of the Corbet lands effectively [[Fee tail|in tail]], favouring in particular Fulk and Roger.<ref name=corb241>[https://archive.org/stream/familyofcorbetit02corb#page/n117/mode/2up Corbet, p.241]</ref> The provisions of these fines were contested by Ipstones and Elizabeth from the outset.<ref name=ips/> However, after the death of Fulk in 1382, much worse followed. Some of the provisions were revealed as mutually-contradictory. Fulk's daughter and sole heiress, also Elizabeth, contested effective ownership of property that had been assigned for life, under a fine of 1363,<ref name=corb241/><ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol15/pp290-307 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Richard II, Volume 15, File 25, no. 742.]</ref> to Joan and her first husband, Sir Robert Harley of [[Willey, Shropshire|Willey]],<ref>Feet of Fines for Shropshire, CP 25/1/195/16, number 42, [http://www.medievalgenealogy.org.uk/fines/abstracts/CP_25_1_195_16.shtml Abstract] at Medieval Genealogy and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT4/CP25%281%29/CP_25_1_195/IMG_0325.htm Photograph of original document] at Anglo-American Legal Tradition.</ref> who died around 1370,<ref name=mp/> with the remainder to Fulk and the heirs of his body. These lands at [[Yockleton]], Shelve, [[Wentnor]] and Caus Forest, were all on the western side of Shropshire, close to the Welsh border and Joan and Harley leased them for the remainder of their lives to Sir Fulk for a rent of \u00a360 a year.<ref>Feet of Fines for Shropshire, CP 25/1/195/16, number 43, [http://www.medievalgenealogy.org.uk/fines/abstracts/CP_25_1_195_16.shtml Abstract] at Medieval Genealogy and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT4/CP25%281%29/CP_25_1_195/IMG_0326.htm Photograph of original document] at Anglo-American Legal Tradition.</ref> However, in 1367, they levied a fine to ensure estates passed to Roger in the event of Fulk's death.<ref>Feet of Fines for Shropshire, CP 25/1/195/17, number 12, [http://www.medievalgenealogy.org.uk/fines/abstracts/CP_25_1_195_17.shtml Abstract] at Medieval Genealogy and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT7/CP25%281%29/CP25_1_195_17/IMG_0014.htm Photograph of original document] at Anglo-American Legal Tradition.</ref> As Joan was still alive when Sir Fulk died in 1382, his daughter, Elizabeth, had a reasonable expectation of continuing to lease the lands under the fine of 1363. Joan, however, intended the lands to go immediately to her younger brother, Roger, according to the fine of 1367. She had reiterated the position after Harley's death in a new fine in 1376,<ref>Feet of Fines for Shropshire, CP 25/1/195/17, number 56, [http://www.medievalgenealogy.org.uk/fines/abstracts/CP_25_1_195_17.shtml Abstract] at Medieval Genealogy and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT7/CP25%281%29/CP25_1_195_17/IMG_0061.htm Photograph of original document] at Anglo-American Legal Tradition.</ref> and this position was assumed by the inquisition post mortem following Sir Fulk's death.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol15/pp290-307 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Richard II, Volume 15, File 25, no. 743.]</ref> There was a series of legal claims and counter-claims, with the Crown intervening to try to secure an [[escheat]] while the young Elizabeth was still a minor. However, Roger emerged victorious in 1385.<ref name=rog>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/corbet-sir-roger-1395 CORBET, Sir Roger (d.1395), of Moreton Corbet, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref>\n\nWhen Elizabeth, Fulk's daughter attained the age of majority in 1390, the entire issue was re-opened. Elizabeth was now married to John Mawddwy or de la Pole, lord of [[Dinas Mawddwy]], who vigorously pursued his wife's claim. Darras, now married to Joan, was just as vigorous in pursuing the interests of Joan and her brother, Roger. The king, [[Richard II of England|Richard II]] was informed that \"strife and debate\" was threatening the peace in Shropshire. It seems that violence had broken out at the beginning of June.<ref name=rog/> It is unlikely that Darras, already an experienced fighting man, was uninvolved, as on 7 June 1390 he was the first of those ordered to appear before King [[Richard II of England|Richard II]] and his Council in [[Court of Chancery|Chancery]] on 23 June, on pain of forfeiting 200 [[Mark (money)|marks]].<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarofclo04grea#page/142/mode/2up Calendar of Close Rolls, 1389\u20131392, p. 142.]</ref> [[Writ]]s in the same terms were issued to seven others, including Sir Roger Corbet and Malcolm de la Mare, Darras's business associate and recently MP for [[Herefordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Herefordshire]].<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/mare-malcolm-de-la-1399 MARE, Malcolm de la (d.c.1399), of Yatton and Little Hereford, Herefs. and Kidderminster, Worcs.] \u2013 Author: Charles Kightly.</ref> A further writ to the [[High Sheriff of Shropshire|Sheriff]] ordered him to compel their attendance.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarofclo04grea#page/142/mode/2up Calendar of Close Rolls, 1389\u20131392, p. 143.]</ref> However, the arrangements for the court appearance were changed and on 22 June writs were issued, this time naming Joan as well as John Darras, ordering the quarrelling gentry to appear instead at the next Shrewsbury [[assize]]s before [[Robert Charleton (justice)|Sir Robert Charleton]].<ref name=ccr8992-199>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarofclo04grea#page/198/mode/2up Calendar of Close Rolls, 1389\u20131392, p. 199.]</ref> Charleton and [[John Hill (died 1408)|Sir John Hill]] were authorised to take security for good behaviour from them and to familiarise themselves in advance with the complexities of the case.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarpatentr02blacgoog#page/n351/mode/2up Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1388\u20131392, p. 340.]</ref> The delay was accompanied by an order for Edward Acton, the Shropshire escheator personally to take the disputed estates into the king's hands, pending a resolution.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarofclo04grea#page/202/mode/2up Calendar of Close Rolls, 1389\u20131392, p. 202.]</ref> After further delays, which were very profitable to king who was pocketing the proceeds, an agreement was reached and on 25 April 1391 the escheator was ordered to cease meddling with the estates.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarofclo04grea#page/256/mode/2up Calendar of Close Rolls, 1389\u20131392, p. 256.]</ref> It seems they were assigned to the Mawddwys, and later to their daughter Elizabeth, who married [[Hugh Burgh]], a future MP for Shropshire and [[Lord High Treasurer of Ireland]]. However, it is likely that Joan and Darras received the consolation of regular rent from them.<ref name=mp/> While losing the case was a blow to prestige, leasing was actually the preferred option among Shropshire landowners like the Corbets, who had been renting out [[demesne]] lands to secure a regular income in uncertain times.<ref>Baugh and Elrington (1989), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol4/pp72-118#h3-0008 Domesday Book: 1300\u20131540 \u2013 The leasing of the demesnes.]</ref> It is also possible that there was a large sum for Joan and John Darras at the ouset of the tenancy: the [[Recognizance]]s preserved in the county archives show that in September 1391 ''John de Mowche'' (presumably a rendering of Mawddwy, which is given as ''Mouthe''<ref name=ccr8992-199/> in the [[Close Rolls]]) undertook to pay John Darras 1000 marks at Easter 1392.<ref>[http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/getrecord/CCA_X3365_67_45v/ Shropshire Archives Document Reference: 3365/67/45v, Recognizances 1391\u20131392], at Discovering Shropshire's History.</ref>\n{{chart top|Family tree to illustrate the Corbet property disputes}}\nBased on pedigrees derived from the Heraldic Visitation of Shropshire, 1623,<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/visitationshrop00britgoog#page/n188/mode/2up Visitation of Shropshire, p. 134-38.]</ref> and in Augusta Corbet's family history,<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/familyofcorbetit02corb#page/368/mode/2up Corbet, facing p. 368.]</ref> supplemented by more recent information from the History of Parliament Online.\n{{tree chart/start}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | | | |Kat |-|Rob1|v|Mat| | | | |Kat=Katherine, daughter of John [[Baron Strange#1299 creation|le Strange]] of [[Knockin]] and [[Myddle]]|Rob1=Sir Robert Corbet (died 1300) of [[Moreton Corbet|Moreton Toret]] and [[Wattlesborough Castle|Wattlesborough]]|Mat=Matilda (died 1309), daughter John de Arundel}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|.|}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | |Am|v| Tom | |Fulk| |John| | | | | | | | | |Am=Amice|Tom=Thomas Corbet (died 1310) of Moreton Toret and Wattlesborough|Fulk=Fulk Corbet, Canon of [[Lichfield Cathedral]]|John=John Corbet}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | | |!}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | |Rob|v|Liz||| | | | | | | | |Rob=Sir RobertCorbet (1304\u201375) of Moreton Toret and Wattlesborough|Liz=Elizabeth, daughter of Fulk, 1st [[Baron Strange of Blackmere]]}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | |,|-|-|-|^|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{tree chart|Harl|v|Joan|-|Dar|!| |Fulk|v|Liz2| | |!| | |Rog|v|Marg1|Fulk=Sir Fulk Corbet (died 1382) of Moreton Corbet|Liz2=Elizabeth|Harl=Robert de Harley|Joan=Joan Corbet|Dar=John Darras of Sidbury and [[Neenton]]|Rog=[[Roger Corbet (died 1395)]]|Marg1=Margaret Erdington (died 1395)|}}\n{{tree chart| |,|-|'| | | | | | | |!| | | | |!| | | | | |!| | | | | |!|}}\n{{tree chart| |!| | | |Liz1|v|Tom1| | | | |!| | | | |Marg1|v|Tom2|!|Liz1=Elizabeth|Tom1=Sir Thomas Corbet (died c.1359)|Marg1=Margaret Corbet|Tom2=Sir Thomas Erdington (died 1395) of [[Erdington]]}}\n{{tree chart| |!| | | | | | |!| | | | | | | |!| | | | | | | |!| | | |)|-|-|-|.| | |}}\n{{tree chart|Al|-|Hamon||Liz1|-|Ip||Liz2|-|Maw| |Tom| |Rob| |Rog|Al=Alicia Harley|Ip=Sir [[John Ipstones]] (d.1394) of [[Blymhill]]|Hamon=Sir Hamon Peshale (died c.1398)|Liz1=Elizabeth Corbet|Maw=John de la Pole of [[Dinas Mawddwy]]|Liz2=Elizabeth Corbet, heiress to Wattlesborough|Tom=Sir Thomas Erdington (c.1371\u20131434) of Erdington|Rob=[[Robert Corbet (died 1420)|Robert Corbet (1383\u20131420)]] of Moreton Corbet|Rog=[[Roger Corbet (died 1430)]] of [[Shrewsbury]]}}\n{{tree chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==Political and military career==\n[[File:A Chronicle of England - Page 328 - Arundel, Gloucester, Nottingham, Derby, and Warwick, Before the King.jpg|thumb|left|The Lords Appellant confront Richard II. In this Victorian illustration, Arundel is portrayed on the left, wearing his arms of a gold rampant lion on a red ground.]]\n[[File:Henry IV Coronation.jpg|thumb|Coronation of Henry IV.]]\n[[File:Owain Glyndwr Siegel 2.jpg|thumb|left|Seal of [[Owain Glynd\u0175r]], proclaimed [[Prince of Wales]] at [[Corwen]] in 1400. Darras earned the approval of both Arundel and the king by serving repeatedly against the Welsh rebellion.]]\n[[File:JohnTalbotEarlOfShrewsbury.jpg|thumb|Effigy of John Talbot, later Earl of Shrewsbury, in [[St Alkmund's Church, Whitchurch]]. A distinguished campaigner in the Hundred Years' War, Talbot seems to have gained control of Darras's estates.]]\n\nDarras formally enlisted as an esquire in the retinue of [[Richard FitzAlan, 11th Earl of Arundel]] in 1387.<ref name=mp/> Among others to do so, and probably thereby form a political and personal bond with Arundel, was Thomas Whitton,<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/whitton-thomas-1411 WHITTON, Thomas (d.1411), of Whitton near Burford, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger.</ref> a long-term associate of Darras. At this point Arundel was one of the [[Lords Appellant]], a leader of the opposition to Richard II's favourites and his policy of peace with France. Darras served with him in a naval campaign against the French, which culminated in a significant victory off [[Margate]]. As a client of the earl, and in association with two other members of his affinity, [[John Burley]] and Fulk Sprenghose, Darras was made trustee of estates belonging to Richard, 4th Lord Talbot, who was married to Arundel's niece, Ankaret le Strange of Blackmere.<ref name=ls288>[https://archive.org/stream/lestrangerecords00lond#page/288/mode/2up Le Strange, p. 288.]</ref> In 1393 he represented his county in the parliament that began on 20 January and lasted about three weeks. His fellow MP was Sir William Hugford, who was closely associated with John le Strange, 6th Baron Strange of Knockin: although powerful, the 11th Earl of Arundel seems to have been much happier to share influence than was to prove the case with his son.\n\nArundel was executed in Richard II's purge of 1397. The inquisition into the earl's Shropshire lands listed the numerous small grants of land he had made to his affinity and others whom he needed to cultivate. One of these was a small estate at [[Gretton, Shropshire]], held by Darras and worth 40 [[shilling]]s annually.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=inu.30000047592476;view=1up;seq=124 Calendar of Inquisitions Miscellaneous (Chancery), 1392\u20131399, p. 114.]</ref> It seems, however, that Darras also had good contacts in the Lancastrian affinity. Earlier in the year, together with Edward Whitton, Henry Wynnesbury, and Fulk Pembridge, Darras was involved in some transaction that required each to pay \u00a3200 to [[Walter Blount (soldier)|Sir Walter Blount]],<ref>[http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/getrecord/CCA_X3365_67_47/ Shropshire Archives Document Reference: 3365/67/47, Recognizances 1396\u20131397], at Discovering Shropshire's History.</ref> An important participant in [[John of Gaunt]]'s military adventures abroad and his leading representative in the Midlands.<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/blount-sir-walter-1403 BLOUNT, Sir Walter (d.1403), of Barton Blount, Derbys.] \u2013 Author: C.R.</ref>\n\nWhen John of Gaunt's son and dispossessed successor, [[Henry IV of England|Henry Bolingbroke]] arrived in England to challenge Richard in 1399, the Arundels rallied to the cause of the [[House of Lancaster]], formerly their bitter enemies: the dead earl's son, [[Thomas FitzAlan, 12th Earl of Arundel]], and brother, [[Thomas Arundel]], the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], became mainstays of the government of Bolingbroke, who came to the throne as Henry IV. Darras seems to have good connections with both parts of the victorious coalition and from this point he contrived to remain in royal favour, albeit sometimes with difficulty. He was made keeper for life of [[Morfe Forest|Morfe]] and Shirlet, areas of [[Royal forest]] on either side of the [[Severn]] in Shropshire, by [[letters patent]] of 4 November 1399.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarpatentr16offigoog#page/n75/mode/2up Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1399\u20131401, p. 64.]</ref> After his loyal service against the [[Glynd\u0175r Rising]] in Wales, a major preoccupation of both Arundel and the king,  further letters patent in February 1407, described Darras as the \"king's esquire,\" and confirmed that the office was indeed a reward for his military service and permitted him to appoint a ranger as a deputy to act in his absences.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=308 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 296.]</ref>\n\nIt was probably his connection with the FitzAlans that assured his appointment as [[High Sheriff of Shropshire]] for 1401-2. Before he took up the shrievalty, his friend [[John Cornwall (c.1366-1414)|Sir John Cornwall]], a former sheriff and also a former retainer of John of Gaunt, was accused of cattle rustling at Wytheford (also rendered Withiford) in Shropshire.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/collectionsforhi15staf#page/n243/mode/2up Collections for a History of Staffordshire, volume 15, p. 102.]</ref> Cornwall counted as family, as he was a grandson of Fulk, 1st Baron Strange of Blackmere, and so a first cousin of Darras's wife.<ref name=cornwall/> However, the case affected the king's interests, as the plaintiffs, who were demanding \u00a3100, alleged that their cattle had already been taken into the custody of the county escheator when Cornwall removed them.<ref name=chs15-103>[https://archive.org/stream/collectionsforhi15staf#page/n245/mode/2up Collections for a History of Staffordshire, volume 15, p. 103.]</ref> In April 1402 Darras was one of four local gentry who stood surety at Westminster for Cornwall that he would keep the peace,<ref>[https://www.familysearch.org/library/books/records/item/581522-redirection Calendar of Close Rolls, 1399\u20131402, p. 555.]</ref> an act that potentially created a conflict of interest. However, the plaintiffs alleged that Darras went much further. When the case was moved to the Shrewsbury assizes by a writ of [[nisi prius]] it was claimed that Darras allowed Cornwall to select the jurors.<ref name=chs15-103/> The jury was dismissed and Darras was ordered to summon a new panel for the next assizes. Darras was also the returning officer when Cornwall was elected to Parliament.<ref name=mp/> Cornwall was a man of considerable prestige, claiming descent from [[John, King of England|King John]],<ref name=cornwall>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/cornwall-sir-john-1366-1414 CORNWALL, Sir John (c.1366\u20131414), of Kinlet, Salop.] \u2013 Authors: J.S. Roskell/L.S. Woodger</ref> but an unstable and dangerous associate, who was to attract constant accusations of violence and intimidation.\n\nThe 12th Earl exercised a much tighter grip on power in the region than his father, dominating parliamentary representation at every election. It was Darras's turn again in 1404, when he was sent to Parliament with John Burley, another lawyer who worked mainly for the Fitzalans and who had fought alongside Darras in the naval campaign of 1387.<ref>Roskell et al,  [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/burley-john-i-141516 BURLEY, John I (d.1415/16), of Broncroft in Corvedale, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L.S. Woodger</ref> Burley had also held the wardship of [[Robert Corbet (died 1420)|Robert Corbet]], the heir of Sir Roger and nephew of Joan.\n\nDarras could not entirely escape penalty when in 1406 he and Roger Willey bought two properties held [[Tenant-in-chief|''in capita'']] without obtaining royal approval: a quarter [[carucate]] of land at [[Worfield]] and a [[moiety title|moiety]] of the [[forester]]ship of Morfe. However, a pardon was granted on 15 November for a mere 6s. 8d.<ref name=cpr1405-08-271>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=283 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 271.]</ref> Darras and Willey then resold both properties to Richard Parlour, a [[Burgess (title)|burgess]] of Bridgnorth, again without asking permission: Parlour was compelled to sue and pay for pardon in 1408, after Darras's death.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=438 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 426.]</ref><ref>Roskell et al,  [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/parlour-richard PARLOUR, Richard, of Bridgnorth, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L.S. Woodger</ref>\n\nIn 1407 Darras, together with Robert Corbet, [[Roger Corbet (died 1430)|Roger Corbet]], nephews of Joan, and William Ryman of Sussex \u2013 all of Arundel's affinity \u2013 were among a group of Shropshire gentry who granted a [[burgage]] in [[Shrewsbury]], known as Ireland Hall, to [[Shrewsbury Abbey]] for pious purposes.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=351 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 339.]</ref><ref name=\"historyofparliamentonline.org\">Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/corbet-robert-1383-1420 CORBET, Robert (1383\u20131420), of Moreton Corbet, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref> The licence to accept this gift, which cost the abbey the considerable sum of 10 marks, was granted on 20 July. The younger Corbets had enlisted with Arundel about two years previously and were to acquire sinister reputations for violence and lawlessness.<ref name=\"historyofparliamentonline.org\"/> They and their uncle probably granted Ireland Hall on behalf of Arundel. The abbot of Shrewsbury, [[Thomas Prestbury]], was a client of Archbishop Arundel, the earl's uncle, and had been imprisoned in 1399 for preaching against the government of Richard II.<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id=107122 |title=Prestbury, Thomas |last=Heale |first=Martin}}</ref> Later in the year Darras attended the election of [[knights of the shire]], witnessing the return of Cornwall and [[David Holbache]], a prominent lawyer and a close associate of Arundel.<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/holbache-david-1422 HOLBACHE, David (d.c.1422), of Dudleston and Oswestry, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref> This was Darras's last important public appearance.\n\n==Death and aftermath==\n\nDarras hanged himself at Neenton, probably during March 1408. The evidence for the date is a commission from the king, issued on 30 March, to four Shropshire gentry to investigate possible concealment of the deceased's goods,<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=497 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 485.]</ref> which as a suicide, escheated to the Crown. A formal order for the escheator to take his estates into the hands of the king was issued on 24 May.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendaroffinero13greauoft#page/120/mode/2up Calendar of Fine Rolls, 1405\u20131413, p. 120.]</ref> His holdings would normally have reverted to their feudal overlords but the young [[Edmund Mortimer, 5th Earl of March]] was the centre of plots against Henry IV and much of his property was temporarily or permanently forfeit.\n\nConsiderable confusion and disputes seem to have followed Darras's unusual and untimely death. At Sidbury the advowson was contested. On 6 July, as a new rector was needed at Sidbury, Henry St George acted as patron, presenting William Walkebache. On 11 August, however, [[John Talbot, 1st Earl of Shrewsbury|John Talbot, 6th Baron Furnivall]], also acting as patron and described as lord of Sidbury, presented Walter Lawrence.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork21unknuoft#page/n189/mode/2up Registrum Roberti Mascall, p. 173.]</ref> Talbot, the young son of Richard, Lord Talbot, and Ankaret le Strange,<ref name=ls288/> was to emerge as Arundel's main political rival in the county, prepared to fight force with force.<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/constituencies/shropshire Shropshire] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref> On 23 August Bishop [[Robert Mascall]] was issued with a writ probiting him from admitting anyone to Sidbury until the issue was decided.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork21unknuoft#page/n83/mode/2up Registrum Roberti Mascall, p. 66.]</ref> The following April the bishop himself presented William Whitehead.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork21unknuoft#page/n191/mode/2up Registrum Roberti Mascall, p. 174.]</ref> By August 1409 Whitehead had resigned and Talbot presented his nominee for a second time,<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork21unknuoft#page/n191/mode/2up Registrum Roberti Mascall, p. 175.]</ref> apparently triumphant in the struggle to take over Darras's lands and rights. The same pattern is shown at Linley, which probably fell into his hands, as his widow, [[Margaret Beauchamp, Countess of Shrewsbury]], held half the manor as a jointure property after his death.<ref name=linley/>\n\nSimilar confusions arose over Darras's keepership of Morfe and Shirlet. Soon after Darras's death the king conferred the office on Sir John Cornwall, removing it from Nicholas Gerard, on the grounds that the office had not been vacant when Gerard acquired it,<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=436 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 424.]</ref> although the story behind the recital of facts is mysterious. There were several Shrewsbury business men named Nicholas Gerard in the 14th century<ref>[http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/search/?q=nicholas+gerard&cb_submit=Search Shropshire Archives search for Nicholas Gerard] at Discovering Shropshire's History.</ref> and this seems to be the one served as MP in 1399<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/gerard-nicholas-1421 GERARD, Nicholas (d.1421), of Shrewsbury, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref> and bailiff in 1412.<ref>[http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/getrecord/CCA_XSB_C_1_1_1_24/ Shropshire Archives Document Reference: 3365/67/12v] at Discovering Shropshire's History.</ref> Cornwall soon proved himself tyrannical in office. By March 1410 the king was ordering Arundel and his legal team, John Burley, David Holbache and Thomas Young,<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/young-%28yonge%29-thomas-i YOUNG, (YONGE), Thomas I, of Sibdon Carwood, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref> together with Lord Furnival, to investigate breaches of customary manorial and grazing rights at [[Worfield]] in Morff Forest,<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079570;view=1up;seq=194 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1408\u20131413, p. 182.]</ref> made by Arundel's brother-in-law, [[William de Beauchamp, 1st Baron Bergavenny]]. Cornwall was clearly quite reckless in his depredations, as there had been similar complaints from William Ferrers, 5th [[Baron Ferrers of Groby]]. Joan Beauchamp, Arundel's sister continued to complain about Cornwall into 1412, after she was widowed,<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079570;view=1up;seq=389 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1408\u20131413, p. 377.]</ref> prompting a further commission of inquiry by the same team. The following year the king received similar complaints from John Marshall, Dean of the [[Church of St. Mary Magdalene, Bridgnorth|royal free chapel at Bridgnorth]]<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079570;view=1up;seq=489 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1408\u20131413, p. 477.]</ref> It seems that, before sending in Arundel's lawyers to investigate, the king secured Cornwall's resignation and on 13 February 1413 installed Roger Willey, Darras's old business partner, as keeper in his place.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079570;view=1up;seq=477 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1408\u20131413, p. 465.]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bastard feudalism]]\n*[[Corbet family]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n\n* {{cite web |url=http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/searching-the-archives/ |title=Archives |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=Discovering Shropshire's History |publisher=Shropshire County Council |access-date=1 July 2016 |quote=}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Capes |editor1-first=William W. |editor1-link= |date=1916 |title=Registrum Johannis Trefnant, Episcopi Herefordensis|volume=20|url=https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork14unknuoft#page/n237/mode/2up |location=London |publisher=Canterbury and York Society |page= |isbn= |access-date= 29 June 2016 }} at Internet Archive.\n* {{cite book |author1-last=Corbet |author1-first=Augusta Elizabeth Brickdale |date= |title=The Family of Corbet; its Life and Times |volume=2 |url=https://archive.org/details/familyofcorbetit02corb |location=London |publisher= St. Catherine Press |page= |isbn= |access-date= 3 October 2013 }} at Internet Archive.\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Baugh |editor1-first=G. C. |editor2-last=Elrington |editor2-first=C. R.|date=1989 |title= A History of the County of Shropshire |volume=4|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol4 |location=London |publisher=British History Online |page= |isbn= |access-date= 28 November 2013 }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Currie |editor1-first=C. R. J.  |authors=A. P. Baggs, G. C. Baugh, D. C. Cox, Jessie McFall, P. A. Stamper|date=1998 |title= Linley|work= A History of the County of Shropshire |volume=10|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol10/pp348-354 |location=London |publisher=British History Online |page= |isbn= |access-date= 20 December 2013 }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Dawes |editor1-first=M.C.B. |date=1935 |title= Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem: Edward III|volume=11 |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol11 |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 28 June 2016 }} at [[British History Online]].\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Dawes |editor1-first=M.C.B. |editor2-last=Wood |editor2-first=A.C. |editor3-last=Gifford |editor3-first=D. H. |date=1970 |title= Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem: Richard II |volume=15 |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol15 |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 30 June 2016 }} at [[British History Online]].\n* {{cite web |url=http://aalt.law.uh.edu/CP25(1)a.html |title=Feet of Fines |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=Anglo-American Legal Tradition |publisher=University of Houston |access-date=30 June 2016 |quote=}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.gasconrolls.org/en/ |title=The Gascon Rolls Project (1317-1468) |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=29 June 2016 |quote=}} \n* {{cite book |author1-first=Patrick |author1-last=Hanks |author2-first=Flavia |author2-last=Hodges |author3-first=A.D. |author3-last=Mills |author4-first=Adrian |author4-last=Room |date= |title= The Oxford Names Companion |year=2002 |volume= |url= |location=Oxford |publisher= OUP |page= |isbn=0-19-860561-7  }}\n* {{Cite ODNB|id=107122 |title=Prestbury, Thomas |last=Heale |first=Martin}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/rchme/heref/vol1/pp90-144 |title=Hereford |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=1931 |website= An Inventory of the Historical Monuments in Herefordshire, Volume 1, South west |publisher=HMSO/ British History Online|access-date=2 July 2016 |quote=}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1053776 |title=Church of Holy Trinity |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2015 |website=Historic England |publisher= |access-date=3 July 2016 |quote=}} \n* {{cite book |author1-last=Le Strange |author1-first=Hamon |editor1-link= |date=1916 |title= Le Strange Records |volume= |url=https://archive.org/details/lestrangerecords00lond |location=London |publisher=Longman, Green |page= |isbn= |access-date= 2 July 2016 }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Maxwell Lyte |editor1-first=H. C. |editor1-link=Henry Maxwell Lyte |date=1922 |title= Calendar of the Close Rolls, Preserved in the Public Record Office: Richard II, 1389\u20131392 |volume=4 |url=https://archive.org/details/calendarofclo04grea |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 30 June 2016 }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Maxwell Lyte |editor1-first=H. C. |editor1-link=Henry Maxwell Lyte |date=1927 |title= Calendar of the Close Rolls, Preserved in the Public Record Office: Henry IV, 1399\u20131402 |volume=1 |url=https://www.familysearch.org/library/books/records/item/581522-redirection |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 1 July 2016 }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Maxwell Lyte |editor1-first=H. C. |editor1-link=Henry Maxwell Lyte |date=1933 |title= Calendar of the Fine Rolls, Preserved in the Public Record Office: Henry IV, 1405\u20131413 |volume=13 |url=https://archive.org/details/calendaroffinero13greauoft |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 2 July 2016 }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Maxwell Lyte |editor1-first=H. C. |editor1-link=Henry Maxwell Lyte |date=1902 |title= Calendar of the Patent Rolls, Preserved in the Public Record Office: Richard II, 1388\u20131392|volume=4|url=https://archive.org/details/calendarpatentr02blacgoog |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 28 June 2016 }} at Internet Archive.\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Maxwell Lyte |editor1-first=H. C. |editor1-link=Henry Maxwell Lyte |date=1903 |title= Calendar of the Patent Rolls, Preserved in the Public Record Office: Henry IV, 1399\u20131401|volume=1|url=https://archive.org/details/calendarpatentr16offigoog |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 1 July 2016 }} at Internet Archive.\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Maxwell Lyte |editor1-first=H. C. |editor1-link=Henry Maxwell Lyte |date=1907 |title= Calendar of the Patent Rolls, Preserved in the Public Record Office: Henry IV, 1405\u20131408|volume=3|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=5 |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 1 July 2016 }} at Hathi Trust.\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Maxwell Lyte |editor1-first=H. C. |editor1-link=Henry Maxwell Lyte |date=1909 |title= Calendar of the Patent Rolls, Preserved in the Public Record Office: Henry IV, 1408\u20131413|volume=4|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079570;view=1up;seq=5 |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 3 July 2016 }} at Hathi Trust.\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Maxwell Lyte |editor1-first=H. C. |editor1-link=Henry Maxwell Lyte |date=1906 |title=Inquisitions and Assessments relating to Feudal Aids, A.D. 1284-1431|volume=4|url=https://archive.org/details/inquisitionsasse04grea |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 28 June 2016 }} at Internet Archive.\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol3/pp153-158 | editor1-last=Page |editor1-first=William Henry |editor1-link=William Henry Page |editor2-last=Willis-Bund |editor2-first= John William |editor2-link=John William Willis-Bund |title=Parishes: Hampton Lovett |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |year=1913 |work=A History of the County of Worcester |volume=3 |accessdate= 19 December 2013 }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4|editor1-last=Page |editor1-first=William Henry |editor1-link=William Henry Page |editor2-last=Willis-Bund |editor2-first= John William |editor2-link=John William Willis-Bund |title= A History of the County of Worcester |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |year=1913 |work=A History of the County of Worcester |volume=4 |accessdate= 19 December 2013 }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Parry |editor1-first=Joseph Henry |editor1-link= |date=1915 |title=Registrum Johannis Gilbert, Episcopi Herefordensis|volume=18|url=https://archive.org/details/canterburyyork18unknuoft |location=London |publisher=Canterbury and York Society |page= |isbn= |access-date= 29 June 2016 }} at Internet Archive.\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Parry |editor1-first=Joseph Henry |editor1-link= |date=1918 |title=Registrum Robert Mascall, Episcopi Herefordensis|volume=21|url=https://archive.org/details/canterburyyork21unknuoft |location=London |publisher=Canterbury and York Society |page= |isbn= |access-date= 2 July 2016 }} at Internet Archive.\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.medievalgenealogy.org.uk/fines/shropshire.shtml |title=Feet of Fines: Shropshire |editor1-last=Philips |editor1-first=Chris  |date=2006 |website=Notes on Medieval Genealogy |publisher= |access-date=30 June 2016 |quote=}}\n* {{cite book |editor=Public Record Office |editor1-first= |editor1-link= |date=1963 |title= Calendar of Inquisitions Miscellaneous (Chancery), 1392\u20131399 |volume=6 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=inu.30000047592476;view=1up;seq=5 |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 1 July 2016 }} at [[Hathi Trust]].\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Roskell |editor1-first=J. S. |editor2-last=Clark |editor2-first=L. |editor3-last=Rawcliffe |editor3-first=C. |date=1993 |title= History of the Parliament, 1386\u20131421: Constituencies |volume=|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/research/constituencies/1386-1421 |location=London |publisher= History of Parliament Online |page= |isbn= |access-date= 27 November 2013 }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Roskell |editor1-first=J. S. |editor2-last=Clark |editor3-first=L. |editor3-last=Rawcliffe |editor2-first=C. |date=1993 |title= History of the Parliament, 1386\u20131421: Members |volume=|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/research/members/members-1386-1421 |location=London |publisher= History of Parliament Online |page= |isbn= |access-date= 27 November 2013 }}\n* {{cite book |editor1=A. E. Stamp |editor2=J. B. W. Chapman |editor3=Cyril Flower |editor4=M. C. B. Dawes |editor5=L. C. Hector |date=1952 |title= Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem: Edward III|volume=14 |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol14 |location=London |publisher=HMSO |page= |isbn= |access-date= 28 June 2016 }} at [[British History Online]].\n* {{cite book |last1= Tresswell |first1=Robert |last2=Vincent |first2=Augustine |author-link2=Augustine Vincent |editor1-last=Grazebrook |editor1-first=George |editor2-last=Rylands |editor2-first=John Paul|editor-link2=John Paul Rylands |date=1889 |title= The visitation of Shropshire, taken in the year 1623 |volume=1 |url=https://archive.org/details/visitationshrop00britgoog |location=London |publisher=Harleian Society |page= |isbn= |access-date= 27 November 2013 }} at Internet Archive.\n* {{cite book |editor= William Salt Archaeological Society |title= Collections for a History of Staffordshire |volume=15  |location=London |publisher=Harrison |year=1894 |url=https://archive.org/details/collectionsforhi15staf |accessdate=1 July 2016}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Wrottesley |editor1-first=George |editor1-link=George Wrottesley|date=1905|title=Pedigrees from the Plea Rolls|volume=|url=https://archive.org/details/pedigreesfromple00wrotrich |work= |location=London |publisher=Public Record Office |pages= |isbn= |access-date= 28 June 2016 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{succession box \n| title=Member of Parliament for [[Shropshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Shropshire]] \n| before= Sir Hugh Cheyne\n| before2= [[Roger Corbet (died 1395)|Sir Roger Corbet]]\n| with= Sir William Hugford\n| years= 1393\n| after= Sir Adam Peshale\n| after2= Sir William Hugford\n}}\n{{succession box \n| title=Member of Parliament for Shropshire \n| before= [[John Burley]]\n| before2= George Hawkestone\n| with= John Burley\n| years= October 1404\n| after= [[David Holbache]]\n| after2= Thomas Whitton\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darras, John}}\n[[Category:1408 deaths]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Shropshire]]\n[[Category:English landowners]]\n[[Category:Medieval English knights]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1393]]\n[[Category:English MPs October 1404]]\n[[Category:People from Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox MP\n| honorific-prefix =Sir\n| name = John Darras\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Shropshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Shropshire]]\n| parliament = English\n| majority = \n| predecessor1 = Sir Hugh Cheyne, Sir [[Roger Corbet (died 1395)]]\n| alongside1= Sir William Hugford\n| successor1 = Sir Adam Peshale, Sir William Hugford\n| term_start1 = 20 January 1393\n| term_end1 = 10 February 1393\n| predecessor2 = [[John Burley]], George Hawkestone\n| alongside2= John Burley\n| successor2 = [[David Holbache]], Thomas Whitton\n| term_start2 = 6 October 1404 \t\n| term_end2 = 13 November 1404\n| birth_date = c. 1355\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = March 1408\n| death_place = [[Neenton]]\n| death_cause=Suicide by hanging\n| nationality = English\n| spouse =Joan Corbet (died c. 1400)\n| party = \n| relations =Sir Roger Corbet (brother-in-law)\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation =Landowner, soldier.\n| profession =\n| religion =Roman Catholic\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n}}\n'''John Darras''' (c.1355\u20131408) was an English soldier, politician and landowner, who fought in the [[Hundred Years' War]] and against the [[Glynd\u0175r Rising]]. A client of the FitzAlan [[Earls of Arundel]], he served them in war and peace, helping consolidate their domination of his native county of [[Shropshire]]. He represented [[Shropshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Shropshire]] twice in the [[House of Commons of England]]. He died by his own hand.\n{{Location map+\n |Shropshire\n|relief=yes\n| width=500\n| float=right\n|border=\n|caption=Relief map of Shropshire and surrounding counties to show estates held or claimed by John Darras (blue dots) and his wife, Joan Corbet (red dots). Estates disputed with the Mawddwys are shown in pink.\n|alt=a map of Shropshire pinpointing estates connected with John Darras and Joan Corbet.\n|places=\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.3640|long=-2.3153|label=Ribbesford|mark = blue pog.svg|position=right|link=Ribbesford}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.3379|long=-2.3957|label=Rock|mark = blue pog.svg|position=top|link=Rock, Worcestershire}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5824|long=-2.4631|label=Linley|mark=blue pog.svg |link=}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.4876|long=-2.5359|label=Neenton|mark=blue pog.svg|position=left|link=Neenton}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.469|long=-2.4669|label=Sidbury|mark=blue pog.svg|position=right|link=}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.6851|long=-2.896|label=Yockleton|mark=pink pog.svg|position=left|link=Yockleton}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5283|long=-2.9099|label=Wentnor|mark=pink pog.svg|position=left|link=Wentnor}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.66|long=-2.9794|label=Caus|mark=pink pog.svg|position=right|link=Caus Castle}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5850|long=-2.981|label=Shelve|mark=pink pog.svg|position=right|link=}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5339|long=-2.345|label=Morfe Forest|label_size=80|mark=Legenda rezerwat scisly.svg|marksize=25 |position=right|link=Morfe Forest}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5786|long=-2.5043|label=Shirlett Forest|label_size=80|mark=Legenda rezerwat scisly.svg|marksize=25 |position=left|link=}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5323|long=-2.4193|label=Bridgnorth|label_size=110 |mark=Burg.svg|marksize=20 |position=left|link=Bridgnorth}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.7108|long=-2.7495|label=Shrewsbury|label_size=110 |mark=Burg.svg|marksize=20 |position=right|link=Shrewsbury}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.6095|long=-2.5979|label=Harley |mark=red pog.svg |position=top|link=Harley, Shropshire}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.5493|long=-2.7137|label=Gretton |mark=red pog.svg |position=left|link=Gretton, Shropshire}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.6036|long=-2.6468|label=Kenley |mark=red pog.svg |position=left|link=Kenley}}\n  {{Location map~ |Shropshire |lat=52.2884|long=-2.1647|label=Hampton Lovett |mark=red pog.svg |position=left|link=Hampton Lovett}}\n}}\n\n==Background and early life==\nJohn Darras was the son of:<ref name=mp>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/darras-john-1355-1408 DARRAS, John (c.1355\u20131408), of Sidbury and Neenton, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref>\n:*'''Ralph Darras''' or Daras of [[Neenton]]. The Darras family were not large landowners but part of the emerging [[landed gentry]]. Ralph Darras held the manors of Neenton and Sidbury,<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol14/pp348-350 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Edward III, Addendum to Vol. X, no. 355.]</ref> both south-west of [[Bridgnorth]] in Shropshire, part of the [[Welsh Marches]]. Although most such families were of [[Anglo-Normans|Anglo-Norman]] origin, Darras, originally rendered de Arras,<ref name=linley/> or d'Arras, signifies origins in [[Arras]], historically the chief town of [[Artois]] in Flanders.<ref>Hanks et al, p. 160</ref> It is generally rendered Daras in late medieval documents.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/inquisitionsasse04grea#page/246/mode/2up Feudal Aids, volume 4, p. 246.]</ref>\n:*'''Joan Forcer''', daughter and coheiress of Thomas Forcer. Joan, together with her sisters Burga and Elizabeth, was also an heiress of Sir Henry Ribbesford of [[Ribbesford]], near [[Bewdley]] in Worcestershire, who was the brother of their grandmother, Avice or Hawise le Forcer.<ref name=rib>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp297-317#h3-0003 Ribbesford with the Borough of Bewdley \u2013 Manors]</ref>\n\nRalph Darras, John's father, died in December 1461, when John was only about seven years of age.<ref name=ipq11-270/> This was during the second major outbreak of the [[Black Death]] in Shropshire,<ref>Baugh and Elrington (1989), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol4/pp72-118#anchorn23 Domesday Book: 1300\u20131540, note anchor 23.]</ref> although there is no record of Ralph Darras's cause of death. The plague brought great economic shifts alongside the human cost. Shropshire [[Inquisition post mortem|inquisitions post mortem]] taken during the plague outbreak show that land lay uncultivated and some landowners struggled to pay even very modest rents,<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol11/pp194-206 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Edward III, Volume 11, File 166, no. 233.]</ref> and some estates were considered worthless.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol11/pp400-414 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Edward III, Volume 11, File 179, no. 537.]</ref> While the majority of the rural population was placed at an advantage by labour shortages, landlords were forced to relax conditions imposed on tenants and to buy in labour.<ref>Baugh and Elrington (1989), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol4/pp72-118#anchorn196 Domesday Book: 1300\u20131540: Demesne agriculture, note anchor 196-199.]</ref> This is the economic and agrarian background to John Darras's lifelong struggles to consolidate and extend his estates and to find additional sources of income, mainly through business and military service.\n\nJohn Darras's mother, Joan, must also have died in his childhood. He fought legal battles to secure her inheritance, but alongside his aunts, not his mother.\n\n==Landowner==\n[[File:Sidbury church - geograph.org.uk - 395182.jpg|thumb|Holy Trinity church at [[Sidbury, Shropshire]]. The nave was already old by the time of Darras, as it was built in the 12th century, although the whole building underwent restoration in 1881.<ref>[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1053776 Church of Holy Trinity] at [[Historic England]].</ref>]]\n[[File:Ribbesford Church - geograph.org.uk - 703615.jpg|thumb|St Leonard's church at Ribbesford. The manor was the focus of early attempts by Darras to enlarge his holdings. There has been a small church on the site since about 1100. It was enlarged from the early 15th century, with modifications including the present nave.<ref>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42900#s5 Ribbesford with the Borough of Bewdley \u2013 Churches]</ref><ref>[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1115135 Church of St Leonard] at Historic England.</ref>]]\nThe inquisition following his father's death, taken at [[Bridgnorth]] on 19 March 1362, shows that the main estates Darras inherited from his father were the manors of Sidbury and Neenton, which were held of [[Edmund Mortimer, 3rd Earl of March]].<ref name=ipq11-270>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol11/pp215-230 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Edward III, Volume 11, File 168, no. 270.]</ref> in return for providing a [[hobelar]] (a light cavalryman mounted on a [[Irish Hobby|hobby]]) for [[Wigmore Castle]] when there was war in the [[Welsh Marches]]. There were also a few other small, scattered holdings, notably a third of the manor of Linley, held of the [[Wenlock Priory|Prior of Wenlock]].<ref name=linley>Currie et al, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol10/pp348-354#h3-0002 Linley \u2013 Manor and other estates.]</ref> This was a small patrimony and Darras fought legal battles, sometimes backed by force, at several points in his life to extend his holdings, although with limited success.\n\nIn 1379,<ref>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp297-317#n193 Ribbesford with the Borough of Bewdley \u2013 Manors, note anchor 193]</ref> and again in 1383,<ref>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp297-317#fnn196 Ribbesford with the Borough of Bewdley \u2013 Manors, footnote 196]</ref> Darras and his aunts Burga and Elizabeth contested ownership of the manors of Ribbesford and [[Rock, Worcestershire]], which had been held by Sir Henry Ribbesford, also under the Mortimers of [[Wigmore, Herefordshire|Wigmore]].<ref name=rib/> They were opposed by John de Resunden, the husband of their distant relative, Iseult. They won their suit but for reasons unknown the estates were both<ref name=rock-manor>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp319-328#h3-0002 Rock or Ake \u2013 Manors.]</ref> soon in the hands of [[Thomas de Beauchamp, 12th Earl of Warwick]], one of the [[Lords Appellant]], who was temporarily stripped of all his lands during [[Richard II of England|Richard II]]'s counter-coup of 1397.\n\n[[File:Priest's gravestone, Rock.jpg|thumb|left|A medieval monk, depicted on a gravestone at Rock. The church was monastic property.]]\nPatronage of the churches on most of these estates, potentially a lucrative right, went to Darras. The [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rectory]] of Sidbury was in his gift and he is known to have made presentations to it. On 16 June 1386 Darras authorised an exchange of clergy, by which the local priest went to St Katherine's chapel in [[Hereford Cathedral]] and the former cathedral chaplain, Philip Kentles, became rector of Sidbury.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork18unknuoft#page/n143/mode/2up ''Registrum Johannis Gilbert'', p. 125.]</ref> St Katherine's chapel served the Bishop's Palace,<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/rchme/heref/vol1/pp90-144#h3-0002 ''Hereford: Ecclesiastical'' in An Inventory of the Historical Monuments in Herefordshire, Volume 1, South west.]</ref> so this exchange must have been of importance to [[John Gilbert (bishop of St David's)|John Gilbert]], presumably earning Darras a modicum of episcopal favour. In April 1392 Darras appointed a successor after Philip's death.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork14unknuoft#page/n421/mode/2up ''Registrum Johannis Trefnant'', p. 176.]</ref> At Neenton too Darras held and used the advowson, presenting Roger Murimore as incumbent of the church in November 1399.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork14unknuoft#page/n427/mode/2up ''Registrum Johannis Trefnant'', p. 183.]</ref> Linley's church was a chapel of Holy Trinity Church in [[Much Wenlock]],<ref>Currie et al, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol10/pp348-354#h3-0006 Linley \u2013 Church.]</ref> which was in the hands of Wenlock Priory, the feudal overlord, leaving Darras with no control. However, while he had effective control of Ribbesford, the [[advowson]] must have been his to exercise, as it went with the manor.<ref>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp297-317#h3-0006 Ribbesford with the Borough of Bewdley \u2013 Advowsons.]</ref> In the case of Rock, however, the principal manor in the parish was not Rock itself but Alton,<ref name=rock-manor/> and the advowson of the church went with it: although there had been challenges from the Ribbesford family, the advowson was held by the [[Abbey of Saint-Evroul]] in [[Normandy]] during the 14th century.<ref>Page and Willis-Bund: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/worcs/vol4/pp319-328#h3-0004 Rock or Ake \u2013 Advowson.]</ref>\n\nAs a substantial, if not grand, landowner, Darras was evidently enjoyed a degree of trust among the local [[landed gentry]]. He is known to have acted for others in land transactions, including Malcolm de la Mare,<ref name=mp/> Thomas Whitton and John Meisy.<ref>[http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/getrecord/CCA_X3365_67_40/ Shropshire Archives Document Reference: 3365/67/40, Recognizances 1377\u20131378], at Discovering Shropshire's History.</ref> His business associates tend to recur as personal and family allies throughout his known career.\n\n{{chart top|Family tree to illustrate the Ribbesford property disputes}}\nDerived from the table given by Wrottesley.<ref>Wrottesley. [https://archive.org/stream/pedigreesfromple00wrotrich#page/134/mode/2up Pedigrees from the Plea Rolls, p. 134.]</ref> and further information from the [[Victoria County History]].<ref name=rib/>\n{{tree chart/start}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|.}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | |Henry| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |Hawise|Henry=Henry de Ribbesford|Hawise=Hawise}}\n{{tree chart| |,|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.| | | | | |!}}\n{{tree chart|Jul| |John| |Walter|v|Con| |John2| |Thomas| | | |Tom|John=John the Elder|Walter=Walter|John2=John the Younger|Thomas=Thomas|Jul=Juliana|Tom=Thomas le Forcer|Con=Constance}}\n{{tree chart| |!| | | | | | | |,|-|^|-|.| | | | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.}}\n{{tree chart|Is| | | | | |Wal| |Rog| | | | | | | |Burg| |Liz| |Joan|v|Ral|Is=Isolda or Iseult|Wal=Walter|Rog=Roger|Burg=Burga|Liz=Elizabeth|Joan=Joan|Ral=Ralph Darras}}\n{{tree chart| |!| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!}}\n{{tree chart|Is|-|JohnR| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |JohnD|Is=Iseult|JohnR=John de Resunden|JohnD=John Darras}}\n{{tree chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==Marriage and family==\n[[File:Moreton Corbet Castle from west 01.JPG|thumb|Remains of the medieval [[keep]] at [[Moreton Corbet Castle]], with the [[curtain wall (fortification)|curtain wall]] curving around to the gatehouse, restored in the mid-16th century on the right. On the right are remains of the [[Elizabethan architecture|Elizabethan]] house. The Corbets of Moreton Corbet were themselves powerful allies but also, like Darras, found further security in the Arundel affinity.]]\nDarras married '''Joan Corbet'''. The marriage took place before 1390. However, as Darras is not recorded as active on Joan's behalf in the Corbet property disputes of 1385, it must have been in the second half of the 1380s. Darras formally entered the Arundel affinity in 1387, which may coincide approximately with his marriage.\n\nJoan Corbet was the daughter of \n:*'''Sir Robert Corbet''' (died 1375) of Moreton Corbet.<ref name=visitation/> The Corbets of Moreton Corbet had taken over as the senior line of Corbets in the region, as the Corbets at [[Caus Castle]] had petered out in 1347.<ref name=landlords/>\n:*'''Elizabeth Le Strange''', daughter of Fulk, 1st [[Baron Strange of Blackmere|Baron Strange]] of [[Blakemere|Blackmere]].<ref name=rog/><ref>[https://archive.org/stream/familyofcorbetit02corb#page/368/mode/2up Corbet, pedigree facing p.368,]</ref> The Le Strange family were another important dynasty of [[Marcher Lords]] with many branches. The Blackmere barony was of fairly recent foundation. Elizabeth's father was called to parliament by [[Edward II of England|Edward II]] and served him as Seneschal of Gascony,<ref>[http://www.gasconrolls.org/indexes/entity-004770.html Fulk Lestrange at the Gascon Rolls Project (1317\u20131478)], accessed 4 December 2013</ref> the head of the administration of the remaining [[Plantagenet]] possessions in France. The title could be passed through both male and female, and the tortuous line of descent of the Le Stranges may have been one of the factors predisposing the Corbets towards reinforcing [[male primogeniture]] through dubious property transactions. From 1383 it passed via female descent and marriage to the Talbot family,<ref name=landlords/> and was one of the many titles collected together by John Talbot, [[Baron Furnivall]] and later [[Earl of Shrewsbury]].\n\nJoan was the widow of Robert de Harley of Willey and had a daughter and heiress, Alice, who married Sir Hamo Peshall or Hamon Peshale. Joan brought a range of properties, acquired from her own family and her first husband, which must have greatly increased Darras's comfort and security while she was alive. She had a considerable amount of [[jointure]] property from her first marriage \u2013 in Shropshire at [[Harley, Shropshire|Harley]], [[Gretton, Shropshire|Gretton]], Willey and [[Kenley, Shropshire|Kenley]], and in [[Worcestershire]] part of a manor at [[Hampton Lovett]],<ref name=mp/> known as Over Hall.<ref name=hampton>A History of the County of Worcester: Volume 3: [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43102#s2 Hampton Lovett \u2013 Manors], cf. footnote 28.</ref> Some of these properties passed to Roger Willey, a relative of Sir Robert Harley, in 1400,<ref name=mp/> presumably on Joan's death: Willey was a business associate of Darras.<ref name=cpr1405-08-271/> The Hampton Lovett property, however, was destined for Alice, Joan and Robert Harley's daughter, who married Sir Hamo Peshall.<ref name=hampton/>\n\nJoan was almost certainly some years older than Darras. It is not clear whether they had children, although Darras may have left a son named Roger.<ref name=mp/> Joan seems to have died around the turn of the century, with her properties largely leaving his control, prompting Darras to an active and fairly successful search for further sources of income in the years following.\n\nJoan's family, the Corbets of [[Moreton Corbet Castle]] were one of the rising gentry families, steadily increasing their estates and their influence.<ref name=landlords>Baugh and Elrington (1989), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol4/pp72-118#h3-0002 Domesday Book: 1300\u20131540: Landlords]</ref> However, they were not of the first rank, and both they and Darras were increasingly to seek advancement through the [[affinities|affinity]] of the FitzAlans, the [[Earls of Arundel]], who were supreme both economically and politically in Shropshire as well being among the greatest magnates in England.\n\n==The Corbet property disputes==\n[[File:Richard II King of England.jpg|thumb|Richard II, who intervened in and profited from the Corbet property disputes.]]\nJoan Corbet's brother, [[Roger Corbet (died 1395)|Sir Roger]], was preoccupied with family disputes over property, many of which involved Joan. Darras inevitably took his wife's side, sometimes bringing him into disrepute with the king and his government.\n\nRoger Corbet had two older brothers, Thomas and John, as well as a younger brother, John, and sisters, including Joan, who was possibly the eldest of the siblings.<ref name=visitation>[https://archive.org/stream/visitationshrop00britgoog#page/n188/mode/2up Visitation of Shropshire, p. 134.]</ref> Roger and Joan's parents, Robert and Elizabeth Corbet, had been concerned to keep the family estates together in a time of short life-spans and tortuous succession that affected many landowning families. As the eldest son, Thomas, predeceased his parents, the initial target had been to prevent the estates going to Elizabeth, his daughter, who had married [[John Ipstones|Sir John Ipstones]], a quarrelsome and sometimes violent man who served twice as MP for [[Staffordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Staffordshire]].<ref name=ips>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/ipstones-sir-john-1394 IPSTONES, Sir John (d.1394), of Blymhill, Staffs.] \u2013 Author: C.R.</ref> In the 1360s they initiated a complex series of property transactions, using the device of [[fine of lands]], and intended to keep the bulk of the Corbet lands effectively [[Fee tail|in tail]], favouring in particular Fulk and Roger.<ref name=corb241>[https://archive.org/stream/familyofcorbetit02corb#page/n117/mode/2up Corbet, p.241]</ref> The provisions of these fines were contested by Ipstones and Elizabeth from the outset.<ref name=ips/> However, after the death of Fulk in 1382, much worse followed. Some of the provisions were revealed as mutually-contradictory. Fulk's daughter and sole heiress, also Elizabeth, contested effective ownership of property that had been assigned for life, under a fine of 1363,<ref name=corb241/><ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol15/pp290-307 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Richard II, Volume 15, File 25, no. 742.]</ref> to Joan and her first husband, Sir Robert Harley of [[Willey, Shropshire|Willey]],<ref>Feet of Fines for Shropshire, CP 25/1/195/16, number 42, [http://www.medievalgenealogy.org.uk/fines/abstracts/CP_25_1_195_16.shtml Abstract] at Medieval Genealogy and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT4/CP25%281%29/CP_25_1_195/IMG_0325.htm Photograph of original document] at Anglo-American Legal Tradition.</ref> who died around 1370,<ref name=mp/> with the remainder to Fulk and the heirs of his body. These lands at [[Yockleton]], Shelve, [[Wentnor]] and Caus Forest, were all on the western side of Shropshire, close to the Welsh border and Joan and Harley leased them for the remainder of their lives to Sir Fulk for a rent of \u00a360 a year.<ref>Feet of Fines for Shropshire, CP 25/1/195/16, number 43, [http://www.medievalgenealogy.org.uk/fines/abstracts/CP_25_1_195_16.shtml Abstract] at Medieval Genealogy and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT4/CP25%281%29/CP_25_1_195/IMG_0326.htm Photograph of original document] at Anglo-American Legal Tradition.</ref> However, in 1367, they levied a fine to ensure estates passed to Roger in the event of Fulk's death.<ref>Feet of Fines for Shropshire, CP 25/1/195/17, number 12, [http://www.medievalgenealogy.org.uk/fines/abstracts/CP_25_1_195_17.shtml Abstract] at Medieval Genealogy and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT7/CP25%281%29/CP25_1_195_17/IMG_0014.htm Photograph of original document] at Anglo-American Legal Tradition.</ref> As Joan was still alive when Sir Fulk died in 1382, his daughter, Elizabeth, had a reasonable expectation of continuing to lease the lands under the fine of 1363. Joan, however, intended the lands to go immediately to her younger brother, Roger, according to the fine of 1367. She had reiterated the position after Harley's death in a new fine in 1376,<ref>Feet of Fines for Shropshire, CP 25/1/195/17, number 56, [http://www.medievalgenealogy.org.uk/fines/abstracts/CP_25_1_195_17.shtml Abstract] at Medieval Genealogy and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT7/CP25%281%29/CP25_1_195_17/IMG_0061.htm Photograph of original document] at Anglo-American Legal Tradition.</ref> and this position was assumed by the inquisition post mortem following Sir Fulk's death.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol15/pp290-307 Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Richard II, Volume 15, File 25, no. 743.]</ref> There was a series of legal claims and counter-claims, with the Crown intervening to try to secure an [[escheat]] while the young Elizabeth was still a minor. However, Roger emerged victorious in 1385.<ref name=rog>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/corbet-sir-roger-1395 CORBET, Sir Roger (d.1395), of Moreton Corbet, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref>\n\nWhen Elizabeth, Fulk's daughter attained the age of majority in 1390, the entire issue was re-opened. Elizabeth was now married to John Mawddwy or de la Pole, lord of [[Dinas Mawddwy]], who vigorously pursued his wife's claim. Darras, now married to Joan, was just as vigorous in pursuing the interests of Joan and her brother, Roger. The king, [[Richard II of England|Richard II]] was informed that \"strife and debate\" was threatening the peace in Shropshire. It seems that violence had broken out at the beginning of June.<ref name=rog/> It is unlikely that Darras, already an experienced fighting man, was uninvolved, as on 7 June 1390 he was the first of those ordered to appear before King [[Richard II of England|Richard II]] and his Council in [[Court of Chancery|Chancery]] on 23 June, on pain of forfeiting 200 [[Mark (money)|marks]].<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarofclo04grea#page/142/mode/2up Calendar of Close Rolls, 1389\u20131392, p. 142.]</ref> [[Writ]]s in the same terms were issued to seven others, including Sir Roger Corbet and Malcolm de la Mare, Darras's business associate and recently MP for [[Herefordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Herefordshire]].<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/mare-malcolm-de-la-1399 MARE, Malcolm de la (d.c.1399), of Yatton and Little Hereford, Herefs. and Kidderminster, Worcs.] \u2013 Author: Charles Kightly.</ref> A further writ to the [[High Sheriff of Shropshire|Sheriff]] ordered him to compel their attendance.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarofclo04grea#page/142/mode/2up Calendar of Close Rolls, 1389\u20131392, p. 143.]</ref> However, the arrangements for the court appearance were changed and on 22 June writs were issued, this time naming Joan as well as John Darras, ordering the quarrelling gentry to appear instead at the next Shrewsbury [[assize]]s before [[Robert Charleton (justice)|Sir Robert Charleton]].<ref name=ccr8992-199>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarofclo04grea#page/198/mode/2up Calendar of Close Rolls, 1389\u20131392, p. 199.]</ref> Charleton and [[John Hill (died 1408)|Sir John Hill]] were authorised to take security for good behaviour from them and to familiarise themselves in advance with the complexities of the case.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarpatentr02blacgoog#page/n351/mode/2up Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1388\u20131392, p. 340.]</ref> The delay was accompanied by an order for Edward Acton, the Shropshire escheator personally to take the disputed estates into the king's hands, pending a resolution.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarofclo04grea#page/202/mode/2up Calendar of Close Rolls, 1389\u20131392, p. 202.]</ref> After further delays, which were very profitable to king who was pocketing the proceeds, an agreement was reached and on 25 April 1391 the escheator was ordered to cease meddling with the estates.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarofclo04grea#page/256/mode/2up Calendar of Close Rolls, 1389\u20131392, p. 256.]</ref> It seems they were assigned to the Mawddwys, and later to their daughter Elizabeth, who married [[Hugh Burgh]], a future MP for Shropshire and [[Lord High Treasurer of Ireland]]. However, it is likely that Joan and Darras received the consolation of regular rent from them.<ref name=mp/> While losing the case was a blow to prestige, leasing was actually the preferred option among Shropshire landowners like the Corbets, who had been renting out [[demesne]] lands to secure a regular income in uncertain times.<ref>Baugh and Elrington (1989), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol4/pp72-118#h3-0008 Domesday Book: 1300\u20131540 \u2013 The leasing of the demesnes.]</ref> It is also possible that there was a large sum for Joan and John Darras at the ouset of the tenancy: the [[Recognizance]]s preserved in the county archives show that in September 1391 ''John de Mowche'' (presumably a rendering of Mawddwy, which is given as ''Mouthe''<ref name=ccr8992-199/> in the [[Close Rolls]]) undertook to pay John Darras 1000 marks at Easter 1392.<ref>[http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/getrecord/CCA_X3365_67_45v/ Shropshire Archives Document Reference: 3365/67/45v, Recognizances 1391\u20131392], at Discovering Shropshire's History.</ref>\n{{chart top|Family tree to illustrate the Corbet property disputes}}\nBased on pedigrees derived from the Heraldic Visitation of Shropshire, 1623,<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/visitationshrop00britgoog#page/n188/mode/2up Visitation of Shropshire, p. 134-38.]</ref> and in Augusta Corbet's family history,<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/familyofcorbetit02corb#page/368/mode/2up Corbet, facing p. 368.]</ref> supplemented by more recent information from the History of Parliament Online.\n{{familytree/start}}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | |Kat |-|Rob1|v|Mat| | | | |Kat=Katherine, daughter of John [[Baron Strange#1299 creation|le Strange]] of [[Knockin]] and [[Myddle]]|Rob1=Sir Robert Corbet (died 1300) of [[Moreton Corbet|Moreton Toret]] and [[Wattlesborough Castle|Wattlesborough]]|Mat=Matilda (died 1309), daughter John de Arundel}}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|.|}}\n{{familytree | | | | | |Am|v| Tom | |Fulk| |John| | | | | | | | | |Am=Amice|Tom=Thomas Corbet (died 1310) of Moreton Toret and Wattlesborough|Fulk=Fulk Corbet, Canon of [[Lichfield Cathedral]]|John=John Corbet}}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | |!}}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | |Rob|v|Liz||| | | | | | | | |Rob=Sir RobertCorbet (1304\u201375) of Moreton Toret and Wattlesborough|Liz=Elizabeth, daughter of Fulk, 1st [[Baron Strange of Blackmere]]}}\n{{familytree | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|^|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{familytree |Harl|v|Joan|-|Dar|!| |Fulk|v|Liz2| | |!| | |Rog|v|Marg1|Fulk=Sir Fulk Corbet (died 1382) of Moreton Corbet|Liz2=Elizabeth|Harl=Robert de Harley|Joan=Joan Corbet|Dar=John Darras of Sidbury and [[Neenton]]|Rog=[[Roger Corbet (died 1395)]]|Marg1=Margaret Erdington (died 1395)|}}\n{{familytree| |,|-|'| | | | | | | |!| | | | |!| | | | | |!| | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree| |!| | | |Liz1|v|Tom1| | | | |!| | | | |Marg1|v|Tom2|!|Liz1=Elizabeth|Tom1=Sir Thomas Corbet (died c.1359)|Marg1=Margaret Corbet|Tom2=Sir Thomas Erdington (died 1395) of [[Erdington]]}}\n{{familytree | |!| | | | | | |!| | | | | | | |!| | | | | | | |!| | | |)|-|-|-|.| | |}}\n{{familytree |Al|-|Hamon||Liz1|-|Ip||Liz2|-|Maw| |Tom| |Rob| |Rog|Al=Alicia Harley|Ip=Sir [[John Ipstones]] (d.1394) of [[Blymhill]]|Hamon=Sir Hamon Peshale (died c.1398)|Liz1=Elizabeth Corbet|Maw=John de la Pole of [[Dinas Mawddwy]]|Liz2=Elizabeth Corbet, heiress to Wattlesborough|Tom=Sir Thomas Erdington (c.1371\u20131434) of Erdington|Rob=[[Robert Corbet (died 1420)|Robert Corbet (1383\u20131420)]] of Moreton Corbet|Rog=[[Roger Corbet (died 1430)]] of [[Shrewsbury]]}}\n{{familytree/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==Political and military career==\n[[File:A Chronicle of England - Page 328 - Arundel, Gloucester, Nottingham, Derby, and Warwick, Before the King.jpg|thumb|left|The Lords Appellant confront Richard II. In this Victorian illustration, Arundel is portrayed on the left, wearing his arms of a gold rampant lion on a red ground.]]\n[[File:Henry IV Coronation.jpg|thumb|Coronation of Henry IV.]]\n[[File:Owain Glyndwr Siegel 2.jpg|thumb|left|Seal of [[Owain Glynd\u0175r]], proclaimed [[Prince of Wales]] at [[Corwen]] in 1400. Darras earned the approval of both Arundel and the king by serving repeatedly against the Welsh rebellion.]]\n[[File:JohnTalbotEarlOfShrewsbury.jpg|thumb|Effigy of John Talbot, later Earl of Shrewsbury, in [[St Alkmund's Church, Whitchurch]]. A distinguished campaigner in the Hundred Years' War, Talbot seems to have gained control of Darras's estates.]]\n\nDarras formally enlisted as an esquire in the retinue of [[Richard FitzAlan, 11th Earl of Arundel]] in 1387.<ref name=mp/> Among others to do so, and probably thereby form a political and personal bond with Arundel, was Thomas Whitton,<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/whitton-thomas-1411 WHITTON, Thomas (d.1411), of Whitton near Burford, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger.</ref> a long-term associate of Darras. At this point Arundel was one of the [[Lords Appellant]], a leader of the opposition to Richard II's favourites and his policy of peace with France. Darras served with him in a naval campaign against the French, which culminated in a significant victory off [[Margate]]. As a client of the earl, and in association with two other members of his affinity, [[John Burley]] and Fulk Sprenghose, Darras was made trustee of estates belonging to Richard, 4th Lord Talbot, who was married to Arundel's niece, Ankaret le Strange of Blackmere.<ref name=ls288>[https://archive.org/stream/lestrangerecords00lond#page/288/mode/2up Le Strange, p. 288.]</ref> In 1393 he represented his county in the parliament that began on 20 January and lasted about three weeks. His fellow MP was Sir William Hugford, who was closely associated with John le Strange, 6th Baron Strange of Knockin: although powerful, the 11th Earl of Arundel seems to have been much happier to share influence than was to prove the case with his son.\n\nArundel was executed in Richard II's purge of 1397. The inquisition into the earl's Shropshire lands listed the numerous small grants of land he had made to his affinity and others whom he needed to cultivate. One of these was a small estate at [[Gretton, Shropshire]], held by Darras and worth 40 [[shilling]]s annually.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=inu.30000047592476;view=1up;seq=124 Calendar of Inquisitions Miscellaneous (Chancery), 1392\u20131399, p. 114.]</ref> It seems, however, that Darras also had good contacts in the Lancastrian affinity. Earlier in the year, together with Edward Whitton, Henry Wynnesbury, and Fulk Pembridge, Darras was involved in some transaction that required each to pay \u00a3200 to [[Walter Blount (soldier)|Sir Walter Blount]],<ref>[http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/getrecord/CCA_X3365_67_47/ Shropshire Archives Document Reference: 3365/67/47, Recognizances 1396\u20131397], at Discovering Shropshire's History.</ref> An important participant in [[John of Gaunt]]'s military adventures abroad and his leading representative in the Midlands.<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/blount-sir-walter-1403 BLOUNT, Sir Walter (d.1403), of Barton Blount, Derbys.] \u2013 Author: C.R.</ref>\n\nWhen John of Gaunt's son and dispossessed successor, [[Henry IV of England|Henry Bolingbroke]] arrived in England to challenge Richard in 1399, the Arundels rallied to the cause of the [[House of Lancaster]], formerly their bitter enemies: the dead earl's son, [[Thomas FitzAlan, 12th Earl of Arundel]], and brother, [[Thomas Arundel]], the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], became mainstays of the government of Bolingbroke, who came to the throne as Henry IV. Darras seems to have good connections with both parts of the victorious coalition and from this point he contrived to remain in royal favour, albeit sometimes with difficulty. He was made keeper for life of [[Morfe Forest|Morfe]] and Shirlet, areas of [[Royal forest]] on either side of the [[Severn]] in Shropshire, by [[letters patent]] of 4 November 1399.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendarpatentr16offigoog#page/n75/mode/2up Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1399\u20131401, p. 64.]</ref> After his loyal service against the [[Glynd\u0175r Rising]] in Wales, a major preoccupation of both Arundel and the king,  further letters patent in February 1407, described Darras as the \"king's esquire,\" and confirmed that the office was indeed a reward for his military service and permitted him to appoint a ranger as a deputy to act in his absences.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=308 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 296.]</ref>\n\nIt was probably his connection with the FitzAlans that assured his appointment as [[High Sheriff of Shropshire]] for 1401-2. Before he took up the shrievalty, his friend [[John Cornwall (c.1366-1414)|Sir John Cornwall]], a former sheriff and also a former retainer of John of Gaunt, was accused of cattle rustling at Wytheford (also rendered Withiford) in Shropshire.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/collectionsforhi15staf#page/n243/mode/2up Collections for a History of Staffordshire, volume 15, p. 102.]</ref> Cornwall counted as family, as he was a grandson of Fulk, 1st Baron Strange of Blackmere, and so a first cousin of Darras's wife.<ref name=cornwall/> However, the case affected the king's interests, as the plaintiffs, who were demanding \u00a3100, alleged that their cattle had already been taken into the custody of the county escheator when Cornwall removed them.<ref name=chs15-103>[https://archive.org/stream/collectionsforhi15staf#page/n245/mode/2up Collections for a History of Staffordshire, volume 15, p. 103.]</ref> In April 1402 Darras was one of four local gentry who stood surety at Westminster for Cornwall that he would keep the peace,<ref>[https://www.familysearch.org/library/books/records/item/581522-redirection Calendar of Close Rolls, 1399\u20131402, p. 555.]</ref> an act that potentially created a conflict of interest. However, the plaintiffs alleged that Darras went much further. When the case was moved to the Shrewsbury assizes by a writ of [[nisi prius]] it was claimed that Darras allowed Cornwall to select the jurors.<ref name=chs15-103/> The jury was dismissed and Darras was ordered to summon a new panel for the next assizes. Darras was also the returning officer when Cornwall was elected to Parliament.<ref name=mp/> Cornwall was a man of considerable prestige, claiming descent from [[John, King of England|King John]],<ref name=cornwall>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/cornwall-sir-john-1366-1414 CORNWALL, Sir John (c.1366\u20131414), of Kinlet, Salop.] \u2013 Authors: J.S. Roskell/L.S. Woodger</ref> but an unstable and dangerous associate, who was to attract constant accusations of violence and intimidation.\n\nThe 12th Earl exercised a much tighter grip on power in the region than his father, dominating parliamentary representation at every election. It was Darras's turn again in 1404, when he was sent to Parliament with John Burley, another lawyer who worked mainly for the Fitzalans and who had fought alongside Darras in the naval campaign of 1387.<ref>Roskell et al,  [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/burley-john-i-141516 BURLEY, John I (d.1415/16), of Broncroft in Corvedale, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L.S. Woodger</ref> Burley had also held the wardship of [[Robert Corbet (died 1420)|Robert Corbet]], the heir of Sir Roger and nephew of Joan.\n\nDarras could not entirely escape penalty when in 1406 he and Roger Willey bought two properties held [[Tenant-in-chief|''in capita'']] without obtaining royal approval: a quarter [[carucate]] of land at [[Worfield]] and a [[moiety title|moiety]] of the [[forester]]ship of Morfe. However, a pardon was granted on 15 November for a mere 6s. 8d.<ref name=cpr1405-08-271>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=283 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 271.]</ref> Darras and Willey then resold both properties to Richard Parlour, a [[Burgess (title)|burgess]] of Bridgnorth, again without asking permission: Parlour was compelled to sue and pay for pardon in 1408, after Darras's death.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=438 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 426.]</ref><ref>Roskell et al,  [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/parlour-richard PARLOUR, Richard, of Bridgnorth, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L.S. Woodger</ref>\n\nIn 1407 Darras, together with Robert Corbet, [[Roger Corbet (died 1430)|Roger Corbet]], nephews of Joan, and William Ryman of Sussex \u2013 all of Arundel's affinity \u2013 were among a group of Shropshire gentry who granted a [[burgage]] in [[Shrewsbury]], known as Ireland Hall, to [[Shrewsbury Abbey]] for pious purposes.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=351 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 339.]</ref><ref name=\"historyofparliamentonline.org\">Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/corbet-robert-1383-1420 CORBET, Robert (1383\u20131420), of Moreton Corbet, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref> The licence to accept this gift, which cost the abbey the considerable sum of 10 marks, was granted on 20 July. The younger Corbets had enlisted with Arundel about two years previously and were to acquire sinister reputations for violence and lawlessness.<ref name=\"historyofparliamentonline.org\"/> They and their uncle probably granted Ireland Hall on behalf of Arundel. The abbot of Shrewsbury, [[Thomas Prestbury]], was a client of Archbishop Arundel, the earl's uncle, and had been imprisoned in 1399 for preaching against the government of Richard II.<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id=107122 |title=Prestbury, Thomas |last=Heale |first=Martin}}</ref> Later in the year Darras attended the election of [[knights of the shire]], witnessing the return of Cornwall and [[David Holbache]], a prominent lawyer and a close associate of Arundel.<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/holbache-david-1422 HOLBACHE, David (d.c.1422), of Dudleston and Oswestry, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref> This was Darras's last important public appearance.\n\n==Death and aftermath==\n\nDarras hanged himself at Neenton, probably during March 1408. The evidence for the date is a commission from the king, issued on 30 March, to four Shropshire gentry to investigate possible concealment of the deceased's goods,<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=497 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 485.]</ref> which as a suicide, escheated to the Crown. A formal order for the escheator to take his estates into the hands of the king was issued on 24 May.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/calendaroffinero13greauoft#page/120/mode/2up Calendar of Fine Rolls, 1405\u20131413, p. 120.]</ref> His holdings would normally have reverted to their feudal overlords but the young [[Edmund Mortimer, 5th Earl of March]] was the centre of plots against Henry IV and much of his property was temporarily or permanently forfeit.\n\nConsiderable confusion and disputes seem to have followed Darras's unusual and untimely death. At Sidbury the advowson was contested. On 6 July, as a new rector was needed at Sidbury, Henry St George acted as patron, presenting William Walkebache. On 11 August, however, [[John Talbot, 1st Earl of Shrewsbury|John Talbot, 6th Baron Furnivall]], also acting as patron and described as lord of Sidbury, presented Walter Lawrence.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork21unknuoft#page/n189/mode/2up Registrum Roberti Mascall, p. 173.]</ref> Talbot, the young son of Richard, Lord Talbot, and Ankaret le Strange,<ref name=ls288/> was to emerge as Arundel's main political rival in the county, prepared to fight force with force.<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/constituencies/shropshire Shropshire] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref> On 23 August Bishop [[Robert Mascall]] was issued with a writ probiting him from admitting anyone to Sidbury until the issue was decided.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork21unknuoft#page/n83/mode/2up Registrum Roberti Mascall, p. 66.]</ref> The following April the bishop himself presented William Whitehead.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork21unknuoft#page/n191/mode/2up Registrum Roberti Mascall, p. 174.]</ref> By August 1409 Whitehead had resigned and Talbot presented his nominee for a second time,<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork21unknuoft#page/n191/mode/2up Registrum Roberti Mascall, p. 175.]</ref> apparently triumphant in the struggle to take over Darras's lands and rights. The same pattern is shown at Linley, which probably fell into his hands, as his widow, [[Margaret Beauchamp, Countess of Shrewsbury]], held half the manor as a jointure property after his death.<ref name=linley/>\n\nSimilar confusions arose over Darras's keepership of Morfe and Shirlet. Soon after Darras's death the king conferred the office on Sir John Cornwall, removing it from Nicholas Gerard, on the grounds that the office had not been vacant when Gerard acquired it,<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079588;view=1up;seq=436 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1405\u20131408, p. 424.]</ref> although the story behind the recital of facts is mysterious. There were several Shrewsbury business men named Nicholas Gerard in the 14th century<ref>[http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/search/?q=nicholas+gerard&cb_submit=Search Shropshire Archives search for Nicholas Gerard] at Discovering Shropshire's History.</ref> and this seems to be the one served as MP in 1399<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/gerard-nicholas-1421 GERARD, Nicholas (d.1421), of Shrewsbury, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref> and bailiff in 1412.<ref>[http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/getrecord/CCA_XSB_C_1_1_1_24/ Shropshire Archives Document Reference: 3365/67/12v] at Discovering Shropshire's History.</ref> Cornwall soon proved himself tyrannical in office. By March 1410 the king was ordering Arundel and his legal team, John Burley, David Holbache and Thomas Young,<ref>Roskell et al, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/young-%28yonge%29-thomas-i YOUNG, (YONGE), Thomas I, of Sibdon Carwood, Salop.] \u2013 Author: L. S. Woodger</ref> together with Lord Furnival, to investigate breaches of customary manorial and grazing rights at [[Worfield]] in Morff Forest,<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079570;view=1up;seq=194 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1408\u20131413, p. 182.]</ref> made by Arundel's brother-in-law, [[William de Beauchamp, 1st Baron Bergavenny]]. Cornwall was clearly quite reckless in his depredations, as there had been similar complaints from William Ferrers, 5th [[Baron Ferrers of Groby]]. Joan Beauchamp, Arundel's sister continued to complain about Cornwall into 1412, after she was widowed,<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079570;view=1up;seq=389 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1408\u20131413, p. 377.]</ref> prompting a further commission of inquiry by the same team. The following year the king received similar complaints from John Marshall, Dean of the [[Church of St. Mary Magdalene, Bridgnorth|royal free chapel at Bridgnorth]]<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079570;view=1up;seq=489 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1408\u20131413, p. 477.]</ref> It seems that, before sending in Arundel's lawyers to investigate, the king secured Cornwall's resignation and on 13 February 1413 installed Roger Willey, Darras's old business partner, as keeper in his place.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031079570;view=1up;seq=477 Calendar of Patent Rolls, 1408\u20131413, p. 465.]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bastard feudalism]]\n*[[Corbet family]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n\n* {{cite web |url=http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/searching-the-archives/ |title=Archives |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=Discovering Shropshire's History |publisher=Shropshire County Council |access-date=1 July 2016 |quote=}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Capes |editor1-first=William W. |editor1-link= |date=1916 |title=Registrum Johannis Trefnant, Episcopi Herefordensis|volume=20|url=https://archive.org/stream/canterburyyork14unknuoft#page/n237/mode/2up |location=London |publisher=Canterbury and York Society |page= |isbn= |access-date= 29 June 2016 }} at Internet Archive.\n* {{cite book |author1-last=Corbet |author1-first=Augusta Elizabeth Brickdale |date= |title=The Family of Corbet; its Life and Times |volume=2 |url=https://archive.org/details/familyofcorbetit02corb |location=London |publisher= St. Catherine Press |page= |isbn= |access-date= 3 October 2013 }} at Internet Archive.\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Baugh |editor1-first=G. C. |editor2-last=Elrington |editor2-first=C. R.|date=1989 |title= A History of the County of Shropshire |volume=4|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol4 |location=London |publisher=British History Online 