national Chopin Piano Competition.\n*[[October 25]] \u2013 [[Virgil Fox]] (68), organist (cancer)\n*[[October 27]] \u2013 [[Steve Peregrin Took]] (31), [[Bongo drum|bongo]] player for [[T. Rex (band)|Tyrannosaurus Rex]] later a solo artist/frontman (asphyxiation)\n*[[November 15]] \u2013 [[Bill Lee (singer)|Bill Lee]] (64), American actor and playback singer \n*[[December 7]] \u2013 [[Darby Crash]] (22), singer of the ([[Germs (band)|Germs]]) (suicide)\n*[[December 8]] \u2013 [[John Lennon]] (40), singer, guitarist and songwriter ([[The Beatles]]) (murdered)\n*[[December 24]] \u2013 [[Siggie Nordstrom]] (87), American model, actress, entertainer, socialite and lead singer (The [[Nordstrom Sisters]])\n*[[December 29]] \u2013 [[Tim Hardin]] (39), singer-songwriter ([[heroin]] overdose)\n*[[December 31]] \u2013 [[Robert Pete Williams]] (66), blues singer and guitarist\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist | group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Music in 1980}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1980 In Music}}\n[[Category:1980 in music| ]]\n[[Category:20th century in music]]\n[[Category:Music by year]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-No Place to Run", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1980_in_music"}
{"title_page": "Drew Peterson", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=[[Scott Peterson]], an individual with a similar name and case}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| image_name = \n| image_size = \n| image_caption = Will County Sheriff's Office<br />mugshot of Drew Peterson\n| birth_name = Drew Walter Peterson\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1954|01|05}}\n| birth_place = [[Bolingbrook, Illinois|Bolingbrook]], [[Illinois]], [[United States|USA]]\n| alias = \n| conviction = Premeditated [[murder]] in the 2004 death of Kathleen Savio, solicitation of [[Murder for hire]] in the attempted murder of James Glasgow\n| children = 6\n| conviction_penalty = 78 years in prison; earliest possible release May 7, 2081\n| conviction_status = [[Incarceration|Incarcerated]]\n| occupation = Former Police Officer\n| spouse = {{marriage|Carol Brown<br>|1974|1980|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Vicki Connolly<br>|1982|1992|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Kathleen Savio<br>|1992|2003|end=divorced}}<br>Stacy Ann Cales <br/>({{abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;2003\u2013?; missing since 2007)\n| parents = \n}}\n\n'''Drew Walter Peterson''' (born January 5, 1954) is a retired [[Bolingbrook, Illinois|Bolingbrook]], [[Illinois]] [[sergeant|police sergeant]] who was convicted in 2012 for the murder of his third wife, Kathleen Savio, a few months after their 2003 divorce. Peterson first received national publicity in 2007 when his fourth wife, Stacy Ann Cales Peterson, [[missing person|disappeared]]. Although the police and Stacy Ann's family suspect [[Crime|foul play]], she has never been found.\n\nSuspicions in Stacy Ann's case were fueled in part by the death of Savio, whose bruised body was found in a dry bathtub in her home in 2004, with a large gash in her scalp.<ref name=\"patch.com\">{{cite news|last1=Hosey|first1=Joseph|title=The Horror of What Kathleen Savio Went Through Before She Died|url=http://www.patch.com/illinois/bolingbrook/the-horror-of-what-kathleen-savio-went-through-before-she-died|accessdate=13 February 2017|agency=Bolingbrook Patch|date=16 August 2012}}</ref> Initially, Savio's official [[cause of death]] was found to be accidental drowning.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walberg|first1=Matthew|last2=Slife|first2=Erica|title=2004 death of Kathleen Savio ruled a homicide|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-02-22/news/0802220126_1_death-of-kathleen-savio-stacy-peterson-ruled|accessdate=13 February 2017|agency=Chicago Tribune|date=22 February 2008}}</ref> In 2009, after the attention from Stacy Ann's disappearance, Peterson was [[indictment|indicted]] for Savio's murder after a second [[autopsy]] showed evidence of a struggle. He was convicted of the murder in 2012, and was sentenced to 38 years in prison on February 21, 2013.\n\nOn February 9, 2015, Peterson was charged with two additional [[felony|felonies]] &ndash; [[solicitation of murder]] and [[contract killing|solicitation of murder for hire]] &ndash; for attempting to have [[Will County, Illinois|Will County]] [[State's Attorney]] James Glasgow killed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drew Peterson charged with attempted murder-for-hire of Illinois prosecutor|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/feb/09/drew-peterson-attempted-murder-for-hire-prosecutor|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=22 Feb 2015|date=9 Feb 2015}}</ref> Peterson was convicted on May 31, 2016, and sentenced to an additional 40 years on July 29, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Drew Peterson gets 40 extra years for plot to kill prosecutor|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-drew-peterson-sentencing-met-20160729-story.html|accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref> On February 21, 2017, he was transferred from [[Illinois Department of Corrections]] custody to the [[United States Penitentiary, Terre Haute|United States Penitentiary]] in [[Terre Haute, Indiana|Terre Haute]], [[Indiana]]. In December 2019, Peterson was transferred to an undisclosed out of state facility.<ref name=\"Patch\">{{cite news |last1=Antinori |first1=Shannon |title=Drew Peterson Moved To A New Prison \u2014 Again |url=https://patch.com/illinois/bolingbrook/drew-peterson-moved-new-prison-again |accessdate=24 March 2020 |publisher=[[Patch Meda]] |date=10 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NWHerald\">{{cite news |last1=HOSEY |first1=JOSEPH |title=Hosey: Where in the world is Drew Peterson? |url=https://www.nwherald.com/2019/12/19/hosey-where-in-the-world-is-drew-peterson/axsx0gm/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |publisher=Northwest Herald |date=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDrew Peterson graduated in 1972 from [[Willowbrook High School]] in [[Villa Park, Illinois]], where he ran [[cross country running|cross country]]. He joined the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] after graduation and briefly attended the [[College of DuPage]] in 1974 before moving to [[Falls Church, Virginia|Falls Church]], [[Virginia]] to train as a military police officer.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\">{{cite web |author=ACandyRose |url=http://www.acandyrose.com/stacy_peterson_recap.htm |title=Stacy Peterson Recap |publisher=Acandyrose.com |accessdate=7 August 2013}}</ref> Peterson began his 30-year career with the local police force in Bolingbrook, Illinois (a suburb of [[Chicago]]) in 1977.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/> In 1978, he was assigned to the Metropolitan Area Narcotics Squad, and in 1979, he received a \"Police Officer of the Year\" award from the department.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/> Peterson retired in November 2007 at age 53 with the rank of sergeant and was given a (tax-free) $79,000-a-year [[pension]] (almost $6,600-a-month).<ref>{{cite web |title=Police board hires expert in effort to strip Drew Peterson of pension |url=https://www.saukvalley.com/2013/03/05/police-board-hires-expert-in-effort-to-strip-drew-peterson-of-pension/ai3o2xm/?page=527 |last=St. Clair |first=Stacy |date=March 5, 2013 |publisher=Chicago Tribune}}</ref> His pension was terminated following his second conviction in May 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drew Peterson loses police pension day after murder-for-hire conviction |url=https://abc7chicago.com/news/drew-peterson-loses-bolingbrook-police-pension-/1369791/ |date=June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=From behind bars, Drew Peterson seeks to have police pension reinstated |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-drew-peterson-appeal-met-20160803-story.html |last=Gutowski |first=Christy |date=August 4, 2016 |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\n==Marriages==\n\n===Carol Brown===\nPeterson and Carol Brown met in high school in Villa Park and together attended his senior [[prom]].<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/><ref name=\"foxnews.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,468385,00.html |title=The Wives of Drew Peterson - Local News &#124; News Articles &#124; National News &#124; US News |publisher=FOXNews.com |date=2008-12-17 |accessdate=2010-06-06}}</ref> They married in 1974, but divorced in 1980, after Brown learned about Peterson's [[infidelity]].<ref name=\"carolbrown\">{{cite news\n| last = Barbara\n| title = Peterson says he loves, misses missing fourth wife - First wife talks, third wife reburied\n| work =| location =Indianapolis| pages =| language =| publisher = [[WLS-TV|WLS]]\n| date = 2009-05-07| url = http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news/local&id=5769607\n| accessdate = 2007-11-19 }}</ref> Together they had sons Stephen Paul Peterson (1980) and Eric Drew Peterson.<ref>http://www.hlntv.com/article/2012/07/11/talking-drew-petersons-son Eric has been estranged from their father for years, but apparently that has not affected the brothers\u2019 relationship with each other. Stephen said he and Eric get along just fine.</ref>\n\n=== Vicki Connolly ===\nPeterson married his second wife, Victoria \"Vicki\" Connolly, in 1982. They operated a bar together in [[Romeoville, Illinois|Romeoville]].<ref name=\"foxnews.com\"/> Connolly alleged a history of [[domestic violence]] during her ten-year marriage to Peterson,<ref name=\"slife\">Slife, Erika. [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-peterson_16_nov16,0,5607495.story ''EXCLUSIVE: Peterson's second wife tells her story''.] Chicago Tribune. 16 November 2007.</ref> as has her daughter, who lived in the household until she turned 17. In the wake of Stacy Ann's disappearance, Connolly told police that during their marriage, Peterson threatened to kill her and make it look like an accident.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Slife|first1=Erika|title=Peterson's second wife tells her story|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2007-11-16/news/0711160301_1_james-glasgow-drew-peterson-stacy-peterson|accessdate=13 February 2017|agency=Chicago Tribune|date=16 November 2007}}</ref> She divorced Peterson after he started dating Kathleen Savio.<ref name=\"foxnews.com\"/> Their divorce was finalized on February 18, 1992. Peterson married Savio two months later.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/>\n\n=== Kathleen Savio ===\nPeterson married accountant Kathleen Savio (born June 13, 1963 in [[Glendale Heights, Illinois]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Kathleen Savio|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/chicagotribune/obituary.aspx?pid=1994345|website=legacy.com|publisher=Chicago Tribune Media Group|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref> on May 3, 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/14542696/Savio-v-Peterson-Complaint |title=Savio v. Peterson Complaint |publisher=Scribd.com |date= |accessdate=2010-06-06}}</ref> Together they had two sons, Thomas (January 5, 1993)<ref>http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-03-19/news/ct-met-drew-peterson-son-valedictoria20110319_1_drew-peterson-bolingbrook-police-sergeant-stacy-peterson After everything, Drew Peterson's son is valedictorian.</ref><ref>http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/08/29/13549299-older-son-of-drew-peterson-kathleen-savio-says-he-believes-dad-is-innocent 19y Old Thomas Peterson Testifies.</ref> and Kristopher (August 8, 1994).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chi-drew-peterson-trial-updates-trial-enters-7th-day-after-key-ruling-20120809,0,4513046.story |title=Kristopher Peterson, who turned 18 on yesterday was in the courtroom speaking to his father this afternoon before testimony resumed after lunch |accessdate=7 August 2013 |work=Chicago Tribune |first1=Matthew |last1=Walberg |first2=Steve |last2=Schmadeke |first3=Andy |last3=Grimm |date=9 August 2012}}</ref> Their divorce was finalized on October 10, 2003.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/> It was reported that between 2002 and 2004, police were called out to the Peterson house eighteen times on domestic disturbance calls, including calls for returning children late after visitation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/May-2008/Unanswered-Cries/ |title=\"Unanswered Cries\" Chicago magazine}}</ref> On March 1, 2004,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/11/30/missing.wife.ap/index.html |title=Peterson case: Did cops protect one of their own? |work=CNN |date=2007-11-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311204059/http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/11/30/missing.wife.ap/index.html |archivedate=2008-03-11 |accessdate=7 August 2013 |df= }}</ref> Savio's body was found in a waterless bathtub. Her death was initially ruled an accidental [[drowning]] by a coroner's jury that included a police officer who personally knew Peterson and assured the other jurors that he was a good man who would never hurt his wife.<ref name=\"jury\">[http://wgnradio.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=51326&Itemid=577 ''Kathleen Savio's Family Sues Drew Peterson ''.] WGN Radio. April 21, 2009.</ref>\n\nHowever, following Stacy Peterson's later disappearance, Savio's body was exhumed and underwent [[forensic]] examination on November 16, 2007.<ref name=\"expert\">Walberg, Matthew and Jo Napolitano. [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-peterson_17nov17,1,2803259.story ''Expert: 3rd wife was slain''.] Chicago Tribune. 17 November 2007.</ref> [[Michael Baden]], a former [[New York City]] [[chief medical examiner|medical examiner]] who conducted the examination at the request of Savio's relatives and [[Fox News]], concluded that she died of drowning following a struggle when her body was placed in the bathtub. Postmortem photos showed extensive bruising and scraping to her back, torso, and face, as well as a large, unexplained gash in her scalp.<ref name=\"patch.com\"/> The results of the official autopsy ordered by the county have yet to be released to the public.<ref name=\"baden\">Tarm, Michael. [http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=3881863 ''Relatives Try to Confront Ill. Officer''.] ABC News.com. 17 November 2007.</ref> [[Will County, Illinois|Will County]] [[State's Attorney]] James Glasgow told the press that, after examining evidence in the case, he believed that the death was a \"[[homicide]] staged to look like an accident\u201d.<ref name=\"baden\"/><ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/services/newspaper/printedition/friday/chi-peterson_16_nov16,0,1765221.story  Peterson's second wife recalls threats] November 16, 2007.</ref> On February 21, 2008, Glasgow announced that a [[pathologist]] had determined that Savio's death was a homicide,<ref name=\"homicide\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/02/21/missing.wife/?iref=mpstoryview ''Death of former cop's third wife ruled a homicide'']. CNN.com. 21 February 2008.</ref> adding that the death had been investigated as such since reopening the case following the exhumation.\n\nReverend Neil Schori, a [[pastor]] at Stacy's church, reported that Stacy had told him that Drew had killed Savio and had made it look like an accident, and that she was afraid of her husband.<ref name=\"lie\">[http://www.nbc5.com/news/14710779/detail.html?rss=chi&psp=news ''Peterson's Family Demands Drew Take Lie Detector Test'']. NBC5.com. Chicago. 27 November 2007.</ref> Stacy had provided Drew's [[alibi]] for his whereabouts on the evening on which Savio died. Peterson's trial, proceeding in July 2012, was jeopardized when prosecutors attempted to introduce evidence that was not allowed. ''[[The Chicago Tribune]]'' reported that the judge would rule on a [[mistrial]] on August 2, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/ct-met-drew-peterson-trial-0802-20120802,0,5478504.story |title=Peterson judge halts testimony after defense seeks mistrial |accessdate=7 August 2013 |work=Chicago Tribune |date=1 August 2012}}</ref> On August 15, Peterson told a judge that he wanted to withdraw a request for a mistrial. His lawyers said that he wanted the current jury to decide if he killed his third wife.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tarm|first=Michael|title=DREW PETERSON WITHDRAWS REQUEST FOR MISTRIAL|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_DREW_PETERSON_TRIAL?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT|publisher=AP|accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref> On September 6, Peterson was convicted of killing Savio.<ref name=\"guilty\">{{cite news|last=Schmadeke|first=Steve|title=Peterson found guilty of murdering Savio|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-drew-peterson-found-guilty-of-murder-20120906,0,3705797.story|accessdate=September 6, 2012|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=September 6, 2012|author2=Stacy St. Clair|author3=Matthew Walberg}}</ref> On February 21, 2013, he was denied a mistrial and sentenced to 38 years in prison.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chi-drew-peterson-sentence-20130221,0,1883440.story |title=Drew Peterson transferred to Pontiac prison| work=Chicago Tribune | first1=Steve | last1=Schmadeke | first2=Matthew | last2=Walberg | first3=Stacy | last3=St. Clair | date=22 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Stacy Ann Peterson===\nAt age 49, Peterson married 19-year-old hotel receptionist Stacy Ann Cales (born January 20, 1984 in [[Downers Grove, Illinois]]) on October 18, 2003, and she subsequently changed her last name to Peterson.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/> Together they had two children, Anthony (born 2003) and Lacy (born 2005).<ref name=\"hlntv.com\">{{cite news | url = http://www.hlntv.com/article/2012/07/11/talking-drew-petersons-son | title = Drew Peterson's son: My life before his arrest | first = Beth | last = Karas | date = July 11, 2012 | work = HLN | publisher = Cable News Network, Inc. | access-date = March 21, 2018}}</ref> Stacy legally [[adoption|adopted]] Savio's children, and treated them like they were her own. She was close to completing her nursing degree from [[Joliet Junior College]] at the time of her disappearance on Sunday, October 28, 2007. Stacy was officially reported [[missing person|missing]] in the early hours of Monday, October 29, after her sister, Cassandra Cales, failed to hear from her when expected.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Peterson claims that Stacy called him at 9 p.m. on Sunday to tell him that she had left him for another man and that she had left her 2002 [[Pontiac Grand Am]] at Bolingbrook's [[Clow International Airport]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Stacy is still considered a missing person. Her family has launched a website to help find her.<ref name=searching>{{cite web|title= Stacy Peterson: Missing since October 28, 2007|url=http://www.SearchingForStacyPeterson.com/|website=Searching for Stacy Peterson|accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Legal trouble==\nSeveral leads were followed in the investigation by [[Illinois State Police]] with FBI involvement. Four search warrants were issued and carried out on Peterson's property following Stacy's disappearance, including the seizure of his firearms and both his and Stacy's vehicles. Peterson announced his plans to retire as a Bolingbrook police sergeant effective December 2007. On November 15, the Bolingbrook Police Pension Board voted to allow Peterson to collect his [[pension]] of $6,067.71 per month,<ref name=\"pension\">WBBM. [http://www.wbbm780.com/Drew-Peterson-Tells-WBBM:-My-Retirement-Sucks/1295074 ''Drew Peterson Tells Newsradio: My Retirement Sucks'']. wbbm780.com. 6 December 2007.</ref> stating current law gave them no option, as he had not been convicted of a crime.<ref name=\"slife\"/>\n\nRick Mims, Peterson's long-time friend, admitted that he and Peterson bought three blue plastic containers from a cable company where they both worked part-time in 2003, and provided photos of these containers to police. Mims also sold his story to [[tabloid newspaper]]s for an undisclosed sum of money. Peterson's stepbrother, Thomas Morphey, who has a history of drug and alcohol addiction, attempted suicide two days after allegedly helping Peterson carry a plastic container from Peterson's Bolingbrook home to his [[sport utility vehicle|SUV]], fearing he may have helped dispose of Stacy's body. Neighbors reported seeing Peterson and another man hauling a 55-gallon barrel, large enough to hold a person, out of the house shortly after the disappearance.\n\nCassandra Cales, Stacy's sister, said she wanted Peterson to take a lie detector test about his knowledge of a blue container that she saw in his garage two days before Stacy disappeared. Joel Brodsky, Peterson's attorney, denied that any container was missing from Peterson's home. There were also reports of truckers referring to the containers, but their stories were treated as not credible after it was discovered that they had not been in the Bolingbrook area at the times they claimed.<ref name=\"lie\"/><ref name=\"barrel\">[http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,314162,00.html ''Missing Mom Stacy Peterson's Family Wants Husband, Drew, to Take Lie Detector Test''] FoxNews.com. 30 November 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.nwherald.com/articles/2007/12/07/news/state/doc47598d8e5a34e756180246.txt ''Police say claim of Peterson sighting by trucker unfounded'']. Northwest Herald. 7 December 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/Top_News/2007/12/07/peterson_case_trucker_lied/1861/ ''Peterson case: Trucker lied''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221090837/http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/Top_News/2007/12/07/peterson_case_trucker_lied/1861/ |date=2007-12-21 }}. UPI.com. 7 December 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/Top_News/2007/11/28/relative_linked_to_stacy_peterson_case/7248/ ''Relative linked to Stacy Peterson case''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080217043102/http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/Top_News/2007/11/28/relative_linked_to_stacy_peterson_case/7248/ |date=2008-02-17 }}. UPI.com. 28 November 2007.</ref><ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=3993648 Peterson's Missing Blue Containers] Dec. 13, 2007.</ref>\n\n===2008 media appearances===\nOn January 23, 2008, Peterson and his attorney, Joel Brodsky, called in to the show of [[Chicago]] radio personality [[Steve Dahl]], who had been lampooning Peterson since the case began. Brodsky suggested that Dahl host an on-air \"dating game\" with Peterson the following day, but WJMK managers and Dahl decided not to go through with it.<ref name=\"chitrib090\">{{cite news|first=Phil|last=Rosenthal|authorlink=Phil Rosenthal|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-01-24/business/0801232291_1_drew-peterson-kathleen-savio-sexual-assault|title=Dahl draws a line on date for Drew|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=2008-01-24|accessdate=2014-10-24}}</ref> Peterson appeared on [[CNN]]'s ''[[Larry King Live]]'' on April 11, 2008, with Brodsky again present to advise which questions Peterson should answer.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0804/11/lkl.01.html | work=CNN | accessdate=2010-05-01 | title=CNN.com}}</ref> The interview reran on May 9, 2009, two days after Peterson's arrest. Peterson subsequently made guest appearances (including one from county jail) on radio station [[WLS (AM)|WLS-AM]] with [[Mancow Muller]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Associated Press 11:20 a.m. CDT, June 5, 2010 |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-ap-il-drewpeterson,0,7065419.story |title=Police investigate lead on Peterson's 4th ssdate=2010-06-06}}</ref> After that radio appearance, Will County Judge Stephen White severely limited Peterson's access to the media.\n\n===2008 engagement to Christina Raines===\nIn December 2008, Peterson's [[publicist]] Glenn Selig confirmed Peterson was engaged to a 23-year-old, Christina Raines; she would have been his fifth wife.<ref>[http://www.wbbm780.com/Drew-Peterson-Engaged/3510541 Drew Peterson Engaged].</ref> On January 30, 2009, it was made public that Raines had moved out of Peterson's house. Her father, Ernie Raines, had issued an [[ultimatum]] to his daughter out of concern about the way Peterson tried to control her and what he feared Peterson could do.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,485905,00.html |title=Drew Peterson's Fiancee Moves Out After Father Issues Ultimatum - Local News &#124; News Articles &#124; National News &#124; US News |publisher=FOXNews.com |date=2009-01-30 |accessdate=2010-06-06}}</ref> Raines moved out of Peterson's home \"when she came to her senses\", calling the engagement a publicity stunt designed to keep Peterson in the media spotlight.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/CRIME/02/02/drew.peterson.breakup/index.html | work=CNN | title=Woman calls her engagement to Drew Peterson a media stunt - CNN.com | date=2009-02-02 | accessdate=2010-05-01}}</ref>\n\n=== 2009 indictment over Savio murder ===\nOn May 7, 2009, Peterson was indicted<ref name=\"PetersonIndictment\">{{cite news |url=http://news.findlaw.com/cnn/docs/crim/drew-peterson-indictment.html|title=Indictment (Illinois v. Drew Peterson)|date=2009-05-07|publisher=FindLaw|accessdate=2009-05-08}}</ref> by a Will County [[grand jury]] and arrested for the murder of Savio.<ref name=\"arrest\">{{cite news | title =Drew Peterson Charged With Murdering Third Wife, Held on $20M Bond  | work =| location =| pages =| language =| publisher = [[Fox News]]| date = 2009-05-07\n| url = http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,519392,00.html| accessdate = 2009-05-07}}</ref> [[Bail]] was set at $20 million.<ref name=\"arrest\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobreakingnews.com/2009/05/peterson-reported-arrested.html |title=Peterson arrested on murder charges |publisher=Chicago Breaking News |date=2009-05-08 |accessdate=2010-06-06}}</ref> In October 2009, Peterson sued [[JP Morgan Chase]] for revoking a [[home equity]] credit line that he wanted to use to pay legal expenses, claiming his income of \"nearly $109,000 per year\" was not sufficient.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/peterson/1848923,drew-peterson-lawsuit-chase-102709.article |title=Drew Peterson suing JP Morgan Chase :: CHICAGO SUN-TIMES :: |publisher=Suntimes.com |date=2009-10-27 |accessdate=2010-06-06 |first=Kara |last=Spak |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100420005341/http://www.suntimes.com/news/peterson/1848923,drew-peterson-lawsuit-chase-102709.article |archive-date=2010-04-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In July 2010, Judge White ruled that Peterson would remain in the Will County Jail for the remainder of his trial and appeals process.<ref>{{Cite web\n |url          = http://www.nationalledger.com/ledgerdc/article_272633142.shtml\n |title        = Drew Peterson Jail Stay Extended by Judge\n |work         = National Ledger\n |date         = July 9, 2010\n |accessdate   = July 11, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100712234731/http://www.nationalledger.com/ledgerdc/article_272633142.shtml\n |archive-date = July 12, 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref> Prosecutors argued he could pose a danger if released.\n\nOn July 21, 2010, it was revealed that hearsay statements indicating Peterson killed two of his wives were not reliable enough for a jury to hear at his trial. After presiding over a lengthy hearing, Judge White issued a four-page sealed ruling in May obtained by the ''Daily Herald''. White ruled that prosecutors proved Peterson killed both Savio and Stacy \"by a preponderance of the evidence,\" but nearly all statements attributed to Stacy \"do not provide sufficient safeguards of reliability.\" (The standard of proof in homicide cases is \"beyond a reasonable doubt\"; \"preponderance of the evidence\" is the standard for fact-finding on questions of admissibility of evidence, even in a criminal case.) Stacy's statements were crucial to the prosecution's case, as it lacked significant direct evidence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2010/07/21/Setback-for-Peterson-prosecution/UPI-55301279728992/ |work=UPI.com |title=Setback for Peterson Prosecution |accessdate=7 August 2013}}</ref> In April 2012, an Illinois appellate court ruled that prosecutors could use eight statements made by both the victim prior to her death and by Peterson's still-missing fourth wife Stacy prior to her disappearance, reversing White's earlier decision. Peterson's defense had contended that introduction of these alleged hearsay comments constituted a violation of his [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Sixth Amendment]] right to confront any witnesses testifying against him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drew Peterson hearing set for Friday|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/05/04/justice/illinois-peterson-trial/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=4 May 2012|date=4 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Illinois State Legislature]] attempted to help the prosecution with the passage of a new Illinois law, 725 ILCS 5/115-10.6, or \"Drew's Law\", which allows prosecutors to enter hearsay statements into evidence under certain conditions. Passed while investigators were looking for Stacy, the legislation permits courts to consider statements from \"unavailable witnesses,\" provided that prosecutors are able to prove that the witness was killed to prevent his or her testimony and that the hearsay statements are reliable. Analysis by the trial court under this new law led to eight out of fourteen hearsay statements being ruled inadmissible because they were insufficiently reliable. On appeal, however, the Court of Appeals reversed the trial court, ruling that the [[common law]] doctrine of forfeiture by wrongdoing, which is less restrictive than \"Drew's Law\", would allow the statements to be admitted.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Holdridge|first1=William|title=People v. Peterson, 2012 Il App (3d) 100514-B|url=http://www.illinoiscourts.gov/opinions/appellatecourt/2012/3rddistrict/3100514.pdf|publisher=Illinois Court of Appeals, Third District}}</ref>\n\nOn August 22, 2012, Jeff Pachter, a witness at Peterson's murder trial, said Peterson offered him $25,000 to hire someone to kill Savio and told him it would be a secret he would take to his grave.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drew Peterson offered $25K to kill his third wife, witness says |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2012/08/22/drew-peterson-offered-25k-to-kill-his-third-wife-witness-says/ |publisher=Fox News |accessdate=22 August 2012 |date=22 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Verdict===\nOn September 6, 2012, Peterson was found guilty of the [[premeditation|premeditated]] murder of Savio.<ref name=\"guilty\"/> Jurors admitted that the most compelling evidence was based on the hearsay statements allowed under \"Drew's Law\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/drew-peterson-jurors-relied-hearsay-testimony/story?id=17184916|title=Drew Peterson Jury Says Hearsay Convinced Them to Convict|first=Colleen|last=Curry|date=7 September 2012}}</ref> On February 21, 2013, Peterson was sentenced to 38 years in prison for the murder of his third wife. He was incarcerated at [[Menard County, Illinois|Menard]], but later moved to the [[Federal Correctional Institution, Terre Haute]] in [[Terre Haute, Indiana]].<ref name=\"Patch\"/><ref name=\"NWHerald\"/> Within a month, he was attacked by another prisoner who hoped to sell his belongings on eBay.<ref name=\"Patch\"/>\n\nAfter a number of appeals, on September 21, 2017, the [[Illinois Supreme Court]] upheld the conviction.\n\nIn December 2019, Peterson was released from federal custody and transferred to a state facility outside of Illinois. His location is not being disclosed for security reasons.<ref name=\"Patch\"/><ref name=\"NWHerald\"/>\n\nThe Illinois Department of Corrections stated, \u201cDrew Peterson has transferred from the Federal Bureau of Prisons to a state facility outside Illinois. He remains under the jurisdiction of the Illinois Department of Corrections. For safety and security purposes, the department does not discuss details concerning the placement of offenders who have transferred under the terms of the Interstate Corrections Compact Agreement.\u201d<ref name=\"NWHerald\"/>\n\n===2015 murder-for-hire charges===\nOn February 9, 2015, Peterson was charged with attempting to put a hit on James Glasgow, the Chicago-area lead prosecutor in his murder trial, after a fellow inmate tipped off prosecutors to the plan and wore a wire to capture evidence against Peterson.<ref>{{cite web| title=Jury convicts \u2018untouchable\u2019 ex-cop Drew Peterson in murder-for-hire plot to kill prosecutor| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/06/01/jury-convicts-drew-peterson-in-murder-for-hire-plot-against-prosecutor-that-sent-him-to-prison-for-killing-his-third-wife/| date=1 June 2016}}</ref> In May 2016, he was found guilty of solicitation of murder and solicitation of murder for hire.<ref>{{cite web|title=Drew Peterson found guilty of trying to have prosecutor killed |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chi-the-drew-peterson-saga-a-timeline-20150209-htmlstory.html|date=1 June 2016}}</ref> He was subsequently sentenced to an additional 40 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|title=Drew Peterson gets 40 extra years for plot to kill prosecutor|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-drew-peterson-sentencing-met-20160729-story.html| date=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Films and documentaries ==\n* The Drew Peterson crimes and suspicions were covered in the [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|OWN]] series [[Dr. Phil (talk show)|Dr. Phil]], episode ''\"A Killer Among Us\"'', original air date: December 7, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dr. Phil: A Killer Among Us? |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/dr-phil/a-killer-among-us-1176462/ |website=TV.com |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=A Killer among Us? |url=https://plugger.drphil.com/shows/show/992/ |website=drphil.com |publisher=Peteski Productions Inc. |accessdate=28 November 2018 |language=en-us |date=7 December 2007}}</ref>\n*In June 2011, the cable television network [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] began filming ''Drew Peterson: Untouchable'', depicting the events surrounding the death of Savio and the disappearance of Stacy. [[Rob Lowe]] portrayed Peterson in the film, [[Cara Buono]] portrayed Savio, and [[Kaley Cuoco]] portrayed Stacy. Peterson filed a [[cease-and-desist letter]] demanding that production on the movie be halted.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/14/film-drewpeterson-idUSN1E76D1L920110714|title = Drew Peterson demands halt to TV movie on murder case|author=Andrew Stern |publisher=Reuters |date=July 14, 2011}}</ref> The film originally aired on January 21, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.tvguide.com/News/Rob-Lowe-Drew-Peterson-Untouchable-Video-1040919.aspx|title = Rob Lowe Sports a Mean 'Stache in Drew Peterson: Untouchable |author = Natalie Abrams|publisher = TV Guide|date=December 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2012/01/will-drew-peterson-see-rob-lowe-play-him-in-lifetime-movie-/1|title = Drew Peterson: Lifetime movie was 'hysterical' |author=Ann Oldenburg |publisher=USA Today |date=January 22, 2012}}</ref>\n* The story was covered in the [[Investigation Discovery]] documentary ''Drew Peterson: An American Murder Mystery'', which premiered on August 27, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Drew Peterson: An American Murder Mystery|url=https://www.investigationdiscovery.com/tv-shows/drew-peterson-an-american-murder-mystery/|date=August 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Chicago|Illinois|Biography}}\n* [http://news.findlaw.com/cnn/docs/crim/drew-peterson-indictment.html Indictment (Illinois v. Peterson)]\n* [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/22316689 Dateline NBC's interview with Drew Peterson]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090513003059/http://www.amw.com/fugitives/brief.cfm?id=55859 Drew Peterson featured on America's Most Wanted] \n* [https://www.scribd.com/doc/14542696/Savio-v-Peterson-Complaint Savio v. Peterson Complaint]\n* [https://www.biography.com/people/drew-peterson-259248 Biography of Drew Peterson]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peterson, Drew}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:American criminals]]\n[[Category:American police officers]]\n[[Category:2000s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:2004 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:American prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:American municipal police officers]]\n[[Category:American police officers convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:American police officers convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Crime in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American murderers]]\n[[Category:Male murderers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Bolingbrook, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Romeoville, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=[[Scott Peterson]], an individual with a similar name and case}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| image_name = \n| image_size = \n| image_caption = Will County Sheriff's Office<br />mugshot of Drew Peterson\n| birth_name = Drew Walter Peterson\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1954|01|05}}\n| birth_place = [[Bolingbrook, Illinois|Bolingbrook]], [[Illinois]], [[United States|USA]]\n| alias = \n| conviction = Premeditated [[murder]] in the 2004 death of Kathleen Savio, solicitation of [[Murder for hire]] in the attempted murder of James Glasgow\n| children = 6\n| conviction_penalty = 78 years in prison; earliest possible release May 7, 2081\n| conviction_status = [[Incarceration|Incarcerated]]\n| occupation = Former Police Officer\n| spouse = {{marriage|Carol Brown<br>|1974|1980|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Vicki Connolly<br>|1982|1992|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Kathleen Savio<br>|1992|2003|end=divorced}}<br>Stacy Ann Cales <br/>({{abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;2003\u2013?; missing since 2007)\n| parents = \n}}\n\n'''Drew Walter Peterson''' (born January 5, 1954) is a retired [[Bolingbrook, Illinois|Bolingbrook]], [[Illinois]] [[sergeant|police sergeant]] who was convicted in 2012 for the murder of his third wife, Kathleen Savio, a few months after their 2003 divorce. Peterson first received national publicity in 2007 when his fourth wife, Stacy Ann Cales Peterson, [[missing person|disappeared]]. Although the police and Stacy Ann's family suspect [[Crime|foul play]], she has never been found.\n\nSuspicions in Stacy Ann's case were fueled in part by the death of Savio, whose bruised body was found in a dry bathtub in her home in 2004, with a large gash in her scalp.<ref name=\"patch.com\">{{cite news|last1=Hosey|first1=Joseph|title=The Horror of What Kathleen Savio Went Through Before She Died|url=http://www.patch.com/illinois/bolingbrook/the-horror-of-what-kathleen-savio-went-through-before-she-died|accessdate=13 February 2017|agency=Bolingbrook Patch|date=16 August 2012}}</ref> Initially, Savio's official [[cause of death]] was found to be accidental drowning.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walberg|first1=Matthew|last2=Slife|first2=Erica|title=2004 death of Kathleen Savio ruled a homicide|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-02-22/news/0802220126_1_death-of-kathleen-savio-stacy-peterson-ruled|accessdate=13 February 2017|agency=Chicago Tribune|date=22 February 2008}}</ref> In 2009, after the attention from Stacy Ann's disappearance, Peterson was [[indictment|indicted]] for Savio's murder after a second [[autopsy]] showed evidence of a struggle. He was convicted of the murder in 2012, and was sentenced to 38 years in prison on February 21, 2013.\n\nOn February 9, 2015, Peterson was charged with two additional [[felony|felonies]] &ndash; [[solicitation of murder]] and [[contract killing|solicitation of murder for hire]] &ndash; for attempting to have [[Will County, Illinois|Will County]] [[State's Attorney]] James Glasgow killed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drew Peterson charged with attempted murder-for-hire of Illinois prosecutor|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/feb/09/drew-peterson-attempted-murder-for-hire-prosecutor|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=22 Feb 2015|date=9 Feb 2015}}</ref> Peterson was convicted on May 31, 2016, and sentenced to an additional 40 years on July 29, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Drew Peterson gets 40 extra years for plot to kill prosecutor|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-drew-peterson-sentencing-met-20160729-story.html|accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref> On February 21, 2017, he was transferred from [[Illinois Department of Corrections]] custody to the [[United States Penitentiary, Terre Haute|United States Penitentiary]] in [[Terre Haute, Indiana|Terre Haute]], [[Indiana]]. In December 2019, Peterson was transferred to an undisclosed out of state facility.<ref name=\"Patch\">{{cite news |last1=Antinori |first1=Shannon |title=Drew Peterson Moved To A New Prison \u2014 Again |url=https://patch.com/illinois/bolingbrook/drew-peterson-moved-new-prison-again |accessdate=24 March 2020 |publisher=[[Patch Meda]] |date=10 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NWHerald\">{{cite news |last1=HOSEY |first1=JOSEPH |title=Hosey: Where in the world is Drew Peterson? |url=https://www.nwherald.com/2019/12/19/hosey-where-in-the-world-is-drew-peterson/axsx0gm/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |publisher=Northwest Herald |date=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDrew Peterson graduated in 1972 from [[Willowbrook High School]] in [[Villa Park, Illinois]], where he ran [[cross country running|cross country]]. He joined the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] after graduation and briefly attended the [[College of DuPage]] in 1974 before moving to [[Falls Church, Virginia|Falls Church]], [[Virginia]] to train as a military police officer.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\">{{cite web |author=ACandyRose |url=http://www.acandyrose.com/stacy_peterson_recap.htm |title=Stacy Peterson Recap |publisher=Acandyrose.com |accessdate=7 August 2013}}</ref> Peterson began his 30-year career with the local police force in Bolingbrook, Illinois (a suburb of [[Chicago]]) in 1977.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/> In 1978, he was assigned to the Metropolitan Area Narcotics Squad, and in 1979, he received a \"Police Officer of the Year\" award from the department.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/> Peterson retired in November 2007 at age 53 with the rank of sergeant and was given a (tax-free) $79,000-a-year [[pension]] (almost $6,600-a-month).<ref>{{cite web |title=Police board hires expert in effort to strip Drew Peterson of pension |url=https://www.saukvalley.com/2013/03/05/police-board-hires-expert-in-effort-to-strip-drew-peterson-of-pension/ai3o2xm/?page=527 |last=St. Clair |first=Stacy |date=March 5, 2013 |publisher=Chicago Tribune}}</ref> His pension was terminated following his second conviction in May 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drew Peterson loses police pension day after murder-for-hire conviction |url=https://abc7chicago.com/news/drew-peterson-loses-bolingbrook-police-pension-/1369791/ |date=June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=From behind bars, Drew Peterson seeks to have police pension reinstated |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-drew-peterson-appeal-met-20160803-story.html |last=Gutowski |first=Christy |date=August 4, 2016 |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\n==Marriages==\n\n===Carol Brown===\nPeterson and Carol Brown met in high school in Villa Park and together attended his senior [[prom]].<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/><ref name=\"foxnews.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,468385,00.html |title=The Wives of Drew Peterson - Local News &#124; News Articles &#124; National News &#124; US News |publisher=FOXNews.com |date=2008-12-17 |accessdate=2010-06-06}}</ref> They married in 1974, but divorced in 1980, after Brown learned about Peterson's [[infidelity]].<ref name=\"carolbrown\">{{cite news\n| last = Barbara\n| title = Peterson says he loves, misses missing fourth wife - First wife talks, third wife reburied\n| work =| location =Indianapolis| pages =| language =| publisher = [[WLS-TV|WLS]]\n| date = 2009-05-07| url = http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news/local&id=5769607\n| accessdate = 2007-11-19 }}</ref> Together they had sons Stephen Paul Peterson (1980) and Eric Drew Peterson.<ref>http://www.hlntv.com/article/2012/07/11/talking-drew-petersons-son Eric has been estranged from their father for years, but apparently that has not affected the brothers\u2019 relationship with each other. Stephen said he and Eric get along just fine.</ref>\n\n=== Vicki Connolly ===\nPeterson married his second wife, Victoria \"Vicki\" Connolly, in 1982. They operated a bar together in [[Romeoville, Illinois|Romeoville]].<ref name=\"foxnews.com\"/> Connolly alleged a history of [[domestic violence]] during her ten-year marriage to Peterson,<ref name=\"slife\">Slife, Erika. [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-peterson_16_nov16,0,5607495.story ''EXCLUSIVE: Peterson's second wife tells her story''.] Chicago Tribune. 16 November 2007.</ref> as has her daughter, who lived in the household until she turned 17. In the wake of Stacy Ann's disappearance, Connolly told police that during their marriage, Peterson threatened to kill her and make it look like an accident.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Slife|first1=Erika|title=Peterson's second wife tells her story|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2007-11-16/news/0711160301_1_james-glasgow-drew-peterson-stacy-peterson|accessdate=13 February 2017|agency=Chicago Tribune|date=16 November 2007}}</ref> She divorced Peterson after he started dating Kathleen Savio.<ref name=\"foxnews.com\"/> Their divorce was finalized on February 18, 1992. Peterson married Savio two months later.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/>\n\n=== Kathleen Savio ===\nPeterson married accountant Kathleen Savio (born June 13, 1963 in [[Glendale Heights, Illinois]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Kathleen Savio|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/chicagotribune/obituary.aspx?pid=1994345|website=legacy.com|publisher=Chicago Tribune Media Group|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref> on May 3, 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/14542696/Savio-v-Peterson-Complaint |title=Savio v. Peterson Complaint |publisher=Scribd.com |date= |accessdate=2010-06-06}}</ref> Together they had two sons, Thomas (January 5, 1993)<ref>http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-03-19/news/ct-met-drew-peterson-son-valedictoria20110319_1_drew-peterson-bolingbrook-police-sergeant-stacy-peterson After everything, Drew Peterson's son is valedictorian.</ref><ref>http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/08/29/13549299-older-son-of-drew-peterson-kathleen-savio-says-he-believes-dad-is-innocent 19y Old Thomas Peterson Testifies.</ref> and Kristopher (August 8, 1994).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chi-drew-peterson-trial-updates-trial-enters-7th-day-after-key-ruling-20120809,0,4513046.story |title=Kristopher Peterson, who turned 18 on yesterday was in the courtroom speaking to his father this afternoon before testimony resumed after lunch |accessdate=7 August 2013 |work=Chicago Tribune |first1=Matthew |last1=Walberg |first2=Steve |last2=Schmadeke |first3=Andy |last3=Grimm |date=9 August 2012}}</ref> Their divorce was finalized on October 10, 2003.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/> It was reported that between 2002 and 2004, police were called out to the Peterson house eighteen times on domestic disturbance calls, including calls for returning children late after visitation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/May-2008/Unanswered-Cries/ |title=\"Unanswered Cries\" Chicago magazine}}</ref> On March 1, 2004,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/11/30/missing.wife.ap/index.html |title=Peterson case: Did cops protect one of their own? |work=CNN |date=2007-11-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311204059/http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/11/30/missing.wife.ap/index.html |archivedate=2008-03-11 |accessdate=7 August 2013 |df= }}</ref> Savio's body was found in a waterless bathtub. Her death was initially ruled an accidental [[drowning]] by a coroner's jury that included a police officer who personally knew Peterson and assured the other jurors that he was a good man who would never hurt his wife.<ref name=\"jury\">[http://wgnradio.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=51326&Itemid=577 ''Kathleen Savio's Family Sues Drew Peterson ''.] WGN Radio. April 21, 2009.</ref>\n\nHowever, following Stacy Peterson's later disappearance, Savio's body was exhumed and underwent [[forensic]] examination on November 16, 2007.<ref name=\"expert\">Walberg, Matthew and Jo Napolitano. [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-peterson_17nov17,1,2803259.story ''Expert: 3rd wife was slain''.] Chicago Tribune. 17 November 2007.</ref> [[Michael Baden]], a former [[New York City]] [[chief medical examiner|medical examiner]] who conducted the examination at the request of Savio's relatives and [[Fox News]], concluded that she died of drowning following a struggle when her body was placed in the bathtub. Postmortem photos showed extensive bruising and scraping to her back, torso, and face, as well as a large, unexplained gash in her scalp.<ref name=\"patch.com\"/> The results of the official autopsy ordered by the county have yet to be released to the public.<ref name=\"baden\">Tarm, Michael. [http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=3881863 ''Relatives Try to Confront Ill. Officer''.] ABC News.com. 17 November 2007.</ref> [[Will County, Illinois|Will County]] [[State's Attorney]] James Glasgow told the press that, after examining evidence in the case, he believed that the death was a \"[[homicide]] staged to look like an accident\u201d.<ref name=\"baden\"/><ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/services/newspaper/printedition/friday/chi-peterson_16_nov16,0,1765221.story  Peterson's second wife recalls threats] November 16, 2007.</ref> On February 21, 2008, Glasgow announced that a [[pathologist]] had determined that Savio's death was a homicide,<ref name=\"homicide\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/02/21/missing.wife/?iref=mpstoryview ''Death of former cop's third wife ruled a homicide'']. CNN.com. 21 February 2008.</ref> adding that the death had been investigated as such since reopening the case following the exhumation.\n\nReverend Neil Schori, a [[pastor]] at Stacy's church, reported that Stacy had told him that Drew had killed Savio and had made it look like an accident, and that she was afraid of her husband.<ref name=\"lie\">[http://www.nbc5.com/news/14710779/detail.html?rss=chi&psp=news ''Peterson's Family Demands Drew Take Lie Detector Test'']. NBC5.com. Chicago. 27 November 2007.</ref> Stacy had provided Drew's [[alibi]] for his whereabouts on the evening on which Savio died. Peterson's trial, proceeding in July 2012, was jeopardized when prosecutors attempted to introduce evidence that was not allowed. ''[[The Chicago Tribune]]'' reported that the judge would rule on a [[mistrial]] on August 2, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/ct-met-drew-peterson-trial-0802-20120802,0,5478504.story |title=Peterson judge halts testimony after defense seeks mistrial |accessdate=7 August 2013 |work=Chicago Tribune |date=1 August 2012}}</ref> On August 15, Peterson told a judge that he wanted to withdraw a request for a mistrial. His lawyers said that he wanted the current jury to decide if he killed his third wife.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tarm|first=Michael|title=DREW PETERSON WITHDRAWS REQUEST FOR MISTRIAL|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_DREW_PETERSON_TRIAL?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT|publisher=AP|accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref> On September 6, Peterson was convicted of killing Savio.<ref name=\"guilty\">{{cite news|last=Schmadeke|first=Steve|title=Peterson found guilty of murdering Savio|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-drew-peterson-found-guilty-of-murder-20120906,0,3705797.story|accessdate=September 6, 2012|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=September 6, 2012|author2=Stacy St. Clair|author3=Matthew Walberg}}</ref> On February 21, 2013, he was denied a mistrial and sentenced to 38 years in prison.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chi-drew-peterson-sentence-20130221,0,1883440.story |title=Drew Peterson transferred to Pontiac prison| work=Chicago Tribune | first1=Steve | last1=Schmadeke | first2=Matthew | last2=Walberg | first3=Stacy | last3=St. Clair | date=22 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Stacy Ann Peterson===\nAt age 49, Peterson married 19-year-old hotel receptionist Stacy Ann Cales (born January 20, 1984 in [[Downers Grove, Illinois]]) on October 18, 2003, and she subsequently changed her last name to Peterson.<ref name=\"acandyrosestacy\"/> Together they had two children, Anthony (born 2003) and Lacy (born 2005).<ref name=\"hlntv.com\">{{cite news | url = http://www.hlntv.com/article/2012/07/11/talking-drew-petersons-son | title = Drew Peterson's son: My life before his arrest | first = Beth | last = Karas | date = July 11, 2012 | work = HLN | publisher = Cable News Network, Inc. | access-date = March 21, 2018}}</ref> Stacy legally [[adoption|adopted]] Savio's children, and treated them like they were her own. She was close to completing her nursing degree from [[Joliet Junior College]] at the time of her disappearance on Sunday, October 28, 2007. Stacy was officially reported [[missing person|missing]] in the early hours of Monday, October 29, after her sister, Cassandra Cales, failed to hear from her when expected.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Peterson claims that Stacy called him at 9 p.m. on Sunday to tell him that she had left him for another man and that she had left her 2002 [[Pontiac Grand Am]] at Bolingbrook's [[Clow International Airport]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Stacy is still considered a missing person. Her family has launched a website to help find her.<ref name=searching>{{cite web|title= Stacy Peterson: Missing since October 28, 2007|url=http://www.SearchingForStacyPeterson.com/|website=Searching for Stacy Peterson|accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Legal trouble==\nSeveral leads were followed in the investigation by [[Illinois State Police]] with FBI involvement. Four search warrants were issued and carried out on Peterson's property following Stacy's disappearance, including the seizure of his firearms and both his and Stacy's vehicles. Peterson announced his plans to retire as a Bolingbrook police sergeant effective December 2007. On November 15, the Bolingbrook Police Pension Board voted to allow Peterson to collect his [[pension]] of $6,067.71 per month,<ref name=\"pension\">WBBM. [http://www.wbbm780.com/Drew-Peterson-Tells-WBBM:-My-Retirement-Sucks/1295074 ''Drew Peterson Tells Newsradio: My Retirement Sucks'']. wbbm780.com. 6 December 2007.</ref> stating current law gave them no option, as he had not been convicted of a crime.<ref name=\"slife\"/>\n\nRick Mims, Peterson's long-time friend, admitted that he and Peterson bought three blue plastic containers from a cable company where they both worked part-time in 2003, and provided photos of these containers to police. Mims also sold his story to [[tabloid newspaper]]s for an undisclosed sum of money. Peterson's stepbrother, Thomas Morphey, who has a history of drug and alcohol addiction, attempted suicide two days after allegedly helping Peterson carry a plastic container from Peterson's Bolingbrook home to his [[sport utility vehicle|SUV]], fearing he may have helped dispose of Stacy's body. Neighbors reported seeing Peterson and another man hauling a 55-gallon barrel, large enough to hold a person, out of the house shortly after the disappearance.\n\nCassandra Cales, Stacy's sister, said she wanted Peterson to take a lie detector test about his knowledge of a blue container that she saw in his garage two days before Stacy disappeared. Joel Brodsky, Peterson's attorney, denied that any container was missing from Peterson's home. There were also reports of truckers referring to the containers, but their stories were treated as not credible after it was discovered that they had not been in the Bolingbrook area at the times they claimed.<ref name=\"lie\"/><ref name=\"barrel\">[http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,314162,00.html ''Missing Mom Stacy Peterson's Family Wants Husband, Drew, to Take Lie Detector Test''] FoxNews.com. 30 November 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.nwherald.com/articles/2007/12/07/news/state/doc47598d8e5a34e756180246.txt ''Police say claim of Peterson sighting by trucker unfounded'']. Northwest Herald. 7 December 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/Top_News/2007/12/07/peterson_case_trucker_lied/1861/ ''Peterson case: Trucker lied''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221090837/http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/Top_News/2007/12/07/peterson_case_trucker_lied/1861/ |date=2007-12-21 }}. UPI.com. 7 December 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/Top_News/2007/11/28/relative_linked_to_stacy_peterson_case/7248/ ''Relative linked to Stacy Peterson case''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080217043102/http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/Top_News/2007/11/28/relative_linked_to_stacy_peterson_case/7248/ |date=2008-02-17 }}. UPI.com. 28 November 2007.</ref><ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=3993648 Peterson's Missing Blue Containers] Dec. 13, 2007.</ref>\n\n===2008 media appearances===\nOn January 23, 2008, Peterson and his attorney, Joel Brodsky, called in to the show of [[Chicago]] radio personality [[Steve Dahl]], who had been lampooning Peterson since the case began. Brodsky suggested that Dahl host an on-air \"dating game\" with Peterson the following day, but WJMK managers and Dahl decided not to go through with it.<ref name=\"chitrib090\">{{cite news|first=Phil|last=Rosenthal|authorlink=Phil Rosenthal|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-01-24/business/0801232291_1_drew-peterson-kathleen-savio-sexual-assault|title=Dahl draws a line on date for Drew|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=2008-01-24|accessdate=2014-10-24}}</ref> Peterson appeared on [[CNN]]'s ''[[Larry King Live]]'' on April 11, 2008, with Brodsky again present to advise which questions Peterson should answer.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0804/11/lkl.01.html | work=CNN | accessdate=2010-05-01 | title=CNN.com}}</ref> The interview reran on May 9, 2009, two days after Peterson's arrest. Peterson subsequently made guest appearances (including one from county jail) on radio station [[WLS (AM)|WLS-AM]] with [[Mancow Muller]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Associated Press 11:20 a.m. CDT, June 5, 2010 |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-ap-il-drewpeterson,0,7065419.story |title=Police investigate lead on Peterson's 4th ssdate=2010-06-06}}</ref> After that radio appearance, Will County Judge Stephen White severely limited Peterson's access to the media.\n\n===2008 engagement to Christina Raines===\nIn December 2008, Peterson's [[publicist]] Glenn Selig confirmed Peterson was engaged to a 23-year-old, Christina Raines; she would have been his fifth wife.<ref>[http://www.wbbm780.com/Drew-Peterson-Engaged/3510541 Drew Peterson Engaged].</ref> On January 30, 2009, it was made public that Raines had moved out of Peterson's house. Her father, Ernie Raines, had issued an [[ultimatum]] to his daughter out of concern about the way Peterson tried to control her and what he feared Peterson could do.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,485905,00.html |title=Drew Peterson's Fiancee Moves Out After Father Issues Ultimatum - Local News &#124; News Articles &#124; National News &#124; US News |publisher=FOXNews.com |date=2009-01-30 |accessdate=2010-06-06}}</ref> Raines moved out of Peterson's home \"when she came to her senses\", calling the engagement a publicity stunt designed to keep Peterson in the media spotlight.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/CRIME/02/02/drew.peterson.breakup/index.html | work=CNN | title=Woman calls her engagement to Drew Peterson a media stunt - CNN.com | date=2009-02-02 | accessdate=2010-05-01}}</ref>\n\n=== 2009 indictment over Savio murder ===\nOn May 7, 2009, Peterson was indicted<ref name=\"PetersonIndictment\">{{cite news |url=http://news.findlaw.com/cnn/docs/crim/drew-peterson-indictment.html|title=Indictment (Illinois v. Drew Peterson)|date=2009-05-07|publisher=FindLaw|accessdate=2009-05-08}}</ref> by a Will County [[grand jury]] and arrested for the murder of Savio.<ref name=\"arrest\">{{cite news | title =Drew Peterson Charged With Murdering Third Wife, Held on $20M Bond  | work =| location =| pages =| language =| publisher = [[Fox News]]| date = 2009-05-07\n| url = http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,519392,00.html| accessdate = 2009-05-07}}</ref> [[Bail]] was set at $20 million.<ref name=\"arrest\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobreakingnews.com/2009/05/peterson-reported-arrested.html |title=Peterson arrested on murder charges |publisher=Chicago Breaking News |date=2009-05-08 |accessdate=2010-06-06}}</ref> In October 2009, Peterson sued [[JP Morgan Chase]] for revoking a [[home equity]] credit line that he wanted to use to pay legal expenses, claiming his income of \"nearly $109,000 per year\" was not sufficient.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/peterson/1848923,drew-peterson-lawsuit-chase-102709.article |title=Drew Peterson suing JP Morgan Chase :: CHICAGO SUN-TIMES :: |publisher=Suntimes.com |date=2009-10-27 |accessdate=2010-06-06 |first=Kara |last=Spak |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100420005341/http://www.suntimes.com/news/peterson/1848923,drew-peterson-lawsuit-chase-102709.article |archive-date=2010-04-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In July 2010, Judge White ruled that Peterson would remain in the Will County Jail for the remainder of his trial and appeals process.<ref>{{Cite web\n |url          = http://www.nationalledger.com/ledgerdc/article_272633142.shtml\n |title        = Drew Peterson Jail Stay Extended by Judge\n |work         = National Ledger\n |date         = July 9, 2010\n |accessdate   = July 11, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100712234731/http://www.nationalledger.com/ledgerdc/article_272633142.shtml\n |archive-date = July 12, 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref> Prosecutors argued he could pose a danger if released.\n\nOn July 21, 2010, it was revealed that hearsay statements indicating Peterson killed two of his wives were not reliable enough for a jury to hear at his trial. After presiding over a lengthy hearing, Judge White issued a four-page sealed ruling in May obtained by the ''Daily Herald''. White ruled that prosecutors proved Peterson killed both Savio and Stacy \"by a preponderance of the evidence,\" but nearly all statements attributed to Stacy \"do not provide sufficient safeguards of reliability.\" (The standard of proof in homicide cases is \"beyond a reasonable doubt\"; \"preponderance of the evidence\" is the standard for fact-finding on questions of admissibility of evidence, even in a criminal case.) Stacy's statements were crucial to the prosecution's case, as it lacked significant direct evidence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2010/07/21/Setback-for-Peterson-prosecution/UPI-55301279728992/ |work=UPI.com |title=Setback for Peterson Prosecution |accessdate=7 August 2013}}</ref> In April 2012, an Illinois appellate court ruled that prosecutors could use eight statements made by both the victim prior to her death and by Peterson's still-missing fourth wife Stacy prior to her disappearance, reversing White's earlier decision. Peterson's defense had contended that introduction of these alleged hearsay comments constituted a violation of his [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Sixth Amendment]] right to confront any witnesses testifying against him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drew Peterson hearing set for Friday|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/05/04/justice/illinois-peterson-trial/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=4 May 2012|date=4 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Illinois State Legislature]] attempted to help the prosecution with the passage of a new Illinois law, 725 ILCS 5/115-10.6, or \"Drew's Law\", which allows prosecutors to enter hearsay statements into evidence under certain conditions. Passed while investigators were looking for Stacy, the legislation permits courts to consider statements from \"unavailable witnesses,\" provided that prosecutors are able to prove that the witness was killed to prevent his or her testimony and that the hearsay statements are reliable. Analysis by the trial court under this new law led to eight out of fourteen hearsay statements being ruled inadmissible because they were insufficiently reliable. On appeal, however, the Court of Appeals reversed the trial court, ruling that the [[common law]] doctrine of forfeiture by wrongdoing, which is less restrictive than \"Drew's Law\", would allow the statements to be admitted.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Holdridge|first1=William|title=People v. Peterson, 2012 Il App (3d) 100514-B|url=http://www.illinoiscourts.gov/opinions/appellatecourt/2012/3rddistrict/3100514.pdf|publisher=Illinois Court of Appeals, Third District}}</ref>\n\nOn August 22, 2012, Jeff Pachter, a witness at Peterson's murder trial, said Peterson offered him $25,000 to hire someone to kill Savio and told him it would be a secret he would take to his grave.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drew Peterson offered $25K to kill his third wife, witness says |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2012/08/22/drew-peterson-offered-25k-to-kill-his-third-wife-witness-says/ |publisher=Fox News |accessdate=22 August 2012 |date=22 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Verdict===\nOn September 6, 2012, Peterson was found guilty of the [[premeditation|premeditated]] murder of Savio.<ref name=\"guilty\"/> Jurors admitted that the most compelling evidence was based on the hearsay statements allowed under \"Drew's Law\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/drew-peterson-jurors-relied-hearsay-testimony/story?id=17184916|title=Drew Peterson Jury Says Hearsay Convinced Them to Convict|first=Colleen|last=Curry|date=7 September 2012}}</ref> On February 21, 2013, Peterson was sentenced to 38 years in prison for the murder of his third wife. He was incarcerated at [[Menard]], but later moved to the [[Federal Correctional Institution, Terre Haute]] in [[Terre Haute, Indiana]].<ref name=\"Patch\"/><ref name=\"NWHerald\"/> Within a month, he was attacked by another prisoner who hoped to sell his belongings on eBay.<ref name=\"Patch\"/>\n\nAfter a number of appeals, on September 21, 2017, the [[Illinois Supreme Court]] upheld the conviction.\n\nIn December 2019, Peterson was released from federal custody and transferred to a state facility outside of Illinois. His location is not being disclosed for security reasons.<ref name=\"Patch\"/><ref name=\"NWHerald\"/>\n\nThe Illinois Department of Corrections stated, \u201cDrew Peterson has transferred from the Federal Bureau of Prisons to a state facility outside Illinois. He remains under the jurisdiction of the Illinois Department of Corrections. For safety and security purposes, the department does not discuss details concerning the placement of offenders who have transferred under the terms of the Interstate Corrections Compact Agreement.\u201d<ref name=\"NWHerald\"/>\n\n===2015 murder-for-hire charges===\nOn February 9, 2015, Peterson was charged with attempting to put a hit on James Glasgow, the Chicago-area lead prosecutor in his murder trial, after a fellow inmate tipped off prosecutors to the plan and wore a wire to capture evidence against Peterson.<ref>{{cite web| title=Jury convicts \u2018untouchable\u2019 ex-cop Drew Peterson in murder-for-hire plot to kill prosecutor| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/06/01/jury-convicts-drew-peterson-in-murder-for-hire-plot-against-prosecutor-that-sent-him-to-prison-for-killing-his-third-wife/| date=1 June 2016}}</ref> In May 2016, he was found guilty of solicitation of murder and solicitation of murder for hire.<ref>{{cite web|title=Drew Peterson found guilty of trying to have prosecutor killed |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chi-the-drew-peterson-saga-a-timeline-20150209-htmlstory.html|date=1 June 2016}}</ref> He was subsequently sentenced to an additional 40 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|title=Drew Peterson gets 40 extra years for plot to kill prosecutor|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-drew-peterson-sentencing-met-20160729-story.html| date=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Films and documentaries ==\n* The Drew Peterson crimes and suspicions were covered in the [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|OWN]] series [[Dr. Phil (talk show)|Dr. Phil]], episode ''\"A Killer Among Us\"'', original air date: December 7, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dr. Phil: A Killer Among Us? |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/dr-phil/a-killer-among-us-1176462/ |website=TV.com |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=A Killer among Us? |url=https://plugger.drphil.com/shows/show/992/ |website=drphil.com |publisher=Peteski Productions Inc. |accessdate=28 November 2018 |language=en-us |date=7 December 2007}}</ref>\n*In June 2011, the cable television network [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] began filming ''Drew Peterson: Untouchable'', depicting the events surrounding the death of Savio and the disappearance of Stacy. [[Rob Lowe]] portrayed Peterson in the film, [[Cara Buono]] portrayed Savio, and [[Kaley Cuoco]] portrayed Stacy. Peterson filed a [[cease-and-desist letter]] demanding that production on the movie be halted.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/14/film-drewpeterson-idUSN1E76D1L920110714|title = Drew Peterson demands halt to TV movie on murder case|author=Andrew Stern |publisher=Reuters |date=July 14, 2011}}</ref> The film originally aired on January 21, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.tvguide.com/News/Rob-Lowe-Drew-Peterson-Untouchable-Video-1040919.aspx|title = Rob Lowe Sports a Mean 'Stache in Drew Peterson: Untouchable |author = Natalie Abrams|publisher = TV Guide|date=December 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2012/01/will-drew-peterson-see-rob-lowe-play-him-in-lifetime-movie-/1|title = Drew Peterson: Lifetime movie was 'hysterical' |author=Ann Oldenburg |publisher=USA Today |date=January 22, 2012}}</ref>\n* The story was covered in the [[Investigation Discovery]] documentary ''Drew Peterson: An American Murder Mystery'', which premiered on August 27, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Drew Peterson: An American Murder Mystery|url=https://www.investigationdiscovery.com/tv-shows/drew-peterson-an-american-murder-mystery/|date=August 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Chicago|Illinois|Biography}}\n* [http://news.findlaw.com/cnn/docs/crim/drew-peterson-indictment.html Indictment (Illinois v. Peterson)]\n* [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/22316689 Dateline NBC's interview with Drew Peterson]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090513003059/http://www.amw.com/fugitives/brief.cfm?id=55859 Drew Peterson featured on America's Most Wanted] \n* [https://www.scribd.com/doc/14542696/Savio-v-Peterson-Complaint Savio v. Peterson Complaint]\n* [https://www.biography.com/people/drew-peterson-259248 Biography of Drew Peterson]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peterson, Drew}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:American criminals]]\n[[Category:American police officers]]\n[[Category:2000s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:2004 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:American prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:American municipal police officers]]\n[[Category:American police officers convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:American police officers convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Crime in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American murderers]]\n[[Category:Male murderers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Bolingbrook, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Romeoville, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMenard(link changed toMenard County, Illinois) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drew_Peterson"}
{"title_page": "Pin Point, Georgia", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name            =\n| image_skyline            =\n| image_flag               =\n| image_seal               =\n| nickname                 =\n| motto                    =\n| pushpin_map              = USA Georgia\n| pushpin_map_caption      = Map showing the location of Pin Point, Georgia\n| coordinates              = {{coord|31|57|11|N|81|05|33|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type         = Country\n| subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1        = State\n| subdivision_name1        = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| subdivision_type2        = County\n| subdivision_name2        = [[Chatham County, Georgia|Chatham County]]\n| established_title        =\n| established_date         =\n| government_type          =\n| leader_title             =\n| leader_name              =\n| area_total_km2           =\n| area_total_sq_mi         =\n| area_land_km2            =\n| area_land_sq_mi          =\n| area_water_km2           =\n| area_water_sq_mi         =\n| elevation_footnotes      =\n| elevation_m              =\n| elevation_ft             =\n| population_footnotes     =\n| population_total         =\n| population_as_of         =\n| population_density_km2   =\n| population_density_sq_mi =\n| population_urban         =\n| population_metro         =\n| timezone                 =\n| utc_offset               =\n| timezone_DST             =\n| utc_offset_DST           =\n| website                  =\n| footnotes                =\n}}\n'''Pin Point''' is an [[unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Chatham County, Georgia|Chatham County]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], United States; it is located {{convert|11|mi|km}} southeast of [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]]. Pin Point is part of the Savannah [[Savannah metropolitan area|Metropolitan Statistical Area]].<ref>[http://georgia.hometownlocator.com/ga/chatham/pin-point.cfm Pin Point, Georgia]</ref>\n\nThe town is best known as the birthplace of [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] Justice [[Clarence Thomas]] on June 23, 1948.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/04/21/AR2007042101475.html?hpid=moreheadlines |title=Justice Thomas's Life A Tangle of Poverty, Privilege and Race|first1=Kevin |last1=Merida |first2=Michael A.|last2= Fletcher|date=22 April 2007|accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nA rural settlement founded by freed [[slavery|slaves]] after the [[American Civil War]],<ref name=\"MayerAbramson1995\">{{cite book|last1=Mayer|first1=Jane|last2=Abramson|first2=Jill|title=Strange Justice: The Selling of Clarence Thomas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uJfWAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=30 October 2011|date=6 November 1995|publisher=Plume|isbn=978-0-452-27499-0|page=33}}</ref> Pin Point is {{convert|1|mi|km|abbr=on}} wide and {{convert|1.6|mi|km|abbr=on}} long.\n\nPin Point is a small, predominantly African American community that has a well-established group of [[Gullah language|Gullah]] speakers.\n\n[http://www.chsgeorgia.org/PHM Pin Point Heritage Museum] was once the Varn and Sons Oyster Canning Factory and offers guests the chance to experience the Gullah/Geechee way of life from religion, to foodways, to the fascinating history.\n\n==Notable residents==\n[[Clarence Thomas]], an American judge, lawyer, and government official who currently serves as an [[Associate Justice|Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/chatham/pin-point-community Pin Point Community] historical marker\n  \n{{Chatham County, Georgia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Chatham County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Savannah metropolitan area]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name            =\n| image_skyline            =\n| image_flag               =\n| image_seal               =\n| nickname                 =\n| motto                    =\n| pushpin_map              = USA Georgia\n| pushpin_map_caption      = Map showing the location of Pin Point, Georgia\n| coordinates              = {{coord|31|57|11|N|81|05|33|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type         = Country\n| subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1        = State\n| subdivision_name1        = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| subdivision_type2        = County\n| subdivision_name2        = [[Chatham County, Georgia|Chatham County]]\n| established_title        =\n| established_date         =\n| government_type          =\n| leader_title             =\n| leader_name              =\n| area_total_km2           =\n| area_total_sq_mi         =\n| area_land_km2            =\n| area_land_sq_mi          =\n| area_water_km2           =\n| area_water_sq_mi         =\n| elevation_footnotes      =\n| elevation_m              =\n| elevation_ft             =\n| population_footnotes     =\n| population_total         =\n| population_as_of         =\n| population_density_km2   =\n| population_density_sq_mi =\n| population_urban         =\n| population_metro         =\n| timezone                 =\n| utc_offset               =\n| timezone_DST             =\n| utc_offset_DST           =\n| website                  =\n| footnotes                =\n}}\n'''Pin Point''' is an [[unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Chatham County, Georgia|Chatham County]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], United States; it is located {{convert|11|mi|km|abbr=on}} southeast of [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]]. Pin Point is part of the Savannah [[Savannah metropolitan area|Metropolitan Statistical Area]].<ref>[http://georgia.hometownlocator.com/ga/chatham/pin-point.cfm Pin Point, Georgia]</ref>\n\nThe town is best known as the birthplace of [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] Justice [[Clarence Thomas]] on June 23, 1948.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/04/21/AR2007042101475.html?hpid=moreheadlines |title=Justice Thomas's Life A Tangle of Poverty, Privilege and Race|first1=Kevin |last1=Merida |first2=Michael A.|last2= Fletcher|date=22 April 2007|accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nA rural settlement founded by freed [[slavery|slaves]] after the [[American Civil War]],<ref name=\"MayerAbramson1995\">{{cite book|last1=Mayer|first1=Jane|last2=Abramson|first2=Jill|title=Strange Justice: The Selling of Clarence Thomas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uJfWAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=30 October 2011|date=6 November 1995|publisher=Plume|isbn=978-0-452-27499-0|page=33}}</ref> Pin Point is {{convert|1|mi|km|,|abbr=on}} wide and {{convert|1.6|mi|km|abbr=on}} long.\n\nPin Point is a small, predominantly African American community that has a well-established group of [[Gullah language|Gullah]] speakers.\n\n[http://www.chsgeorgia.org/PHM Pin Point Heritage Museum] was once the Varn and Sons Oyster Canning Factory and offers guests the chance to experience the Gullah/Geechee way of life from religion, to foodways, to the fascinating history.\n\n==Notable residents==\n[[Clarence Thomas]], an American judge, lawyer, and government official who currently serves as an [[Associate Justice|Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/chatham/pin-point-community Pin Point Community] historical marker\n  \n{{Chatham County, Georgia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Chatham County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Savannah metropolitan area]]\n", "name_user": "DePiep", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix {{convert}} input error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pin_Point,_Georgia"}
{"title_page": "UFO discography", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist          = [[UFO (band)|UFO]]\n| Image           =\n| Caption         =\n| Studio          = 22\n| Live            = 14\n| Compilation     = 16\n| Video           = 2\n| Singles         = 11\n}}\n\nThe following is a comprehensive discography of [[UFO (band)|UFO]], an [[England|English]] [[hard rock]] band formed in 1968. The band became a transitional band between early [[hard rock]] and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] and the [[new wave of British heavy metal]]. UFO's influence was strongly felt in the 1980s heavy metal scene and they have been cited as a primary influence of [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] of [[Iron Maiden]], [[Kirk Hammett]] of [[Metallica]], [[Dave Mustaine]] of [[Megadeth]], [[Joey Tempest]] of [[Europe (band)|Europe]], [[Frank Hannon]] of [[Tesla (band)|Tesla]], and [[Mike McCready]] of [[Pearl Jam]], among others.\n\n==Albums==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class =\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=\"230\"|title\n!colspan=\"2\"|Peak chart positions\n!rowspan=\"2\"|[[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<br /><ref name=\"BPI\">{{cite web| title=The BPI - Search the Awards Database |url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/ |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=2008-05-31}}</ref>\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|[[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web| url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=sepultura|chart=all}} |title=Artist Chart History - UFO |publisher=[[Billboard charts]] |accessdate=2008-05-31}}</ref> \n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|[[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br /><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web| url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artists/ |title=The Official Charts Company - UFO |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=2008-06-25}}</ref>\n|-\n|1970\n|''[[UFO 1]]''\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|align=\"left\"| \n|-\n|1971\n|''[[UFO 2: Flying]]''\n|al