{"title_page": "Katrina McClain Award", "text_new": "{{Infobox award\n| name           = Katrina McClain Award\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| description    = The best women's college basketball power forward in the United States\n| presenter      = [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame]] & <br>[[Women's Basketball Coaches Association]] (WBCA)\n| country        = [[United States]]\n| location       =\n| year           = 2018\n| holder         = [[Ruthy Hebard]], [[2019\u201320 Oregon Ducks women's basketball team|Oregon]]\n| website        = [http://www.hoophallawards.com/mcclain.php Katrina McClain Award]\n}}\nThe '''Katrina McClain Award''' is an award presented annually to the best women's basketball [[Power forward (basketball)|power forward]] in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] competition. It is named after Hall of Famer [[Katrina McClain|Katrina McClain-Pittman]], a two-time USA Basketball Female Athlete of the Year with two Olympic gold, one Olympic bronze, and three FIBA World Championships medals. McClain was the WBCA National Player of the Year in her senior season at [[Georgia Bulldogs women's basketball|Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hoophall.com/news/naismith-memorial-basketball-hall-of-fame-wbca-announce-four-new-womens-college-basketball-awards/|title=The Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame :: Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame, WBCA Announce Four New Women\u2019s College Basketball Awards|website=www.hoophall.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> \n\nThe Katrina McClain Award was first presented in 2018, when WBCA and the Naismith Hall, in collaboration with ESPN, incorporated the [[Nancy Lieberman Award]], presented since 2000 to the top NCAA women's point guard, into a new set of awards known as the \"Naismith Starting Five\". All five awards are presented at the WBCA convention (except in 2020, when the convention was not held due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]) to players at each of the five traditional basketball positions. These awards parallel a previously existing set of men's basketball positional awards also presented by the Hall. In addition to the Lieberman Award, the other three new awards are:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbca.org/recognize/player-awards/naismith-starting-5 |title=Naismith Starting 5 |publisher=Women's Basketball Coaches Association |accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Ann Meyers Drysdale Award|Ann Meyers Drysdale Shooting Guard Award]]\n* [[Cheryl Miller Award|Cheryl Miller Small Forward Award]]\n* [[Lisa Leslie Award|Lisa Leslie Center Award]]\n\nWinner for each of the Starting Five awards is determined by a selection committee consisting of Hall of Famers, WBCA coaching members, and media, and headed by the award's namesake. Fan voting through the Hall's website is also incorporated into the selection process.\n\n==Key==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:#FFE6BD\" |*\n|Awarded, in addition, a national Player of the Year award: <br>the [[Naismith College Player of the Year]], [[Wade Trophy]] or the [[John R. Wooden Award]]\n|-\n|Player (X)\n|Denotes the number of times the player has received the Katrina McClain Award\n|}\n\n==Winners== \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Season\n!Player\n!School\n!Class\n!Ref.\n|-\n| [[2017\u201318 NCAA Division I women's basketball season|2017\u201318]]\n| {{sortname|Ruthy|Hebard}}\n| [[2017\u201318 Oregon Ducks women's basketball team|Oregon]]\n| {{sort|2|Sophomore}}\n| \n|-\n| [[2018\u201319 NCAA Division I women's basketball season|2018\u201319]]\n| {{sortname|Napheesa|Collier}}\n| [[2018\u201319 UConn Huskies women's basketball team|UConn]]\n| {{sort|4|Senior}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hoophall.com/news/naismith-memorial-basketball-hall-of-fame-wbca-name-winners-of-five-womens-college-basketball-awards/|title=The Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame :: Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame, WBCA Name Winners of Five Women\u2019s College Basketball Awards|website=www.hoophall.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I women's basketball season|2019\u201320]]\n| {{sortname|Ruthy|Hebard}} <small>(2)</small>\n| [[2019\u201320 Oregon Ducks women's basketball team|Oregon]]\n| {{sort|4|Senior}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hoophall.com/news/naismith-memorial-basketball-hall-of-fame-wbca-name-winners-of-five-womens-college-basketball-awards1/|title=The Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame :: Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame, WBCA Name Winners of Five Women\u2019s College Basketball Awards|website=www.hoophall.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Winners by school==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"; style=\"text-align:center\";\n|-\n!School !! Winners || class=\"unsortable\"| Years\n|-\n| [[Oregon Ducks women's basketball|Oregon]] || 2 || 2018, 2020\n|-\n| [[UConn Huskies women's basketball|UConn]] || 1 || 2019\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Karl Malone Award]] \u2013 the counterpart to the McClain Award; given to the best men's NCAA power forward\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hoophallawards.com/mcclain.php Official website]\n\n{{Women's college basketball award navbox}}\n{{Katrina McClain Award}}\n\n[[Category:College basketball player of the year awards in the United States]]\n[[Category:College basketball trophies and awards in the United States]]\n[[Category:College women's basketball in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sports awards honoring women]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 2018]]\n[[Category:College sports trophies and awards in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox award\n| name           = Katrina McClain Award\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| description    = The best women's college basketball power f