{"title_page": "Kary Mullis", "text_new": "{{Short description|American biochemist}}{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name=Kary Mullis\n| image = Kary Mullis.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Mullis in 2006\n| birth_name = Kary Banks Mullis\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1944|12|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Lenoir, North Carolina]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2019|08|07|1944|12|28}}\n| death_place = [[Newport Beach, California]], U.S.<ref name=\"death1\" /><ref name=\"death2\" />\n| nationality = American\n| field = [[Molecular biology]]\n| work_institution = \n| thesis_title = Schizokinen: structure and synthetic work\n| thesis_url = http://www.worldcat.org/title/schizokinen-structure-and-synthetic-work/oclc/17971376&referer=brief_results\n| thesis_year = 1973\n| alma_mater = [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] <small>(BS, 1966)</small><br />[[University of California, Berkeley]] <small>(PhD, 1973)</small>\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Joe Neilands|J. B. Neilands]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for = Invention of [[polymerase chain reaction]]\n| prizes = {{Nowrap|[[William Allan Award]] {{Small|(1990)}}<br />[[Robert Koch Prize]] <small>(1992)</small><br />[[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] <small>(1993)</small><br />[[Japan Prize]] <small>(1993)</small><ref name=jp>[http://www.japanprize.jp/en/laureates_by_year1990.html Laureates of the Japan Prize]. japanprize.jp</ref>\n}}\n| religion = \n| footnotes = <!-- | parents=Cecil Banks Mullis and Bernice Alberta Barker Mullis<ref name=nobelbio /> unsuppored parameter -->\n}}\n\n'''Kary Banks Mullis''' (December 28, 1944&nbsp;\u2013 August 7, 2019) was an American [[biochemistry|biochemist]]. In recognition of his invention of the [[polymerase chain reaction]] (PCR) technique, he shared the 1993 [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] with [[Michael Smith (chemist)|Michael Smith]]<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last1=Shampo | first1=M. A.\n| last2=Kyle | first2=R. A.\n| title=Kary B. Mullis&nbsp;\u2014 Nobel Laureate for procedure to replicate DNA\n| journal=Proceedings | publisher=Mayo Clinic\n| volume=77\n| issue=7\n| page=606\n| year=2002\n| pmid=12108595\n| doi=10.4065/77.7.606\n| doi-access=free\n}}</ref> and was awarded the [[Japan Prize]] in the same year. His invention became a central technique in [[biochemistry]] and [[molecular biology]], described by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as \"highly original and significant, virtually dividing biology into the two epochs of before PCR and after PCR.\"<ref name=\"NYTimes1998\" />\n\n== Early life ==\nMullis was born in [[Lenoir, North Carolina]], near the [[Blue Ridge Mountains]],<ref name=\"nobelbio\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/chemistry/1993/mullis/biographical/ |title= Autobiography |publisher=Nobel prize |date=March 21, 1998 |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> on December 28, 1944. His family had a background in farming in this rural area. As a child, Mullis said, he was interested in observing organisms in the countryside.<ref name=\"biotechnology101\">{{Cite book| url= https://archive.org/details/biotechnology1010000shma | url-access= registration | page= [https://archive.org/details/biotechnology1010000shma/page/184 184] | quote= kary mullis. | title=Biotechnology 101 | publisher= Greenwood Press | first=Brian Robert | last=Shmaefsky |date= October 30, 2006|access-date=July 27, 2010|isbn=978-0-313-33528-0}}</ref> He grew up in [[Columbia, South Carolina]],<ref name=\"biotechnology101\" /> where he attended [[Dreher High School]]<ref name=nobellecture>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/1993/mullis-lecture.html|title=Nobel Lecture \u2013 The Polymerase Chain Reaction|publisher=nobelprize.org|author=Kary Mullis|date=December 8, 1993}}</ref>, graduating in the class of 1962. His interest in chemistry started when he learned how to chemically synthesize and build solid fuel propulsion rockets as a high school student during the 1950s.<ref>[https://www.ted.com/talks/kary_mullis_on_what_scientists_do?language=en Kary Mullis: Play! Experiment! Discover! | TED Talk]. TED.com. Retrieved on May 9, 2016.</ref>\n\nHe earned a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] in [[chemistry]]<ref name=\"nobelbio\" /> from the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] in [[Atlanta]] in 1966, during which time he married his first wife and started a business.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\">{{Citation| last=Yoffe| first=Emily | authorlink=Emily Yoffe| publisher=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]| title=Is Kary Mullis God? Nobel Prize winner's new life| volume=122 | number=1 |date=July 1994 | pages=68\u201375}}</ref> He earned his [[Ph.D.]] in 1973 in [[biochemistry]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], in [[Joe Neilands|J. B. Neilands]]' laboratory, which focused on synthesis and structure of bacterial iron transporter molecules.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Kary Banks |last=Mullis |title=Schizokinen: Structure and Synthetic Work |url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/302680803/5655A51FB3D04612PQ/ |work=[[ProQuest]] |date=1973 |access-date=July 6, 2017}}</ref> As a graduate student, he published a sole-author paper in ''Nature'' in the field of [[astrophysics]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MULLIS|first=KARY|date=1968|title=Cosmological Significance of Time Reversal|journal=Nature|volume=218|issue=5142|pages=663\u2013664|doi=10.1038/218663b0|issn=0028-0836|bibcode=1968Natur.218..663M|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/9bedef8385043ca9603539ce73ae5f144dcd84eb}}</ref> Following his graduation, Mullis completed postdoctoral fellowships in pediatric [[cardiology]] at the [[University of Kansas Medical Center]] (1973-1977) and [[pharmaceutical chemistry]] at the [[University of California, San Francisco]] (1977-1979).<ref name=\":2\">http://www.karymullis.com/pdf/karymullis-cv.pdf</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter receiving his doctorate, Mullis briefly left science to write fiction before accepting the University of Kansas fellowship.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> During his postdoctoral work, he managed a bakery for two years.<ref name=\"NYTimes1998\">{{Citation | url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802E7DD1331F936A2575AC0A96E958260 | title=Scientist at Work/Kary Mullis; After the 'Eureka', a Nobelist Drops Out | first=Nicholas | last=Wade | journal=[[The New York Times]] | date=September 15, 1998}}</ref> Mullis returned to science at the encouragement of friend [[Thomas White]], who later helped Mullis land a position with the biotechnology company [[Cetus Corporation]] of [[Emeryville, California]].<ref name=\"biotechnology101\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes1998\" /> Mullis worked as a [[DNA]] [[chemist]] at Cetus for seven years; it was there, in 1983, that Mullis invented the polymerase chain reaction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/science/tq/displayStory.cfm?Story_id=2477036 |title= The Economist |date= March 13, 2004|access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> After leaving Cetus in 1986, Mullis served as director of molecular biology for Xytronyx, Inc. in [[San Diego]] for two years. While inventing a UV-sensitive ink at Xytronyx, he became skeptical of the existence of the ozone hole.\n\nMullis served as a consultant for multiple corporations on nucleic acid chemistry.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes1998\" /> While writing a National Institutes of Health grant progress report on the development of a human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) test for Specialty Labs, he became skeptical that HIV was the cause of acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS).<ref name=\"Naked\" /> In 1992, Mullis founded a business to sell pieces of jewelry containing the amplified DNA of deceased famous people such as [[Elvis Presley]] and [[Marilyn Monroe]].<ref name=\"lifeonedge\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.questia.com/googleScholar.qst;jsessionid=HL2GySNR8dj13v4D64WDGhlzhN8Fkspv6nJF6JwngX1NzhyfwZlK!930663388?docId=5002303854 |title= The Hastings Center Report |pages= 30 | year=1998 |publisher=Questia |access-date=July 27, 2010|last1= Andrews |first1= Lori |last2= Nelkin |first2= Dorothy }}</ref> Also in 1992 he founded [[Atomic Tags]], in La Jolla, California. Atomic Tags sought to develop technology using atomic-force microscopy and bar-coded antibodies tagged with heavy metals to create highly multiplexed, parallel immunoassays.\n\nMullis was a member of the [[USA Science and Engineering Festival]]'s Advisory Board.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.usasciencefestival.org/about/advisors |title=Advisors |publisher=USA science festival |date= |access-date=July 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100421005310/http://www.usasciencefestival.org/about/advisors/ |archivedate=April 21, 2010 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2014, he was named a distinguished researcher at the [[Children's Hospital Oakland Research Institute]] in [[Oakland, California]].<ref name=\"website\">[http://www.karymullis.com/biography.shtml Dr. Kary Banks Mullis]. Karymullis.com. Retrieved on May 9, 2016.</ref>\n\n=== PCR and other inventions ===\n{{Main|Taq Polymerase|History of polymerase chain reaction}}\nIn 1983, Mullis was working for [[Cetus Corporation]] as a chemist.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Late one night while driving with his girlfriend, who was also a chemist at Cetus, he had the idea to use a pair of primers to bracket the desired DNA sequence and to copy it using DNA polymerase; a technique that would allow rapid amplification of a small stretch of DNA and become a standard procedure in molecular biology laboratories.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Cetus took Mullis off his usual projects to concentrate on PCR full-time.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Mullis succeeded in demonstrating PCR December 16, 1983.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> In his Nobel Prize lecture, he remarked that the success did not make up for his girlfriend breaking up with him. \"I was sagging as I walked out to my little silver [[Honda Civic]]. Neither [assistant] Fred, empty Beck's bottles, nor the sweet smell of the dawn of the age of PCR could replace Jenny. I was lonesome.\"<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> He received a $10,000 bonus from Cetus for the invention.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" />\n\nOther Cetus scientists, including [[Randall Saiki]] and [[Henry Erlich]], were placed on PCR projects to work on determining if PCR could amplify a specific human gene ([[betaglobin]]) from genomic DNA. Saiki generated the needed data and Erlich authored the first paper to include utilization of the technique,<ref name=\"NYTimes1998\" /> while Mullis was still working on a paper that would describe PCR itself.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Mullis' 1985 paper with R. K. Saiki and H. A. Erlich, \"Enzymatic Amplification of \u03b2-globin Genomic Sequences and Restriction Site Analysis for Diagnosis of Sickle Cell Anemia\"\u2014the polymerase chain reaction invention (PCR) -- was honored by a Citation for Chemical Breakthrough Award from the Division of History of Chemistry of the American Chemical Society in 2017.<ref name=\"breakthrough\">{{Cite web|title=Citations for Chemical Breakthrough Awards 2017 Awardees|url=http://www.scs.illinois.edu/~mainzv/HIST/awards/CCB-2017_Awardees.php|website=Division of the History of Chemistry|access-date=12 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Saiki|first1=R.|last2=Scharf|first2=S|last3=Faloona|first3=F|last4=Mullis|first4=K.|last5=Horn|first5=G.|last6=Erlich|first6=H.|last7=Arnheim|first7=N|title=Enzymatic amplification of beta-globin genomic sequences and restriction site analysis for diagnosis of sickle cell anemia|journal=Science|date=20 December 1985|volume=230|issue=4732|pages=1350\u20131354|doi=10.1126/science.2999980|pmid=2999980|bibcode=1985Sci...230.1350S}}</ref>\n\nA drawback of the technique was that the DNA polymerase in the reaction was destroyed by the high heat used at the start of each replication cycle and had to be replaced. In 1986, Saiki started to use ''[[Thermophilus aquaticus]]'' (Taq) [[DNA polymerase]] to amplify segments of DNA. The Taq polymerase was heat resistant and only need to be added to the reaction once, making the technique dramatically more affordable and subject to automation. This modification of Mullis' invention revolutionized [[biochemistry]], [[molecular biology]], [[genetics]], medicine, and [[forensics]].\n\nMullis also invented a UV-sensitive plastic that changes color in response to light.\n\nHe founded Altermune LLC in 2011 to pursue new ideas on the immune system.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/09/22/idUS134319+22-Sep-2011+BW20110922 Loxbridge and Dr Kary Mullis Announce the Formation of Altermune Technologies with $7m Seed Investment.] [https://web.archive.org/web/20140914135558/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/09/22/idUS134319+22-Sep-2011+BW20110922 Archived]</ref> Mullis described the company's novel technology in a presentation:\n{{Quote | style=font-size:100% |It is a method using specific synthetic chemical linkers to divert an immune response from its nominal target to something completely different which you would right now like to be temporarily immune to. Let's say you just got exposed to a new strain of the flu. You're already immune to alpha-1,3-galactosyl-galactose bonds. All humans are. Why not divert a fraction of those antibodies to the influenza strain you just picked up? A chemical linker synthesized with an alpha-1,3-gal-gal bond on one end and a DNA aptamer devised to bind specifically to the strain of influenza you have on the other end will link anti-alpha-Gal antibodies to the influenza virus and presto!--you have fooled your immune system into attacking the new virus.<ref name=\"nobelbio\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ted.com/talks/lang/eng/kary_mullis_next_gen_cure_for_killer_infections.html |title=Kary Mullis' next-gen cure for killer infections &#124; Video on |publisher=Ted.com |date=February 2009 |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref>}}\n\nThe first proof-of-principle of this technology, re-targeting pre-existing antibodies to the surface of a pathogenic strep bacteria using an alpha-gal modified aptamer (\"alphamer\"), was published in 2015 in collaboration with scientists at the University of California, San Diego.<ref>{{Cite press release | first=Heather | last=Buschman | title=Molecular Homing Beacon Redirects Human Antibodies to Fight Pathogenic Bacteria | url=http://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/pressrelease/molecular_homing_beacon_redirects_human_antibodies_to_fight_pathogenic_bact | publisher=[[University of California, San Diego]] | date=May 6, 2015 | access-date=July 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid=25940316 | title=Retargeting pre-existing human antibodies to a bacterial pathogen with an alpha-Gal conjugated aptamer | doi=10.1007/s00109-015-1280-4 | pmc=4469262 | volume=93 | issue=6 | year=2015 | journal=J. Mol. Med. | pages=619\u201331 | last1=Kristian | first1=SA | last2=Hwang | first2=JH | last3=Hall | first3=B | last4=Leire | first4=E | last5=Iacomini | first5=J | last6=Old | first6=R | last7=Galili | first7=U | last8=Roberts | first8=C | last9=Mullis | first9=KB | last10=Westby | first10=M | last11=Nizet | first11=V}}</ref>\n\n=== Accreditation of the PCR technique ===\nA concept similar to that of PCR had been described before Mullis' work. Nobel laureate [[H. Gobind Khorana]] and Kjell Kleppe, a Norwegian scientist, authored a paper 17 years earlier describing a process they termed \"repair replication\" in the ''[[Journal of Molecular Biology]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last1=Kleppe|first1=K.|last2=Ohtsuka|first2=E.|last3=Kleppe|first3=R.|last4=Molineux|first4=I.|last5=Khorana|first5=H. G.|authorlink5=Har Gobind Khorana|year=1971|title=Studies on polynucleotides *1, *2XCVI. Repair replication of short synthetic DNA's as catalyzed by DNA polymerases|journal=Journal of Molecular Biology|volume=56|issue=2|pages=341\u2013361|doi=10.1016/0022-2836(71)90469-4|pmc=|pmid=4927950}}</ref> Using repair replication, Kleppe duplicated and then quadrupled a small synthetic molecule with the help of two primers and DNA polymerase. The method developed by Mullis used repeated thermal cycling, which allowed the rapid and exponential amplification of large quantities of any desired DNA sequence from an extremely complex template. Later a heat-stable DNA polymerase was incorporated into the process.\n\nHis co-workers at Cetus, who were embittered by his abrupt departure from the company,<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" />\ncontested that Mullis was solely responsible for the idea of using [[Taq polymerase]] in PCR. However, other scientists have written that the \"full potential [of PCR] was not realized\" until Mullis' work in 1983,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dexRnDtLlWUC&pg=PA20&dq=%22kary+mullis%22+%2B+%22kjell+kleppe%22 |title=''Artificial DNA: Methods and Applications'' by Yury E. Khudyakov, Howard A. Fields |access-date=July 27, 2010|isbn=978-0-8493-1426-1|year=2003|last1=Khudyakov |first1=Yury E. |last2=Fields |first2=Howard A.}}</ref> and that Mullis' colleagues failed to see the potential of the technique when he presented it to them.<ref name=\"lifeonedge\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=J5IwomfEGiEC&pg=PA103&dq=%22kary+mullis%22 |title=''Life on the Edge: Amazing Creatures Thriving in Extreme Environments'' by Michael Gross |date= January 24, 2001|access-date=July 27, 2010|isbn=978-0-7382-0445-1|last1=Gross |first1=Michael}}</ref> As a result, some controversy surrounds the balance of credit that should be given to Mullis versus the team at Cetus.<ref name=\"NYTimes1998\" /> In practice, credit has accrued to both the inventor and the company (although not its individual workers) in the form of a Nobel Prize and a $10,000 Cetus bonus for Mullis and $300 million for Cetus when the company sold the patent to [[Hoffmann-La Roche|Roche Molecular Systems]]. After [[DuPont (1802\u20132017)|DuPont]] lost out to Roche on that sale, the company unsuccessfully disputed Mullis' patent on the alleged grounds that PCR had been previously described in 1971.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Mullis and Erlich took Cetus' side in the case, and Khorana refused to testify for DuPont; the jury upheld Mullis' patent in 1991.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> However, in February 1999, the patent of Hoffman-La Roche (United States Patent No. 4,889,818) was found by the courts to be unenforceable, after Dr. Thomas Kunkel testified in the case ''Hoffman-La Roche v. Promega Corporation''<ref name=Roche_v_Promega>{{Cite web|url=https://www.casemine.com/judgement/us/5914b97badd7b0493478b532|title=Hoffmann-La Roche, Inc. v. Promega Corporation, (N.D.Cal. 2001)|publisher=Casemine|author=United States District Court, N.D. California.|date=July 26, 2001|access-date=April 8, 2018}}</ref> on behalf of the defendants ([[Promega Corporation]]) that \"prior art\" (i.e. articles on the subject of Taq polymerase published by other groups prior to the work of Gelfand and Stoffel, and their patent application regarding the purification of Taq polymerase) existed, in the form of two articles, published by Alice Chien et al. in 1976,<ref name=\"Chien\">{{Cite journal | last1=Chien | first1=A. | last2=Edgar | first2=D.B. | last3=Trela | first3=J.M. | title=Deoxyribonucleic acid polymerase from the extreme thermophile Thermus aquaticus | journal=J. Bacteriol. | volume=127 | issue=3 | pages=1550\u20131557 | year=1976 | pmid=8432 | pmc=232952 | doi=10.1128/jb.127.3.1550-1557.1976}}</ref> and A. S. Kaledin et al. in 1980.<ref name=\"Kaledin\">{{Cite journal | last1=Kaledin | first1=A.S. | last2=Sliusarenko | first2=A.G. | last3=Gorodetskii | first3=S.I. | title=Isolation and properties of DNA polymerase from extreme thermophylic bacteria Thermus aquaticus YT-1 | journal=[[Biokhimiia]] | volume=45 | issue=4 | pages=644\u2013651 | year=1980 | pmid=7378495}}</ref>\n\nThe [[anthropology|anthropologist]] [[Paul Rabinow]] wrote a book on the history of the PCR method in 1996 (entitled ''Making PCR'') in which he discussed whether Mullis \"invented\" PCR or \"merely\" came up with the concept of it. Rabinow, a [[Michel Foucault|Foucault]] scholar interested in issues of the production of knowledge, used the topic to argue against the idea that scientific discovery is the product of individual work, writing, \"Committees and science journalists like the idea of associating a unique idea with a unique person, the lone genius. PCR is thought by some to be an example of teamwork, but by others as the genius of one who was smart enough to put things together which were present to all, but overlooked. For Mullis, the light bulb went off, but for others it did not. This is consistent with the idea, that the prepared (educated) mind who is careful to observe and not overlook, is what separates the genius scientist from his many also smart scientists. The proof is in the fact that the person who has the light bulb go off never forgets the \"Ah!\" experience, while the others never had this photochemical reaction go off in their brains.\"<ref>{{Cite web|author=Richard Bilsker |url=http://www.hyle.org/journal/issues/4/bilsker.htm |title=Ethnography of a Nobel Prize |publisher=Hyle.org |date= |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Personal views ==\nMullis was quoted saying \"the never-ending quest for more grants and staying with established dogmas\" has hurt science.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> He believed that \"science is being practiced by people who are dependent on being paid for what they are ''going'' to find out,\" not for what they actually produce.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Mullis was described by some as an \"impatient and impulsive researcher\" who finds routine laboratory work boring and instead thinks about his research while driving and surfing. He came up with the idea of the polymerase chain reaction while driving along a highway.<ref>{{Cite book | last =Fridell | first=R |title=Decoding life: unraveling the mysteries of the genome |publisher= Lerner Publications | location =Minneapolis |year=2005 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Cpa6lEhiD0C&pg=PA88#v=onepage&q&f=false | page=88 |isbn=978-0-8225-1196-0}}</ref>\n\nIn his 1998 humorous autobiography, Mullis expressed disagreement with the scientific evidence supporting [[climate change]] and [[ozone depletion]], the evidence that [[AIDS denialism|HIV causes AIDS]], and asserted his belief in [[astrology]].<ref name=\"Naked\" />\n<ref name=\"naked-capricorn\">{{cite book |title=Dancing Naked in the Mind Field |first=Kary |last=Mullis |author-link=Kary Mullis |year=1998 |chapter=Chapter 15: I am a Capricorn |page=143\u201353 |chapter-url=http://www.crawfordperspectives.com/documents/IAMACAPRICORN_000.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051221093301/http://www.crawfordperspectives.com/documents/IAMACAPRICORN_000.pdf |archive-date=December 21, 2005 |url-status=live |isbn=<!--uncertain-->}}</ref> \nMullis claimed climate change and the HIV/AIDS connection are due to a [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy]] of environmentalists, government agencies, and scientists attempting to preserve their careers and earn money, rather than scientific evidence.<ref name=Naked>{{Cite book | title=Dancing Naked in the Mind Field | last=Mullis | first=K | year=1998 | publisher=Vintage Books | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MCAqomvRYNMC&pg=PA115#v=onepage&q&f=false | pages=115\u201318, 143\u201353 | isbn=978-0-679-44255-4}}</ref> \nMullis has been criticized for his association with HIV skeptic [[Peter Duesberg]],<ref name=\"Find\">{{Cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/HEALTH/AIDS/9909/15/aids.heresies3/ | title=AIDS heresies: From maverick science to conspiracy theories | publisher=CNN | date=September 15, 1999 | access-date=February 26, 2014 | author=Horvath, Hacsi}}</ref> claiming that AIDS is an arbitrary diagnosis used when HIV antibodies are found in a patient's blood.<ref name=Informer>{{Cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79665692.html |title=Washington Informer |publisher=High beam |date=May 31, 2000 |access-date=July 27, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104075451/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79665692.html |archive-date=November 4, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The medical and scientific consensus is that Duesberg's hypothesis is [[pseudoscience]], HIV having been conclusively proven to be the cause of AIDS<ref name= iomreport >{{Cite book | url=http://books.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=771&page=2 | title=Confronting AIDS: Update 1988 | publisher=[[Institute of Medicine]] of the [[U.S. National Academy of Sciences]] | year=1988 | quote=... the evidence that HIV causes AIDS is scientifically conclusive.| doi=10.17226/771 | pmid=25032454 | isbn=978-0-309-03879-9 | author1=Institute of Medicine (US) Committee for the Oversight of AIDS Activities }}</ref><ref name=niaid>{{Cite web | url=http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/topics/HIVAIDS/Understanding/howHIVCausesAIDS/HIVcausesAIDS.htm | title=The Evidence that HIV Causes AIDS | access-date=October 14, 2009 | publisher=[[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Disease]] | date=September 4, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124091249/http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/topics/HIVAIDS/Understanding/howHIVCausesAIDS/HIVcausesAIDS.htm |archivedate=November 24, 2009}}</ref> and that global warming is occurring because of human activities.<ref name=Beyond>{{Cite journal| last=Oreskes| first=Naomi| author-link=Naomi Oreskes | title=Beyond the Ivory Tower: The Scientific Consensus on Climate Change | journal=Science | volume=306 | page=1686 | date=December 2004| url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/full/306/5702/1686 | quote=Such statements suggest that there might be substantive disagreement in the scientific community about the reality of anthropogenic climate change. This is not the case. ... Politicians, economists, journalists, and others may have the impression of confusion, disagreement, or discord among climate scientists, but that impression is incorrect.| doi=10.1126/science.1103618| pmid=15576594| issue=5702| doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=National>{{Cite web | url=http://nationalacademies.org/onpi/06072005.pdf | title=Joint Science Academies' Statement | date=July 6, 2005 | access-date=June 9, 2011 | publisher=United States National Academies}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dels-old.nas.edu/dels/rpt_briefs/climate_change_2008_final.pdf |title=Understanding and Responding to Climate Change |year=2008 |access-date=June 9, 2011 |publisher=United States National Academies |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423073539/http://dels-old.nas.edu/dels/rpt_briefs/climate_change_2008_final.pdf |archivedate=April 23, 2013}}</ref> Seth Kalichman, AIDS researcher and author of ''Denying AIDS'', \"[admits] that it seems odd to include a Nobel laureate among the who's who of AIDS pseudoscientists\".<ref name=Kalichman>{{Cite book |authorlink=Seth Kalichman|author=Kalichman, Seth |title=Denying AIDS: Conspiracy Theories, Pseudoscience, and Human Tragedy |publisher=Copernicus Books ([[Springer Science+Business Media]]) |location=New York |year=2009 |pages= [https://books.google.com/books?id=_mtDBCDwxugC&pg=PA177#v=onepage&q&f=false 177\u2013178] |isbn=978-0-387-79475-4 | url =}}</ref> Mullis also wrote the foreword to the book ''What If Everything You Thought You Knew About AIDS Was Wrong?'' by [[Christine Maggiore]],<ref name=Wrong>{{Cite book |author=Maggiore C|title=What If Everything You Thought You Knew About AIDS Was Wrong? |publisher=American Foundation For AIDS Alternative |location= |year=2006 |pages= |isbn=978-0-9674153-2-1 |oclc= |doi= |access-date=}}</ref> an HIV-positive AIDS denialist who, along with her 3-years-old daughter, died of an AIDS-related illness.<ref name=LATdeath>{{Cite news |title= Christine Maggiore, vocal skeptic of AIDS research, dies at 52|newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]]|date= December 30, 2008|access-date=December 30, 2008|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-christine-maggiore30-2008dec30,0,7407966.story |first1=Anna |last1=Gorman |first2=Alexandra |last2=Zavis}}</ref> A ''[[New York Times]]'' article listed Mullis as one of several scientists who, after success in their area of research, go on to make unfounded, sometimes bizarre statements in other areas.<ref name=NYT>{{Cite news | last=Johnson | first=G | title=Bright Scientists, Dim Notions | work=[[The New York Times]] | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/28/weekinreview/28johnson.html?_r=3&adxnnl=1&oref=slogin&ref=science&adxnnlx=1193583001-IE12EKQeJt1sjwCUOYPVWg&oref=slogin | date=October 28, 2007 | access-date=August 6, 2010}}</ref> An article in the ''[[Skeptical Inquirer]]'' described Mullis as an \"AIDS denialist with scientific credentials [who] has never done any scientific research on HIV or AIDS.\"<ref name=SI>{{Cite journal | url=http://www.csicop.org/si/show/aids_denialism_vs._science/ | title=AIDS Denialism vs. Science | volume=31 | issue=5 | last=Nattrass | first=N | year=2007 | journal=[[Skeptical Inquirer]]}}</ref> However, he consulted for Specialty Labs, in Santa Monica, developing a nucleic acid based HIV test. While writing a NIH grant progress report, he was unable to find a peer-reviewed reference that HIV was the cause of AIDS.<ref name=\"Naked\" /><ref name=\"Wrong\" /> Mullis published an alternative theory of AIDS in 1994.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mullis|first=Kary B.|date=1995|title=A hypothetical disease of the immune system that may bear some relation to the Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome|journal=Genetica|volume=95|issue=1\u20133|pages=195\u2013197|doi=10.1007/bf01435010|pmid=7744261|issn=0016-6707}}</ref> He questioned the scientific validity of the link between HIV and AIDS, leading some to label him an \"AIDS denialist.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Seth|last=Kalichman| url=https://newhumanist.org.uk/articles/2165/how-to-spot-an-aids-denialist | title=How to spot an AIDS denialist | date=November 3, 2009 | access-date=August 14, 2019 | journal=New Humanist}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Basu|first=Paroma|date=June 1, 2005|title=AIDS denialists back on the upswing|journal=Nature|volume=11|issue=6|page=581|doi=10.1038/nm0605-581b|pmid=15937451|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/01d1fc960fff86c208c277f9f13fefde49140065}}</ref>\n\n== Use of hallucinogens ==\nMullis detailed his experiences synthesizing and testing various psychedelic amphetamines and a difficult trip on [[Diethyltryptamine|DET]] in his autobiography. In a Q&A interview published in the September 1994 issue of ''[[California Monthly]]'', Mullis said, \"Back in the 1960s and early 1970s I took plenty of [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]]. A lot of people were doing that in Berkeley back then. And I found it to be a mind-opening experience. It was certainly much more important than any courses I ever took.\"<ref>{{Cite journal | last=Schoch | first=Russell | title=Q&A \u2013 A Conversation with Kerry Mullis | journal=California Monthly | volume=105 | issue=1 | page=20 | publisher=[[California Alumni Association]] | location=Berkeley, California |date=September 1994| url=http://www.alumni.berkeley.edu/Alumni/Cal_Monthly/September_1994/QA_-_A_Conversation_with_Kerry_Mullis.asp | access-date=March 11, 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901144701/http://www.alumni.berkeley.edu/Alumni/Cal_Monthly/September_1994/QA_-_A_Conversation_with_Kerry_Mullis.asp | archivedate=September 1, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{vn|date=December 2019}} During a symposium held for centenarian [[Albert Hofmann]], Hofmann said Mullis had told him that LSD had \"helped him develop the polymerase chain reaction that helps amplify specific DNA sequences\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/science/discoveries/news/2006/01/70015 |title=LSD: The Geek's Wonder Drug? |access-date=March 11, 2008 |author=Harrison, Ann |date=January 16, 2006 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |publisher=Wired |quote=Like Herbert, many scientists and engineers also report heightened states of creativity while using LSD. During a press conference on Friday, Hofmann revealed that he was told by Nobel-prize-winning chemist Kary Mullis that LSD had helped him develop the polymerase chain reaction that helps amplify specific DNA sequences.}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nKnown for his quick wit and colorful stories, Mullis enjoyed [[surfing]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Golden |first=Frederic |url=http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,91819,00.html |title=''Time Magazine'', December 13, 2000 |magazine=Time.com |date=December 13, 2000 |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> He married four times,<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> and had a total of three children by two of his wives. At the time of his death, he had two grandchildren. He used profanities to make a point and often said, \"Oh, Lord,\" in response to the absurdities experienced in life.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Mullis reported an encounter with a \"standard extraterrestrial raccoon\" at his cabin in the woods of northern California around midnight one night in 1985; he denied being on [[psychedelic drug]]s at the time.<ref>{{Citation|last=Bullard|first=Thomas|title=The Myth and Mystery of UFOs|url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/v33/n22/jenny-diski/what-might-they-want|number=22|type=Review|journal=LRB|volume=33|place=UK|date=November 17, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Naked\" />\n\nMullis died of [[pneumonia]]<ref name=\"death1\">{{Cite news|url=https://mynewsla.com/education/2019/08/08/nobel-winner-kary-banks-mullis-who-revolutionized-dna-research-dies-in-o-c/|title=Nobel Winner Kary Banks Mullis, Who Revolutionized DNA Research, Dies in O.C.|publisher=MyNewsLA.com|date=August 8, 2019|access-date=August 11, 2019}}</ref> on August 7, 2019 at age 74 in [[Newport Beach, California]].<ref name=\"death2\">{{Cite news|first=Debbie|last=Dclark|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/news/nobel-prize-winning-chemist-who-grew-up-in-sc-capital/article_f69354e6-baa3-11e9-b4d2-e7b21bfe5bfd.html|title=Nobel Prize-winning chemist who grew up in SC capital dies at 74|publisher=postandcourier.com | work=[[The Post and Courier]] |date=August 9, 2019|access-date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Publications and books ==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Mullis | first1 = Kary | year = 1968 | title = Cosmological Significance of Time Reversal | journal = Nature | volume = 218 | issue = 5142| pages = 663\u2013664 | doi = 10.1038/218663b0 | bibcode = 1968Natur.218..663M | url = https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/9bedef8385043ca9603539ce73ae5f144dcd84eb }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Mullis | first1 = K.F. | last2 = Faloona | first2 = F. | last3 = Scharf | first3 = S. | last4 = Saiki | first4 = R. | last5 = Horn | first5 = G. | last6 = Erlich | first6 = H. | year = 1986 | title = Specific enzymatic amplification of DNA in vitro: The polymerase chain reaction | url = | journal = Cold Spring Harbor Symposia on Quantitative Biology| volume = 51 | issue = | pages = 263\u2013273 | doi = 10.1101/sqb.1986.051.01.032 | pmid = 3472723 }}\n* K. Mullis, 1990, ''The unusual origin of the polymerase chain reaction''. ''Scientific American'', April 56\u201365.\n* ''The Polymerase Chain Reaction'', 1994, co-edited Francious Ferre and Richard A. Gibbs (Basel: Birkhauser) {{ISBN|0817637508}} {{ISBN|978-0817637507}}.\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1007/BF01435010|pmid=7744261|title=A hypothetical disease of the immune system that may bear some relation to the Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome|journal=Genetica|volume=95|issue=1\u20133|pages=195\u2013197|year=1995|last1=Mullis|first1=Kary B.|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/bd1f14f63e48f1aa3be46a6cb138b9eb56379858}}\n* Mullis' 1998 humorous autobiography ''Dancing Naked in the Mind Field'' ({{ISBN|978-0679774006}}), gives his account of the commercial development of [[polymerase chain reaction|PCR]], as well as providing insights into his opinions and experiences. In the book, Mullis chronicles his romantic relationships, use of LSD, synthesis and self-testing of novel psychoactive substances, belief in [[astrology]] and an encounter with an [[Extraterrestrial life|extraterrestrial]] in the form of a fluorescent raccoon.\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n* 1990&nbsp;\u2014 [[William Allan Award|William Allan Memorial Award]] of the American Society of Human Genetics,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ashg.org/awards/pastrecipients.shtml#allan|title=Past Recipients, William Allan Award|publisher=American Society of Human Genetics|access-date=August 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804212043/http://www.ashg.org/awards/pastrecipients.shtml#allan|archive-date=August 4, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> Preis Biochemische Analytik of the German Society of Clinical Chemistry and [[Boehringer Mannheim]]<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.dgkl.de/en/die-dgkl/awards/preis-fuer-biochemische-analytik/preistraeger/|title=Award Winners 1970&nbsp;\u2014 2017|publisher=German Society for Clinical Chemistry and Laboratory Medicine|access-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n* 1991&nbsp;\u2014 National Biotechnology Award,<ref name=\"newton\">{{Cite book| url= https://books.google.com/?id=1jM4B1JffrgC&pg=PA163 | title=Forensic Chemistry | first=David E. | last=Newton|date= 2007|access-date=August 14, 2019|isbn=978-1438109763|publisher=Facts On File, Inc.|location=New York}}</ref> [[Canada Gairdner International Award|Gairdner Award]],<ref name=\"newton\" /> R&D Scientist of the Year,<ref name=\"newton\" /> [[John Scott Award]] of the City Trusts of [[Philadelphia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.garfield.library.upenn.edu/johnscottaward(full).html |title=John Scott Award Winners |publisher=U Penn |date=October 28, 2005 |access-date=July 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701201455/http://www.garfield.library.upenn.edu/johnscottaward%28full%29.html |archivedate=July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n* 1992&nbsp;\u2014 California Scientist of the Year Award<ref name=\"newton\" />\n* 1992&nbsp;\u2014 [[Robert Koch Prize]]<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.robert-koch-stiftung.de/index.php?article_id=15&clang=1|title=Robert Koch Award|publisher=Robert-Koch-Stiftung|access-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n* 1993&nbsp;\u2014 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, [[Japan Prize]],<ref name=jp /> Thomas A. Edison Award<ref name=\"newton\" />\n* 1994&nbsp;\u2014 Honorary degree of Doctor of Science from the [[University of South Carolina]]<ref name=\"website\" />\n* 1998&nbsp;\u2014 Inducted into the [[National Inventors Hall of Fame]],<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.invent.org/Hall_Of_Fame/109.html |title=Hall of Fame |contribution=Inventor Profile |publisher=Invent.org |date=December 28, 1944 |access-date=July 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706045503/http://www.invent.org/hall_of_fame/109.html |archivedate=July 6, 2010 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Ronald H. Brown American Innovator Award<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.uspto.gov/web/offices/com/speeches/98-18.htm | title= Nobel Prize Winner Among Rondal H. Brown Award Recipients | publisher= PTO | place=USA | date=October 13, 1998 |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref>\n* 2004&nbsp;\u2014 Honorary degree in Pharmaceutical Biotechnology from the [[University of Bologna]], Italy<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.almanews.unibo.it/03_04/Html/mullis.htm|title=Laurea ad honorem a Kary Mullis|publisher=University of Bologna|access-date=August 14, 2019|language=Italian}}</ref>\n* 2010&nbsp;\u2014 Honorary degree of Doctor honoris causa in the field of biological sciences from [[Masaryk University]], Czech Republic<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.muni.cz/en/about-us/awards/342|title=Kary Banks Mullis|publisher=Masaryk University|access-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{POV section|date=September 2019}}\n* [[House of Numbers (2009 film)|House of Numbers]]\n* [[Luc Montagnier]]&nbsp;\u2014 Nobel prize winning HIV researcher who now endorses [[homeopathy]]\n* [[Nobel Prize controversies]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*[[Paul Rabinow]], ''Making PCR: a story of biotechnology'' (University of Chicago Press, 1996). {{ISBN|0-226-70147-6}}\n* Anthony Liversidge, {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010121194200/http://omnimag.com/archives/interviews/mullis.html |date=January 21, 2001 |title=\"Kary Mullis, the great gene machine\"}}, ''[[Omni (magazine)|Omni]]'' magazine (April 1992).\n* Kary Mullis, ''Dancing Naked in the Mind Field''. Vintage Books (1998). {{ISBN|0-679-44255-3}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Kary Mullis}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Citation | url=http://www.karymullis.com/ | title=Kary Mullis | type=personal webpage}}.\n*{{Citation | url=http://www.directoryinventor.com/inventor/03d4659f7b0373002cb929636bca9e48_1.html/ | title=Patent portfolio | publisher=Directory inventor | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130110223017/http://www.directoryinventor.com/inventor/03d4659f7b0373002cb929636bca9e48_1.html/ | archivedate=January 10, 2013 | df=mdy-all}}.\n*{{Find a Grave|201986282}}\n\n=== Interviews ===\n*{{Citation | url=http://nobelprize.org/mediaplayer/index.php?id=428 | year=2005 | title=Interview | publisher=Nobel Prize committee}}.\n*{{Citation | url=http://old.valleyadvocate.com/hiv-aids/i980714.html | year=1998 | title=Interview | first=Sarah | last=Klipfel | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050706052721/http://old.valleyadvocate.com/hiv-aids/i980714.html | archivedate=July 6, 2005 | df=mdy-all}} regarding his views on HIV/AIDS.\n\n{{Nobel Prize in Chemistry}}\n{{1993 Nobel Prize winners}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mullis, Kary}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:American biochemists]]\n[[Category:American Nobel laureates]]\n[[Category:Nobel laureates in Chemistry]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS denialists]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Columbia, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Lenoir, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Biotechnologists]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic drug advocates]]\n[[Category:Scientists from North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American biochemist}}{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name=Kary Mullis\n| image = Kary Mullis.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Mullis in 2006\n| birth_name = Kary Banks Mullis\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1944|12|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Lenoir, North Carolina]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2019|08|07|1944|12|28}}\n| death_place = [[Newport Beach, California]], U.S.<ref name=\"death1\" /><ref name=\"death2\" />\n| nationality = American\n| field = [[Molecular biology]]\n| work_institution = \n| thesis_title = Schizokinen: structure and synthetic work\n| thesis_url = http://www.worldcat.org/title/schizokinen-structure-and-synthetic-work/oclc/17971376&referer=brief_results\n| thesis_year = 1973\n| alma_mater = [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] <small>(BS, 1966)</small><br />[[University of California, Berkeley]] <small>(PhD, 1973)</small>\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Joe Neilands|J. B. Neilands]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for = Invention of [[polymerase chain reaction]]\n| prizes = {{Nowrap|[[William Allan Award]] {{Small|(1990)}}<br />[[Robert Koch Prize]] <small>(1992)</small><br />[[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] <small>(1993)</small><br />[[Japan Prize]] <small>(1993)</small><ref name=jp>[http://www.japanprize.jp/en/laureates_by_year1990.html Laureates of the Japan Prize]. japanprize.jp</ref>\n}}\n| religion = \n| footnotes = <!-- | parents=Cecil Banks Mullis and Bernice Alberta Barker Mullis<ref name=nobelbio /> unsuppored parameter -->\n}}\n\n'''Kary Banks Mullis''' (December 28, 1944&nbsp;\u2013 August 7, 2019) was an American [[biochemistry|biochemist]]. In recognition of his invention of the [[polymerase chain reaction]] (PCR) technique, he shared the 1993 [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] with [[Michael Smith (chemist)|Michael Smith]]<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last1=Shampo | first1=M. A.\n| last2=Kyle | first2=R. A.\n| title=Kary B. Mullis&nbsp;\u2014 Nobel Laureate for procedure to replicate DNA\n| journal=Proceedings | publisher=Mayo Clinic\n| volume=77\n| issue=7\n| page=606\n| year=2002\n| pmid=12108595\n| doi=10.4065/77.7.606\n| doi-access=free\n}}</ref> and was awarded the [[Japan Prize]] in the same year. His invention became a central technique in [[biochemistry]] and [[molecular biology]], described by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as \"highly original and significant, virtually dividing biology into the two epochs of before PCR and after PCR.\"<ref name=\"NYTimes1998\" />\n\n== Early life ==\nMullis was born in [[Lenoir, North Carolina]], near the [[Blue Ridge Mountains]],<ref name=\"nobelbio\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/chemistry/1993/mullis/biographical/ |title= Autobiography |publisher=Nobel prize |date=March 21, 1998 |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> on December 28, 1944. His family had a background in farming in this rural area. As a child, Mullis said, he was interested in observing organisms in the countryside.<ref name=\"biotechnology101\">{{Cite book| url= https://archive.org/details/biotechnology1010000shma | url-access= registration | page= [https://archive.org/details/biotechnology1010000shma/page/184 184] | quote= kary mullis. | title=Biotechnology 101 | publisher= Greenwood Press | first=Brian Robert | last=Shmaefsky |date= October 30, 2006|access-date=July 27, 2010|isbn=978-0-313-33528-0}}</ref> He grew up in [[Columbia, South Carolina]],<ref name=\"biotechnology101\" /> where he attended [[Dreher High School]]<ref name=nobellecture>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/1993/mullis-lecture.html|title=Nobel Lecture \u2013 The Polymerase Chain Reaction|publisher=nobelprize.org|author=Kary Mullis|date=December 8, 1993}}</ref>, graduating in the class of 1962. His interest in chemistry started when he learned how to chemically synthesize and build solid fuel propulsion rockets as a high school student during the 1950s.<ref>[https://www.ted.com/talks/kary_mullis_on_what_scientists_do?language=en Kary Mullis: Play! Experiment! Discover! | TED Talk]. TED.com. Retrieved on May 9, 2016.</ref>\n\nHe earned a [[B.S.]] in [[chemistry]]<ref name=\"nobelbio\" /> from the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] in [[Atlanta]] in 1966, during which time he married his first wife and started a business.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\">{{Citation| last=Yoffe| first=Emily | authorlink=Emily Yoffe| publisher=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]| title=Is Kary Mullis God? Nobel Prize winner's new life| volume=122 | number=1 |date=July 1994 | pages=68\u201375}}</ref> He earned his [[Ph.D.]] in 1973 in [[biochemistry]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], in [[Joe Neilands|J. B. Neilands]]' laboratory, which focused on synthesis and structure of bacterial iron transporter molecules.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Kary Banks |last=Mullis |title=Schizokinen: Structure and Synthetic Work |url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/302680803/5655A51FB3D04612PQ/ |work=[[ProQuest]] |date=1973 |access-date=July 6, 2017}}</ref> As a graduate student, he published a sole-author paper in ''Nature'' in the field of [[astrophysics]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MULLIS|first=KARY|date=1968|title=Cosmological Significance of Time Reversal|journal=Nature|volume=218|issue=5142|pages=663\u2013664|doi=10.1038/218663b0|issn=0028-0836|bibcode=1968Natur.218..663M|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/9bedef8385043ca9603539ce73ae5f144dcd84eb}}</ref> Following his graduation, Mullis completed postdoctoral fellowships in pediatric [[cardiology]] at the [[University of Kansas Medical Center]] (1973-1977) and [[pharmaceutical chemistry]] at the [[University of California, San Francisco]] (1977-1979).<ref name=\":2\">http://www.karymullis.com/pdf/karymullis-cv.pdf</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter receiving his doctorate, Mullis briefly left science to write fiction before accepting the University of Kansas fellowship.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> During his postdoctoral work, he managed a bakery for two years.<ref name=\"NYTimes1998\">{{Citation | url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802E7DD1331F936A2575AC0A96E958260 | title=Scientist at Work/Kary Mullis; After the 'Eureka', a Nobelist Drops Out | first=Nicholas | last=Wade | journal=[[The New York Times]] | date=September 15, 1998}}</ref> Mullis returned to science at the encouragement of friend [[Thomas White]], who later helped Mullis land a position with the biotechnology company [[Cetus Corporation]] of [[Emeryville, California]].<ref name=\"biotechnology101\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes1998\" /> Mullis worked as a [[DNA]] [[chemist]] at Cetus for seven years; it was there, in 1983, that Mullis invented the polymerase chain reaction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/science/tq/displayStory.cfm?Story_id=2477036 |title= The Economist |date= March 13, 2004|access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> After leaving Cetus in 1986, Mullis served as director of molecular biology for Xytronyx, Inc. in [[San Diego]] for two years. While inventing a UV-sensitive ink at Xytronyx, he became skeptical of the existence of the ozone hole.\n\nMullis served as a consultant for multiple corporations on nucleic acid chemistry.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes1998\" /> While writing a National Institutes of Health grant progress report on the development of a human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) test for Specialty Labs, he became skeptical that HIV was the cause of acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS).<ref name=\"Naked\" /> In 1992, Mullis founded a business to sell pieces of jewelry containing the amplified DNA of deceased famous people such as [[Elvis Presley]] and [[Marilyn Monroe]].<ref name=\"lifeonedge\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.questia.com/googleScholar.qst;jsessionid=HL2GySNR8dj13v4D64WDGhlzhN8Fkspv6nJF6JwngX1NzhyfwZlK!930663388?docId=5002303854 |title= The Hastings Center Report |pages= 30 | year=1998 |publisher=Questia |access-date=July 27, 2010|last1= Andrews |first1= Lori |last2= Nelkin |first2= Dorothy }}</ref> Also in 1992 he founded [[Atomic Tags]], in La Jolla, California. Atomic Tags sought to develop technology using atomic-force microscopy and bar-coded antibodies tagged with heavy metals to create highly multiplexed, parallel immunoassays.\n\nMullis was a member of the [[USA Science and Engineering Festival]]'s Advisory Board.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.usasciencefestival.org/about/advisors |title=Advisors |publisher=USA science festival |date= |access-date=July 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100421005310/http://www.usasciencefestival.org/about/advisors/ |archivedate=April 21, 2010 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2014, he was named a distinguished researcher at the [[Children's Hospital Oakland Research Institute]] in [[Oakland, California]].<ref name=\"website\">[http://www.karymullis.com/biography.shtml Dr. Kary Banks Mullis]. Karymullis.com. Retrieved on May 9, 2016.</ref>\n\n=== PCR and other inventions ===\n{{Main|Taq Polymerase|History of polymerase chain reaction}}\nIn 1983, Mullis was working for [[Cetus Corporation]] as a chemist.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Late one night while driving with his girlfriend, who was also a chemist at Cetus, he had the idea to use a pair of primers to bracket the desired DNA sequence and to copy it using DNA polymerase; a technique that would allow rapid amplification of a small stretch of DNA and become a standard procedure in molecular biology laboratories.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Cetus took Mullis off his usual projects to concentrate on PCR full-time.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Mullis succeeded in demonstrating PCR December 16, 1983.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> In his Nobel Prize lecture, he remarked that the success did not make up for his girlfriend breaking up with him. \"I was sagging as I walked out to my little silver [[Honda Civic]]. Neither [assistant] Fred, empty Beck's bottles, nor the sweet smell of the dawn of the age of PCR could replace Jenny. I was lonesome.\"<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> He received a $10,000 bonus from Cetus for the invention.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" />\n\nOther Cetus scientists, including [[Randall Saiki]] and [[Henry Erlich]], were placed on PCR projects to work on determining if PCR could amplify a specific human gene ([[betaglobin]]) from genomic DNA. Saiki generated the needed data and Erlich authored the first paper to include utilization of the technique,<ref name=\"NYTimes1998\" /> while Mullis was still working on a paper that would describe PCR itself.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Mullis' 1985 paper with R. K. Saiki and H. A. Erlich, \"Enzymatic Amplification of \u03b2-globin Genomic Sequences and Restriction Site Analysis for Diagnosis of Sickle Cell Anemia\"\u2014the polymerase chain reaction invention (PCR) -- was honored by a Citation for Chemical Breakthrough Award from the Division of History of Chemistry of the American Chemical Society in 2017.<ref name=\"breakthrough\">{{Cite web|title=Citations for Chemical Breakthrough Awards 2017 Awardees|url=http://www.scs.illinois.edu/~mainzv/HIST/awards/CCB-2017_Awardees.php|website=Division of the History of Chemistry|access-date=12 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Saiki|first1=R.|last2=Scharf|first2=S|last3=Faloona|first3=F|last4=Mullis|first4=K.|last5=Horn|first5=G.|last6=Erlich|first6=H.|last7=Arnheim|first7=N|title=Enzymatic amplification of beta-globin genomic sequences and restriction site analysis for diagnosis of sickle cell anemia|journal=Science|date=20 December 1985|volume=230|issue=4732|pages=1350\u20131354|doi=10.1126/science.2999980|pmid=2999980|bibcode=1985Sci...230.1350S}}</ref>\n\nA drawback of the technique was that the DNA polymerase in the reaction was destroyed by the high heat used at the start of each replication cycle and had to be replaced. In 1986, Saiki started to use ''[[Thermophilus aquaticus]]'' (Taq) [[DNA polymerase]] to amplify segments of DNA. The Taq polymerase was heat resistant and only need to be added to the reaction once, making the technique dramatically more affordable and subject to automation. This modification of Mullis' invention revolutionized [[biochemistry]], [[molecular biology]], [[genetics]], medicine, and [[forensics]].\n\nMullis also invented a UV-sensitive plastic that changes color in response to light.\n\nHe founded Altermune LLC in 2011 to pursue new ideas on the immune system.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/09/22/idUS134319+22-Sep-2011+BW20110922 Loxbridge and Dr Kary Mullis Announce the Formation of Altermune Technologies with $7m Seed Investment.] [https://web.archive.org/web/20140914135558/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/09/22/idUS134319+22-Sep-2011+BW20110922 Archived]</ref> Mullis described the company's novel technology in a presentation:\n{{Quote | style=font-size:100% |It is a method using specific synthetic chemical linkers to divert an immune response from its nominal target to something completely different which you would right now like to be temporarily immune to. Let's say you just got exposed to a new strain of the flu. You're already immune to alpha-1,3-galactosyl-galactose bonds. All humans are. Why not divert a fraction of those antibodies to the influenza strain you just picked up? A chemical linker synthesized with an alpha-1,3-gal-gal bond on one end and a DNA aptamer devised to bind specifically to the strain of influenza you have on the other end will link anti-alpha-Gal antibodies to the influenza virus and presto!--you have fooled your immune system into attacking the new virus.<ref name=\"nobelbio\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ted.com/talks/lang/eng/kary_mullis_next_gen_cure_for_killer_infections.html |title=Kary Mullis' next-gen cure for killer infections &#124; Video on |publisher=Ted.com |date=February 2009 |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref>}}\n\nThe first proof-of-principle of this technology, re-targeting pre-existing antibodies to the surface of a pathogenic strep bacteria using an alpha-gal modified aptamer (\"alphamer\"), was published in 2015 in collaboration with scientists at the University of California, San Diego.<ref>{{Cite press release | first=Heather | last=Buschman | title=Molecular Homing Beacon Redirects Human Antibodies to Fight Pathogenic Bacteria | url=http://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/pressrelease/molecular_homing_beacon_redirects_human_antibodies_to_fight_pathogenic_bact | publisher=[[University of California, San Diego]] | date=May 6, 2015 | access-date=July 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid=25940316 | title=Retargeting pre-existing human antibodies to a bacterial pathogen with an alpha-Gal conjugated aptamer | doi=10.1007/s00109-015-1280-4 | pmc=4469262 | volume=93 | issue=6 | year=2015 | journal=J. Mol. Med. | pages=619\u201331 | last1=Kristian | first1=SA | last2=Hwang | first2=JH | last3=Hall | first3=B | last4=Leire | first4=E | last5=Iacomini | first5=J | last6=Old | first6=R | last7=Galili | first7=U | last8=Roberts | first8=C | last9=Mullis | first9=KB | last10=Westby | first10=M | last11=Nizet | first11=V}}</ref>\n\n=== Accreditation of the PCR technique ===\nA concept similar to that of PCR had been described before Mullis' work. Nobel laureate [[H. Gobind Khorana]] and Kjell Kleppe, a Norwegian scientist, authored a paper 17 years earlier describing a process they termed \"repair replication\" in the ''[[Journal of Molecular Biology]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last1=Kleppe|first1=K.|last2=Ohtsuka|first2=E.|last3=Kleppe|first3=R.|last4=Molineux|first4=I.|last5=Khorana|first5=H. G.|authorlink5=Har Gobind Khorana|year=1971|title=Studies on polynucleotides *1, *2XCVI. Repair replication of short synthetic DNA's as catalyzed by DNA polymerases|journal=Journal of Molecular Biology|volume=56|issue=2|pages=341\u2013361|doi=10.1016/0022-2836(71)90469-4|pmc=|pmid=4927950}}</ref> Using repair replication, Kleppe duplicated and then quadrupled a small synthetic molecule with the help of two primers and DNA polymerase. The method developed by Mullis used repeated thermal cycling, which allowed the rapid and exponential amplification of large quantities of any desired DNA sequence from an extremely complex template. Later a heat-stable DNA polymerase was incorporated into the process.\n\nHis co-workers at Cetus, who were embittered by his abrupt departure from the company,<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" />\ncontested that Mullis was solely responsible for the idea of using [[Taq polymerase]] in PCR. However, other scientists have written that the \"full potential [of PCR] was not realized\" until Mullis' work in 1983,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dexRnDtLlWUC&pg=PA20&dq=%22kary+mullis%22+%2B+%22kjell+kleppe%22 |title=''Artificial DNA: Methods and Applications'' by Yury E. Khudyakov, Howard A. Fields |access-date=July 27, 2010|isbn=978-0-8493-1426-1|year=2003|last1=Khudyakov |first1=Yury E. |last2=Fields |first2=Howard A.}}</ref> and that Mullis' colleagues failed to see the potential of the technique when he presented it to them.<ref name=\"lifeonedge\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=J5IwomfEGiEC&pg=PA103&dq=%22kary+mullis%22 |title=''Life on the Edge: Amazing Creatures Thriving in Extreme Environments'' by Michael Gross |date= January 24, 2001|access-date=July 27, 2010|isbn=978-0-7382-0445-1|last1=Gross |first1=Michael}}</ref> As a result, some controversy surrounds the balance of credit that should be given to Mullis versus the team at Cetus.<ref name=\"NYTimes1998\" /> In practice, credit has accrued to both the inventor and the company (although not its individual workers) in the form of a Nobel Prize and a $10,000 Cetus bonus for Mullis and $300 million for Cetus when the company sold the patent to [[Hoffmann-La Roche|Roche Molecular Systems]]. After [[DuPont (1802\u20132017)|DuPont]] lost out to Roche on that sale, the company unsuccessfully disputed Mullis' patent on the alleged grounds that PCR had been previously described in 1971.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Mullis and Erlich took Cetus' side in the case, and Khorana refused to testify for DuPont; the jury upheld Mullis' patent in 1991.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> However, in February 1999, the patent of Hoffman-La Roche (United States Patent No. 4,889,818) was found by the courts to be unenforceable, after Dr. Thomas Kunkel testified in the case ''Hoffman-La Roche v. Promega Corporation''<ref name=Roche_v_Promega>{{Cite web|url=https://www.casemine.com/judgement/us/5914b97badd7b0493478b532|title=Hoffmann-La Roche, Inc. v. Promega Corporation, (N.D.Cal. 2001)|publisher=Casemine|author=United States District Court, N.D. California.|date=July 26, 2001|access-date=April 8, 2018}}</ref> on behalf of the defendants ([[Promega Corporation]]) that \"prior art\" (i.e. articles on the subject of Taq polymerase published by other groups prior to the work of Gelfand and Stoffel, and their patent application regarding the purification of Taq polymerase) existed, in the form of two articles, published by Alice Chien et al. in 1976,<ref name=\"Chien\">{{Cite journal | last1=Chien | first1=A. | last2=Edgar | first2=D.B. | last3=Trela | first3=J.M. | title=Deoxyribonucleic acid polymerase from the extreme thermophile Thermus aquaticus | journal=J. Bacteriol. | volume=127 | issue=3 | pages=1550\u20131557 | year=1976 | pmid=8432 | pmc=232952 | doi=10.1128/jb.127.3.1550-1557.1976}}</ref> and A. S. Kaledin et al. in 1980.<ref name=\"Kaledin\">{{Cite journal | last1=Kaledin | first1=A.S. | last2=Sliusarenko | first2=A.G. | last3=Gorodetskii | first3=S.I. | title=Isolation and properties of DNA polymerase from extreme thermophylic bacteria Thermus aquaticus YT-1 | journal=[[Biokhimiia]] | volume=45 | issue=4 | pages=644\u2013651 | year=1980 | pmid=7378495}}</ref>\n\nThe [[anthropology|anthropologist]] [[Paul Rabinow]] wrote a book on the history of the PCR method in 1996 (entitled ''Making PCR'') in which he discussed whether Mullis \"invented\" PCR or \"merely\" came up with the concept of it. Rabinow, a [[Michel Foucault|Foucault]] scholar interested in issues of the production of knowledge, used the topic to argue against the idea that scientific discovery is the product of individual work, writing, \"Committees and science journalists like the idea of associating a unique idea with a unique person, the lone genius. PCR is thought by some to be an example of teamwork, but by others as the genius of one who was smart enough to put things together which were present to all, but overlooked. For Mullis, the light bulb went off, but for others it did not. This is consistent with the idea, that the prepared (educated) mind who is careful to observe and not overlook, is what separates the genius scientist from his many also smart scientists. The proof is in the fact that the person who has the light bulb go off never forgets the \"Ah!\" experience, while the others never had this photochemical reaction go off in their brains.\"<ref>{{Cite web|author=Richard Bilsker |url=http://www.hyle.org/journal/issues/4/bilsker.htm |title=Ethnography of a Nobel Prize |publisher=Hyle.org |date= |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Personal views ==\nMullis was quoted saying \"the never-ending quest for more grants and staying with established dogmas\" has hurt science.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> He believed that \"science is being practiced by people who are dependent on being paid for what they are ''going'' to find out,\" not for what they actually produce.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Mullis was described by some as an \"impatient and impulsive researcher\" who finds routine laboratory work boring and instead thinks about his research while driving and surfing. He came up with the idea of the polymerase chain reaction while driving along a highway.<ref>{{Cite book | last =Fridell | first=R |title=Decoding life: unraveling the mysteries of the genome |publisher= Lerner Publications | location =Minneapolis |year=2005 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Cpa6lEhiD0C&pg=PA88#v=onepage&q&f=false | page=88 |isbn=978-0-8225-1196-0}}</ref>\n\nIn his 1998 humorous autobiography, Mullis expressed disagreement with the scientific evidence supporting [[climate change]] and [[ozone depletion]], the evidence that [[AIDS denialism|HIV causes AIDS]], and asserted his belief in [[astrology]].<ref name=\"Naked\" />\n<ref name=\"naked-capricorn\">{{cite book |title=Dancing Naked in the Mind Field |first=Kary |last=Mullis |author-link=Kary Mullis |year=1998 |chapter=Chapter 15: I am a Capricorn |page=143\u201353 |chapter-url=http://www.crawfordperspectives.com/documents/IAMACAPRICORN_000.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051221093301/http://www.crawfordperspectives.com/documents/IAMACAPRICORN_000.pdf |archive-date=December 21, 2005 |url-status=live |isbn=<!--uncertain-->}}</ref> \nMullis claimed climate change and the HIV/AIDS connection are due to a [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy]] of environmentalists, government agencies, and scientists attempting to preserve their careers and earn money, rather than scientific evidence.<ref name=Naked>{{Cite book | title=Dancing Naked in the Mind Field | last=Mullis | first=K | year=1998 | publisher=Vintage Books | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MCAqomvRYNMC&pg=PA115#v=onepage&q&f=false | pages=115\u201318, 143\u201353 | isbn=978-0-679-44255-4}}</ref> \nMullis has been criticized for his association with HIV skeptic [[Peter Duesberg]],<ref name=\"Find\">{{Cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/HEALTH/AIDS/9909/15/aids.heresies3/ | title=AIDS heresies: From maverick science to conspiracy theories | publisher=CNN | date=September 15, 1999 | access-date=February 26, 2014 | author=Horvath, Hacsi}}</ref> claiming that AIDS is an arbitrary diagnosis used when HIV antibodies are found in a patient's blood.<ref name=Informer>{{Cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79665692.html |title=Washington Informer |publisher=High beam |date=May 31, 2000 |access-date=July 27, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104075451/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79665692.html |archive-date=November 4, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The medical and scientific consensus is that Duesberg's hypothesis is [[pseudoscience]], HIV having been conclusively proven to be the cause of AIDS<ref name= iomreport >{{Cite book | url=http://books.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=771&page=2 | title=Confronting AIDS: Update 1988 | publisher=[[Institute of Medicine]] of the [[U.S. National Academy of Sciences]] | year=1988 | quote=... the evidence that HIV causes AIDS is scientifically conclusive.| doi=10.17226/771 | pmid=25032454 | isbn=978-0-309-03879-9 | author1=Institute of Medicine (US) Committee for the Oversight of AIDS Activities }}</ref><ref name=niaid>{{Cite web | url=http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/topics/HIVAIDS/Understanding/howHIVCausesAIDS/HIVcausesAIDS.htm | title=The Evidence that HIV Causes AIDS | access-date=October 14, 2009 | publisher=[[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Disease]] | date=September 4, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124091249/http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/topics/HIVAIDS/Understanding/howHIVCausesAIDS/HIVcausesAIDS.htm |archivedate=November 24, 2009}}</ref> and that global warming is occurring because of human activities.<ref name=Beyond>{{Cite journal| last=Oreskes| first=Naomi| author-link=Naomi Oreskes | title=Beyond the Ivory Tower: The Scientific Consensus on Climate Change | journal=Science | volume=306 | page=1686 | date=December 2004| url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/full/306/5702/1686 | quote=Such statements suggest that there might be substantive disagreement in the scientific community about the reality of anthropogenic climate change. This is not the case. ... Politicians, economists, journalists, and others may have the impression of confusion, disagreement, or discord among climate scientists, but that impression is incorrect.| doi=10.1126/science.1103618| pmid=15576594| issue=5702| doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=National>{{Cite web | url=http://nationalacademies.org/onpi/06072005.pdf | title=Joint Science Academies' Statement | date=July 6, 2005 | access-date=June 9, 2011 | publisher=United States National Academies}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dels-old.nas.edu/dels/rpt_briefs/climate_change_2008_final.pdf |title=Understanding and Responding to Climate Change |year=2008 |access-date=June 9, 2011 |publisher=United States National Academies |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423073539/http://dels-old.nas.edu/dels/rpt_briefs/climate_change_2008_final.pdf |archivedate=April 23, 2013}}</ref> Seth Kalichman, AIDS researcher and author of ''Denying AIDS'', \"[admits] that it seems odd to include a Nobel laureate among the who's who of AIDS pseudoscientists\".<ref name=Kalichman>{{Cite book |authorlink=Seth Kalichman|author=Kalichman, Seth |title=Denying AIDS: Conspiracy Theories, Pseudoscience, and Human Tragedy |publisher=Copernicus Books ([[Springer Science+Business Media]]) |location=New York |year=2009 |pages= [https://books.google.com/books?id=_mtDBCDwxugC&pg=PA177#v=onepage&q&f=false 177\u2013178] |isbn=978-0-387-79475-4 | url =}}</ref> Mullis also wrote the foreword to the book ''What If Everything You Thought You Knew About AIDS Was Wrong?'' by [[Christine Maggiore]],<ref name=Wrong>{{Cite book |author=Maggiore C|title=What If Everything You Thought You Knew About AIDS Was Wrong? |publisher=American Foundation For AIDS Alternative |location= |year=2006 |pages= |isbn=978-0-9674153-2-1 |oclc= |doi= |access-date=}}</ref> an HIV-positive AIDS denialist who, along with her 3-years-old daughter, died of an AIDS-related illness.<ref name=LATdeath>{{Cite news |title= Christine Maggiore, vocal skeptic of AIDS research, dies at 52|newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]]|date= December 30, 2008|access-date=December 30, 2008|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-christine-maggiore30-2008dec30,0,7407966.story |first1=Anna |last1=Gorman |first2=Alexandra |last2=Zavis}}</ref> A ''[[New York Times]]'' article listed Mullis as one of several scientists who, after success in their area of research, go on to make unfounded, sometimes bizarre statements in other areas.<ref name=NYT>{{Cite news | last=Johnson | first=G | title=Bright Scientists, Dim Notions | work=[[The New York Times]] | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/28/weekinreview/28johnson.html?_r=3&adxnnl=1&oref=slogin&ref=science&adxnnlx=1193583001-IE12EKQeJt1sjwCUOYPVWg&oref=slogin | date=October 28, 2007 | access-date=August 6, 2010}}</ref> An article in the ''[[Skeptical Inquirer]]'' described Mullis as an \"AIDS denialist with scientific credentials [who] has never done any scientific research on HIV or AIDS.\"<ref name=SI>{{Cite journal | url=http://www.csicop.org/si/show/aids_denialism_vs._science/ | title=AIDS Denialism vs. Science | volume=31 | issue=5 | last=Nattrass | first=N | year=2007 | journal=[[Skeptical Inquirer]]}}</ref> However, he consulted for Specialty Labs, in Santa Monica, developing a nucleic acid based HIV test. While writing a NIH grant progress report, he was unable to find a peer-reviewed reference that HIV was the cause of AIDS.<ref name=\"Naked\" /><ref name=\"Wrong\" /> Mullis published an alternative theory of AIDS in 1994.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mullis|first=Kary B.|date=1995|title=A hypothetical disease of the immune system that may bear some relation to the Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome|journal=Genetica|volume=95|issue=1\u20133|pages=195\u2013197|doi=10.1007/bf01435010|pmid=7744261|issn=0016-6707}}</ref> He questioned the scientific validity of the link between HIV and AIDS, leading some to label him an \"AIDS denialist.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Seth|last=Kalichman| url=https://newhumanist.org.uk/articles/2165/how-to-spot-an-aids-denialist | title=How to spot an AIDS denialist | date=November 3, 2009 | access-date=August 14, 2019 | journal=New Humanist}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Basu|first=Paroma|date=June 1, 2005|title=AIDS denialists back on the upswing|journal=Nature|volume=11|issue=6|page=581|doi=10.1038/nm0605-581b|pmid=15937451|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/01d1fc960fff86c208c277f9f13fefde49140065}}</ref>\n\n== Use of hallucinogens ==\nMullis detailed his experiences synthesizing and testing various psychedelic amphetamines and a difficult trip on [[Diethyltryptamine|DET]] in his autobiography. In a Q&A interview published in the September 1994 issue of ''[[California Monthly]]'', Mullis said, \"Back in the 1960s and early 1970s I took plenty of [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]]. A lot of people were doing that in Berkeley back then. And I found it to be a mind-opening experience. It was certainly much more important than any courses I ever took.\"<ref>{{Cite journal | last=Schoch | first=Russell | title=Q&A \u2013 A Conversation with Kerry Mullis | journal=California Monthly | volume=105 | issue=1 | page=20 | publisher=[[California Alumni Association]] | location=Berkeley, California |date=September 1994| url=http://www.alumni.berkeley.edu/Alumni/Cal_Monthly/September_1994/QA_-_A_Conversation_with_Kerry_Mullis.asp | access-date=March 11, 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901144701/http://www.alumni.berkeley.edu/Alumni/Cal_Monthly/September_1994/QA_-_A_Conversation_with_Kerry_Mullis.asp | archivedate=September 1, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{vn|date=December 2019}} During a symposium held for centenarian [[Albert Hofmann]], Hofmann said Mullis had told him that LSD had \"helped him develop the polymerase chain reaction that helps amplify specific DNA sequences\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/science/discoveries/news/2006/01/70015 |title=LSD: The Geek's Wonder Drug? |access-date=March 11, 2008 |author=Harrison, Ann |date=January 16, 2006 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |publisher=Wired |quote=Like Herbert, many scientists and engineers also report heightened states of creativity while using LSD. During a press conference on Friday, Hofmann revealed that he was told by Nobel-prize-winning chemist Kary Mullis that LSD had helped him develop the polymerase chain reaction that helps amplify specific DNA sequences.}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nKnown for his quick wit and colorful stories, Mullis enjoyed [[surfing]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Golden |first=Frederic |url=http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,91819,00.html |title=''Time Magazine'', December 13, 2000 |magazine=Time.com |date=December 13, 2000 |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> He married four times,<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> and had a total of three children by two of his wives. At the time of his death, he had two grandchildren. He used profanities to make a point and often said, \"Oh, Lord,\" in response to the absurdities experienced in life.<ref name=\"esquire 1994\" /> Mullis reported an encounter with a \"standard extraterrestrial raccoon\" at his cabin in the woods of northern California around midnight one night in 1985; he denied being on [[psychedelic drug]]s at the time.<ref>{{Citation|last=Bullard|first=Thomas|title=The Myth and Mystery of UFOs|url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/v33/n22/jenny-diski/what-might-they-want|number=22|type=Review|journal=LRB|volume=33|place=UK|date=November 17, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Naked\" />\n\nMullis died of [[pneumonia]]<ref name=\"death1\">{{Cite news|url=https://mynewsla.com/education/2019/08/08/nobel-winner-kary-banks-mullis-who-revolutionized-dna-research-dies-in-o-c/|title=Nobel Winner Kary Banks Mullis, Who Revolutionized DNA Research, Dies in O.C.|publisher=MyNewsLA.com|date=August 8, 2019|access-date=August 11, 2019}}</ref> on August 7, 2019 at age 74 in [[Newport Beach, California]].<ref name=\"death2\">{{Cite news|first=Debbie|last=Dclark|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/news/nobel-prize-winning-chemist-who-grew-up-in-sc-capital/article_f69354e6-baa3-11e9-b4d2-e7b21bfe5bfd.html|title=Nobel Prize-winning chemist who grew up in SC capital dies at 74|publisher=postandcourier.com | work=[[The Post and Courier]] |date=August 9, 2019|access-date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Publications and books ==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Mullis | first1 = Kary | year = 1968 | title = Cosmological Significance of Time Reversal | journal = Nature | volume = 218 | issue = 5142| pages = 663\u2013664 | doi = 10.1038/218663b0 | bibcode = 1968Natur.218..663M | url = https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/9bedef8385043ca9603539ce73ae5f144dcd84eb }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Mullis | first1 = K.F. | last2 = Faloona | first2 = F. | last3 = Scharf | first3 = S. | last4 = Saiki | first4 = R. | last5 = Horn | first5 = G. | last6 = Erlich | first6 = H. | year = 1986 | title = Specific enzymatic amplification of DNA in vitro: The polymerase chain reaction | url = | journal = Cold Spring Harbor Symposia on Quantitative Biology| volume = 51 | issue = | pages = 263\u2013273 | doi = 10.1101/sqb.1986.051.01.032 | pmid = 3472723 }}\n* K. Mullis, 1990, ''The unusual origin of the polymerase chain reaction''. ''Scientific American'', April 56\u201365.\n* ''The Polymerase Chain Reaction'', 1994, co-edited Francious Ferre and Richard A. Gibbs (Basel: Birkhauser) {{ISBN|0817637508}} {{ISBN|978-0817637507}}.\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1007/BF01435010|pmid=7744261|title=A hypothetical disease of the immune system that may bear some relation to the Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome|journal=Genetica|volume=95|issue=1\u20133|pages=195\u2013197|year=1995|last1=Mullis|first1=Kary B.|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/bd1f14f63e48f1aa3be46a6cb138b9eb56379858}}\n* Mullis' 1998 humorous autobiography ''Dancing Naked in the Mind Field'' ({{ISBN|978-0679774006}}), gives his account of the commercial development of [[polymerase chain reaction|PCR]], as well as providing insights into his opinions and experiences. In the book, Mullis chronicles his romantic relationships, use of LSD, synthesis and self-testing of novel psychoactive substances, belief in [[astrology]] and an encounter with an [[Extraterrestrial life|extraterrestrial]] in the form of a fluorescent raccoon.\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n* 1990&nbsp;\u2014 [[William Allan Award|William Allan Memorial Award]] of the American Society of Human Genetics,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ashg.org/awards/pastrecipients.shtml#allan|title=Past Recipients, William Allan Award|publisher=American Society of Human Genetics|access-date=August 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804212043/http://www.ashg.org/awards/pastrecipients.shtml#allan|archive-date=August 4, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> Preis Biochemische Analytik of the German Society of Clinical Chemistry and [[Boehringer Mannheim]]<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.dgkl.de/en/die-dgkl/awards/preis-fuer-biochemische-analytik/preistraeger/|title=Award Winners 1970&nbsp;\u2014 2017|publisher=German Society for Clinical Chemistry and Laboratory Medicine|access-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n* 1991&nbsp;\u2014 National Biotechnology Award,<ref name=\"newton\">{{Cite book| url= https://books.google.com/?id=1jM4B1JffrgC&pg=PA163 | title=Forensic Chemistry | first=David E. | last=Newton|date= 2007|access-date=August 14, 2019|isbn=978-1438109763|publisher=Facts On File, Inc.|location=New York}}</ref> [[Canada Gairdner International Award|Gairdner Award]],<ref name=\"newton\" /> R&D Scientist of the Year,<ref name=\"newton\" /> [[John Scott Award]] of the City Trusts of [[Philadelphia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.garfield.library.upenn.edu/johnscottaward(full).html |title=John Scott Award Winners |publisher=U Penn |date=October 28, 2005 |access-date=July 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701201455/http://www.garfield.library.upenn.edu/johnscottaward%28full%29.html |archivedate=July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n* 1992&nbsp;\u2014 California Scientist of the Year Award<ref name=\"newton\" />\n* 1992&nbsp;\u2014 [[Robert Koch Prize]]<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.robert-koch-stiftung.de/index.php?article_id=15&clang=1|title=Robert Koch Award|publisher=Robert-Koch-Stiftung|access-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n* 1993&nbsp;\u2014 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, [[Japan Prize]],<ref name=jp /> Thomas A. Edison Award<ref name=\"newton\" />\n* 1994&nbsp;\u2014 Honorary degree of Doctor of Science from the [[University of South Carolina]]<ref name=\"website\" />\n* 1998&nbsp;\u2014 Inducted into the [[National Inventors Hall of Fame]],<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.invent.org/Hall_Of_Fame/109.html |title=Hall of Fame |contribution=Inventor Profile |publisher=Invent.org |date=December 28, 1944 |access-date=July 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706045503/http://www.invent.org/hall_of_fame/109.html |archivedate=July 6, 2010 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Ronald H. Brown American Innovator Award<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.uspto.gov/web/offices/com/speeches/98-18.htm | title= Nobel Prize Winner Among Rondal H. Brown Award Recipients | publisher= PTO | place=USA | date=October 13, 1998 |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref>\n* 2004&nbsp;\u2014 Honorary degree in Pharmaceutical Biotechnology from the [[University of Bologna]], Italy<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.almanews.unibo.it/03_04/Html/mullis.htm|title=Laurea ad honorem a Kary Mullis|publisher=University of Bologna|access-date=August 14, 2019|language=Italian}}</ref>\n* 2010&nbsp;\u2014 Honorary degree of Doctor honoris causa in the field of biological sciences from [[Masaryk University]], Czech Republic<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.muni.cz/en/about-us/awards/342|title=Kary Banks Mullis|publisher=Masaryk University|access-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{POV section|date=September 2019}}\n* [[House of Numbers (2009 film)|House of Numbers]]\n* [[Luc Montagnier]]&nbsp;\u2014 Nobel prize winning HIV researcher who now endorses [[homeopathy]]\n* [[Nobel Prize controversies]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*[[Paul Rabinow]], ''Making PCR: a story of biotechnology'' (University of Chicago Press, 1996). {{ISBN|0-226-70147-6}}\n* Anthony Liversidge, {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010121194200/http://omnimag.com/archives/interviews/mullis.html |date=January 21, 2001 |title=\"Kary Mullis, the great gene machine\"}}, ''[[Omni (magazine)|Omni]]'' magazine (April 1992).\n* Kary Mullis, ''Dancing Naked in the Mind Field''. Vintage Books (1998). {{ISBN|0-679-44255-3}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Kary Mullis}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Citation | url=http://www.karymullis.com/ | title=Kary Mullis | type=personal webpage}}.\n*{{Citation | url=http://www.directoryinventor.com/inventor/03d4659f7b0373002cb929636bca9e48_1.html/ | title=Patent portfolio | publisher=Directory inventor | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130110223017/http://www.directoryinventor.com/inventor/03d4659f7b0373002cb929636bca9e48_1.html/ | archivedate=January 10, 2013 | df=mdy-all}}.\n*{{Find a Grave|201986282}}\n\n=== Interviews ===\n*{{Citation | url=http://nobelprize.org/mediaplayer/index.php?id=428 | year=2005 | title=Interview | publisher=Nobel Prize committee}}.\n*{{Citation | url=http://old.valleyadvocate.com/hiv-aids/i980714.html | year=1998 | title=Interview | first=Sarah | last=Klipfel | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050706052721/http://old.valleyadvocate.com/hiv-aids/i980714.html | archivedate=July 6, 2005 | df=mdy-all}} regarding his views on HIV/AIDS.\n\n{{Nobel Prize in Chemistry}}\n{{1993 Nobel Prize winners}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mullis, Kary}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:American biochemists]]\n[[Category:American Nobel laureates]]\n[[Category:Nobel laureates in Chemistry]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS denialists]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Columbia, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Lenoir, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Biotechnologists]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic drug advocates]]\n[[Category:Scientists from North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Fixing links to disambiguation pages, improving links, other minor cleanup tasks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kary_Mullis"}
{"title_page": "Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko", "text_new": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Auxiliary bishop\n| honorific-prefix = [[Monsignor]]\n| name             = Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Zagreb|Auxiliary bishop of Zagreb]]\n| image            = Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| church           = \n| archdiocese      = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Zagreb]]\n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = [[Zagreb]]\n| elected          = \n| appointed        = 11 February 2008\n| term             = \n| term_start       = 29 March 2008\n| quashed          = \n| term_end         = \n| predecessor      = \n| opposed          = \n| successor        = \n| other_post       = Titular Bishop of Rotary (2008-)\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = 28 June 1992\n| ordained_by      = [[Franjo Kuharic]]\n| consecration     = 29 March 2008\n| consecrated_by   = [[Josip Bozanic]]\n| cardinal         = \n| rank             = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1966|08|01|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[\u00d0ivan]] near [[Vrbovec]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]]<br /> <small>(now [[Croatia]])</small>\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| buried           = \n| nationality      = [[Croatia]]n\n| religion         = Roman Catholic\n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| previous_post    = \n| alma_mater       = [[Pontifical Gregorian University]]<br>[[Pontifical Atheneum of St. Anselm]]\n| motto            = In novitate vitae <br />In newness of life<br />(Romans 6:4)\n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = Coat of arms of Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko.svg\n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n<!---------- Sainthood ---------->\n| feast_day        = \n| venerated        = \n| saint_title      = \n| beatified_date   = \n| beatified_place  = \n| beatified_by     = \n| canonized_date   = \n| canonized_place  = \n| canonized_by     = \n| attributes       = \n| patronage        = \n| shrine           = \n| suppressed_date  = \n<!---------- Other ---------->\n}}\n\n'''Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko''' (born in [[\u00d0ivan]] near [[Vrbovec]], 1 August 1966) is a [[Croatia]]n prelate of the Roman Catholic Church who serves as [[Auxiliary bishop]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Zagreb]] since  March 29, 2008.\n\n==Early life and education==\nIvan \u0160a\u0161ko was born in a small village of [[\u00d0ivan]] near [[Vrbovec]] on 1 August 1966 to Stjepan and Ljubica \u0160a\u0161ko. He attended first two classes of the elementary school in [[Banovo]], and finished it at [[Vrbovec]] in the year 1981. After graduation, he attended [[minor seminary]] in [[Zagreb]]. He graduated from ''Interdiocese Preparatory Seminary'' in 1985 after which he went to serve [[conscription]] in the army. In autumn of 1986, \u0160a\u0161ko entered [[major seminary]] and started the study of theology and philosophy at the Catholic Theological Faculty of the [[University of Zagreb]]. Upon completion of the second year of study in 1988, \u0160a\u0161ko went to [[Rome]] to the [[Pontifical Atheneum of St. Anselm]] where he stayed until 1994 and continued his studies at the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] from which he graduated in 1991. In the same year, he was ordained a deacon for the [[Archdiocese of Zagreb]] and began postgraduate studies and specialization in the liturgy at the [[Pontifical Atheneum of St. Anselm]]. On 28 June 1992, \u0160a\u0161ko was ordained a priest for the [[Archdiocese of Zagreb]] by Cardinal [[Franjo Kuhari\u0107]]. He gained his Master's degree on 10 June 1994. That same year he became a member of the [[Pontifical Croatian College of St. Jerome]] and continued writing a doctoral dissertation. \u0160a\u0161ko successfully defended a dissertation on 28 November 1997, with the thesis ''Dona, munera, sancta sacrif\u00edcio - and omnibus ... facere digneris: dinamismo pneumatologici part Canone Romano. Ricerca e proposta per una rilettura teologico-liturgica''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zg-nadbiskupija.hr/nadbiskupski-duhovni-stol/pomocni-biskupi-i-generalni-vikari/mons-ivan-sasko |title=Mons. Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko - Zagreba\u010dka nadbiskupija |website=Zg-nadbiskupija.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1996 \u0160a\u0161ko came back to Croatia and started working as an assistant in the Department of the liturgy of the Zagreb Catholic Theological Faculty. From the year 2000 he worked as [[docent]] in the same department. From 2002 to 2007, he was head of the Department of the liturgy. From 2001 he is a member of the Assembly of prebendaries of the [[Zagreb cathedral]]. In 2008 he was appointed canon of the Cathedral Kaptol of Zagreb. In January 2005 he was appointed President of the Commission for the establishment of the [[Catholic University of Croatia]], and still today, after the University opening in 2006, continues as the President of the Commission of the University. In April 2005 he was elected associate professor in the Department of the liturgy of Zagreb Catholic Theological Faculty. He is member of the editorial board of the scientific journal ''[[Bogoslovska smotra]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbk.hr/?type=diocesan&ID=5 |title=HBK - Hrvatska biskupska konferencija |website=Hbk.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref> In October 2005, \u0160a\u0161ko participated in the IX Regular General Synod of Bishops in the [[Holy See|Vatican]], in a group of Assistants to the Special Secretary of the Synod. During three pastoral visits of [[Pope John Paul II]] to Croatia, he was one of those responsible for the preparation of liturgical celebrations.\n\nOn 11 February 2008, [[Pope Benedict XVI]] appointed \u0160a\u0161ko auxiliary bishop of Zagreb and titular Bishop of Rotary. Cardinal [[Josip Bozani\u0107]] ordained him on 29 March 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glas-koncila.hr/?conID=6316 |title=Doga\u0111anja &#124; Zare\u0111en zagreba\u010dki pomo\u0107ni biskup Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko &#124; Portal Glasa Koncila |website=Glas-koncila.hr |date=2008-03-29 |accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sasko, Ivan}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic bishops in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Croatian theologians]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Auxiliary bishop\n| honorific-prefix = [[Monsignor]]\n| name             = Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Zagreb|Auxiliary bishop of Zagreb]]\n| image            = Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| church           = \n| archdiocese      = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Zagreb]]\n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = [[Zagreb]]\n| elected          = \n| appointed        = 11 February 2008\n| term             = \n| term_start       = 29 March 2008\n| quashed          = \n| term_end         = \n| predecessor      = \n| opposed          = \n| successor        = \n| other_post       = Titular Bishop of Rotary (2008-)\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = 28 June 1992\n| ordained_by      = [[Franjo Kuharic]]\n| consecration     = 29 March 2008\n| consecrated_by   = [[Josip Bozanic]]\n| cardinal         = \n| rank             = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1966|08|01|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[\u00d0ivan]] near [[Vrbovec]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]]<br /> <small>(now [[Croatia]])</small>\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| buried           = \n| nationality      = [[Croatia]]n\n| religion         = Roman Catholic\n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| previous_post    = \n| alma_mater       = [[Pontifical Gregorian University]]<br>[[Pontifical Atheneum of St. Anselm]]\n| motto            = In novitate vitae <br />In newness of life<br />(Romans 6:4)\n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = Coat of arms of Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko.svg\n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n<!---------- Sainthood ---------->\n| feast_day        = \n| venerated        = \n| saint_title      = \n| beatified_date   = \n| beatified_place  = \n| beatified_by     = \n| canonized_date   = \n| canonized_place  = \n| canonized_by     = \n| attributes       = \n| patronage        = \n| shrine           = \n| suppressed_date  = \n<!---------- Other ---------->\n}}\n\n'''Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko''' (born in [[\u00d0ivan]] near [[Vrbovec]], 1 August 1966) is a [[Croatia]]n prelate of the Roman Catholic Church who serves as [[Auxiliary bishop]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Zagreb]] since  March 29, 2008.\n\n==Early life and education==\nIvan \u0160a\u0161ko was born in a small village of [[\u00d0ivan]] near [[Vrbovec]] on 1 August 1966 to Stjepan and Ljubica \u0160a\u0161ko. He attended first two classes of the elementary school in [[Banovo]], and finished it at [[Vrbovec]] in the year 1981. After graduation, he attended [[minor seminary]] in [[Zagreb]]. He graduated from ''Interdiocese Preparatory Seminary'' in 1985 after which he went to serve [[conscription]] in the army. In autumn of 1986, \u0160a\u0161ko entered [[major seminary]] and started the study of theology and philosophy at the Catholic Theological Faculty of the [[University of Zagreb]]. Upon completion of the second year of study in 1988, \u0160a\u0161ko went to [[Rome]] to the [[Pontifical Atheneum of St. Anselm]] where he stayed until 1994 and continued his studies at the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] from which he graduated in 1991. In the same year, he was ordained a deacon for the [[Archdiocese of Zagreb]] and began postgraduate studies and specialization in the liturgy at the [[Pontifical Atheneum of St. Anselm]]. On 28 June 1992, \u0160a\u0161ko was ordained a priest for the [[Archdiocese of Zagreb]] by Cardinal [[Franjo Kuhari\u0107]]. He gained his Master's degree on 10 June 1994. That same year he became a member of the [[Pontifical Croatian College of St. Jerome]] and continued writing a doctoral dissertation. \u0160a\u0161ko successfully defended a dissertation on 28 November 1997, with the thesis ''Dona, munera, sancta sacrif\u00edcio - and omnibus ... facere digneris: dinamismo pneumatologici part Canone Romano. Ricerca e proposta per una rilettura teologico-liturgica''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zg-nadbiskupija.hr/nadbiskupski-duhovni-stol/pomocni-biskupi-i-generalni-vikari/mons-ivan-sasko |title=Mons. Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko - Zagreba\u010dka nadbiskupija |website=Zg-nadbiskupija.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1996 \u0160a\u0161ko came back to Croatia and started working as an assistant in the Department of the liturgy of the Zagreb Catholic Theological Faculty. From the year 2000 he worked as [[docent]] in the same department. From 2002 to 2007, he was head of the Department of the liturgy. From 2001 he is a member of the Assembly of prebendaries of the [[Zagreb cathedral]]. In 2008 he was appointed canon of the Cathedral Kaptol of Zagreb. In January 2005 he was appointed President of the Commission for the establishment of the [[Catholic University of Croatia]], and still today, after the University opening in 2006, continues as the President of the Commission of the University. In April 2005 he was elected associate professor in the Department of the liturgy of Zagreb Catholic Theological Faculty. He is member of the editorial board of the scientific journal ''Bogoslovska smotra''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbk.hr/?type=diocesan&ID=5 |title=HBK - Hrvatska biskupska konferencija |website=Hbk.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref> In October 2005, \u0160a\u0161ko participated in the IX Regular General Synod of Bishops in the [[Holy See|Vatican]], in a group of Assistants to the Special Secretary of the Synod. During three pastoral visits of [[Pope John Paul II]] to Croatia, he was one of those responsible for the preparation of liturgical celebrations.\n\nOn 11 February 2008, [[Pope Benedict XVI]] appointed \u0160a\u0161ko auxiliary bishop of Zagreb and titular Bishop of Rotary. Cardinal [[Josip Bozani\u0107]] ordained him on 29 March 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glas-koncila.hr/?conID=6316 |title=Doga\u0111anja &#124; Zare\u0111en zagreba\u010dki pomo\u0107ni biskup Ivan \u0160a\u0161ko &#124; Portal Glasa Koncila |website=Glas-koncila.hr |date=2008-03-29 |accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sasko, Ivan}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic bishops in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Croatian theologians]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Mudroslov", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivan_%C5%A0a%C5%A1ko"}
